title_clean: Acer AL2216Wbd 22" LCD Monitor - Black
description_clean: Add more screen real estate to your computer's desktop with the 22-inch Acer AL2216Wbd LCD monitor, which features an elegantly sophisticated, stylish black casing. But more than just a monitor for your desktop or laptop PC, the AL2216Wbd is also an excellent choice for gamers with its blazing fast 5ms (millisecond) response time. It also offers a high level of brightness with a 300 cd/m2 rating and a 700:1 contrast ratio. Other features include a 1680 x 1050-pixel resolution, dual DVI and VGA inputs, VESA compatibility for wall mounting, and user friendly controls on the front.The monitor's 5ms response time is essential for hard-core gamers, and it's also great for watching high-intensity action movies with fast movement. It offers a high level of brightness with a 300 cd/m2 (candela per square meter) rating and a 700:1 contrast ratio. (The higher the contrast ratio, the greater a monitor's ability to display subtle color details and not get washed out by ambient room light.) The screen also has a 170-degree horizontal and 160-degree vertical viewing angle.The AL2216Wbd has a 22-inch screen (measured diagonally) that is framed by a thin, black bezel. The screen housing measures 20.2 inches wide by 16 inches tall. It sits upon a flat stand that measures 7.8 inches deep. Get just the right view with forward and backward tilting. The spare back includes just a power connector and the two video inputs: analog VGA and digital DVI with HDCP, which enables you to hook this monitor up to a cable or satellite set-top box for watching your favorite TV programs. It also supports Kensington locks for added security.What's in the BoxLCD monitor, power cable, VGA/D-Sub cable, DVI cable, printed user guideTech TalkHDCP-- High-Bandwidth Digital Content Protection (HDCP) is a form of copy protection technology designed to prevent transmission of non-encrypted high-definition content as it travels across DVI or HDMI digital connections.Response Time-- The amount of time it takes for a liquid crystal cell to from active (black) to inactive (white) and back against to active (black). It's measured in milliseconds (ms), and the lower the number the faster the response time--translating to a smoother picture with fewer pixilated or ghosted artifacts.

reviewText: I have used similar antennae before with good results.  We live south of St. Louis so the directionality of these "Christmas tree" antennae works fine.  We also don't live in a valley.  Picks up all the local channels with super easy setup.  I've used a similar, unamplified, one without the rabbit ears that gave just as good of performance but could not find that Phillips model any longer.  This antenna is a great place to start and it may be all you'll ever need.

reviewText: This protector has a thin strip of sticky foam tape that adheres it to the edges of the LCD, this leaves an air gap between the LCD and the protector, which is okay. Unfortunately, the strip does not go all the way around; it has gaps near the bottom corners so dust and lint get between the protector and the screen. Then it's hard to see the screen. Then you take it off and lose fifteen dollars. Then you have to spend another ten dollars on a traditional screen protector. I suggest you skip this protector unless you are okay with taking it off and cleaning it occasionally, but who knows how many times you can do that before the adhesive wears out? Alternatively, if you are willing to buy (or already have) some thin double sided foam tape, you can fill in the areas that Sony missed. I guess the success of that hack would depend on the thickness of your tape and your cutting skills... good luck either way. And no, I have not actually bought another type of protector for my NEX-5, it's going unprotected until I stop smarting from buying this one!
summary: Protects screen, but it get's very dusty, then you can't see it. : (

reviewText: I have been testing this mouse for everyday use. I mainly use Internet Explorer, Outlook, Word, Excel, Adobe Photoshop and Visual Studio.The ON-OFF button on the back is a BIG PLUS. It should save battery - only if you remember to switch it off... (I am not sure if it is automatically off when not in use)The middle area is the touch-sensitive surface for scrolling up and down. It follows the way you flick/touch it - fast to scroll fast in a long page, or flick it slower to move slower. It takes a while to get used to.The left and right buttons are pretty basic.Compared toMicrosoft Touch Mouse, this is better. Microsoft touch mouse is too big.I rate 4 star because this mouse is heavy and it requires 2 AA batteries. Other regular mice I have require only 1 AA battery.

reviewText: I was particularly interested in reviewing this because my travel laptop accepts only thin drives and was nearing the limit of its 320GB capacity.My hard drives are loaded with applications and I am not very fastidious about removing all the startup garbage they install - so this drive had become a very slow booter: just over nine (9) minutes. No, I am not joking: just over nine (9) minutes running Windows 7 Ultimate on an Intel Core i7.Of course that was then. Having installed the Seagate Solid State Hybrid Drive and giving it the opportunity to "learn" what is on my system through repeated boot-ups, my boot-up time is now just over three (3) minutes.I've checked it more than a dozen times because I simply didn't believe it. But boot-up time has now stabilized at about 3 minutes 10 seconds.The Seagate unit replaced a Hitachi 320GB 7200RPM drive, so there doesn't appear to be much difference in the launch time of applications, other than the two that launch when Windows starts.Installation was the same as with any hard drive: I cloned the original hard drive to the Seagate, installed it in the computer and then rebooted several times in order to allow the Seagate to "learn" the boot process.As I said, my boot time went from nine minutes to three. No kidding. At this point, I don't think things will improve unless I start getting rid of the abundance of startup programs on this computer, which I should do in any event.If there were a 1TB Hybrid unit like this that spun at 7200RPM, I'd buy it in a flash.As it is, the Seagate Laptop Thin 500 GB Solid State Hybrid Drive is a very, very impressive performer.Jerry

reviewText: I picked up 2 of these for xmas gifts when the price recently dropped. I have owned 2 of the previous models of netbooks from Acer. Here's my breakdown:Pro's:Full Windows 7, runs like a champ. Very smooth setup.The 11.6 screen is the sweet spot! Res is much higher than previous netbooks (1440x768?) and watching videos on the 11.6 is great!It still feels like a netbook, nice and small.All the features you need, multiple USB ports, bluetooth, WifiN, card reader slot, etc.New power adapter is smaller & more streamlined that previous models - this is also a nice thing to see (smaller adapters.)Trackpad is improved and larger. Yay! Previous models' trackpads were small and often hard to use.The battery is a little more streamlined than previous models (if you had the extended battery).Con's:The keyboard is a little spongy (it flexes down when you type on it a lot).It came with a TON of bloatware. Be prepared to spend an hour just deleting all the crap. I mean, seriously Acer??It was pretty poky until I installed the 4gb memory (it comes with a 2gb). So be prepared to spend a little extra on more memory. It's very well worth it. I spent $25 I think.It's still largely a "one task at a time" computer but when the larger screen you don't feel so cramped.Highly recommended if you catch at a good price.

reviewText: This 6 foot Micra Digital USB A to USB Mini-5pin cable is very handy to have if you've lost a cable for a phone, bluetooth speaker or back-up hard drive that uses this size. Sometimes, back up drives or gadgets come with very short cords (I have one that's about 2 inches for the cord part.) and you just want a more convenient size. This cable works just fine and is a tiny fraction of the cost you'd pay at one of the big box electronics stores for this type of cable. Micra Digital also sells a similar cable in a 3 foot size if that is a better fit for you. Belkin Micra Digital USB A to USB Mini-5pin Cable (3ft). I also find it handy to keep a back-up cable in my car along with a USB cigarette lighter charger similar to this 2 Port USB Car Cigarette Lighter Adapter Dual Plug for iPod MP3 Players Charger - Color White just in case I need it while away from home.Note that this cable isn't the right size for a Kindle Fire. They use a Micro-USB connector.
summary: Handy cable at a great price

reviewText: I've owned several Olympus digital cameras over the years (E-1, E-330, E-3, E-PL1, and now the E-P3) and the E-P3 is by far be best Olympus digital camera to date. Not only is this camera extremely compact while still using the same DSLR-size image sensor found in Olympus DSLRs, but the new auto focus system inside this camera makes it one of the fastest focusing cameras on the market (depending on the lens you're using).The 14-42mm R II kit zoom lens focuses extremely fast and is good enough for casual/vacation use but the real advantage of a camera like the E-P3 is the ability to use interchangeable lenses. My favorite lenses to use with this camera are the Olympus 17mm f/2.8 pancake lens, the Panasonic Leica 25mm f/1.4, and the Olympus 45mm f/1.8 lenses. I also have the 9-18mm zoom lens when I need to have a wide angle lens. I owned the Panasonic 20mm f/1.7 lens for a while but it focuses slowly compared to the 17mm and 25mm lenses.One feature that I didn't expect to use was the touchscreen display. I thought I'd just use the screen to compose my images like any other camera, but I discovered that it's really nice to be able to touch the screen EXACTLY where you want to focus and have the camera instantly take the picture.In any case, the durable metal construction, built-in image stabilization, built-in wireless flash control, and decent 3fps burst shooting mode make the E-P3 a solid DSLR replacement if you're looking for DSLR quality without the bulk. I also have several Sony NEX cameras and lenses and I can tell you that as of November 2011 the Olympus system has a MUCH better selection of lenses ... and that has more impact on image quality than the differences between the Olympus image sensors and the Sony image sensors.
summary: The Best Olympus Camera So Far

reviewText: My iTunes folder is approaching 800 GB, so I had been looking at 2TB drives for backup when the chance to try the Seagate FreeAgent GoFlex Desk 2 TB FireWire 800 USB 2.0 External Hard Drive for Mac STBC2000101 came along. I did have some previous experience with the GoFlex desktop product line; back in December, I had purchased a Seagate FreeAgent GoFlex Desk 2 TB USB 2.0 External Hard Drive STAC2000100 to hold my EyeTV archive.Unlike the first drive, this one was already formatted for Mac use, so the set-up was just a matter of plugging it in and powering it up. While my Mac Mini does have a FireWire 800 port, I still have devices that are Firewire 400. It's OK to mix FW 400 and FW 800, but the tradeoff is that the Firewire bus will be limited to the lower speed.I use Time Machine to back up everything except my iTunes folder to a Time Capsule. The sheer size of the iTunes folder (which is located on an external 1TB LaCie FW400 drive) makes it impractical to include it with the main backup. I had been backing up iTunes to a LaCie 1TB USB external drive, but that drive had started un-mounting itself for no apparent reason (and missing backup sessions) and was becoming too small to do a full backup and more than a few incremental additions.Apple has not done a serious update to Backup for years, so I decided to find something more up-to-date for use with the new drive. I settled on Get Backup 2. I installed the software and set up a job to back up the iTunes folder, about 760 GB at the time. This was an hours-long, overnight process which was interrupted about halfway through by a 3-hour power failure.  The next morning, I ran some diagnostics on the drive, found no problems, and restarted the backup from the beginning. The backup proceeded uninterrupted this time and was complete when I checked it the following morning. I then ran several smaller backup jobs to storage on this drive.The drive comes with some installable Seagate software that includes drivers and a simple management and diagnostic application. Conveniently for me, the drivers and app also work with the Seagate drive I purchased previously. The capacity LEDs on both drives interfaces are now accurate. The newer drive has been up and running now for about there weeks with no apparent issues or problemsOne thing I like about the GoFlex concept is that it separates the interface electronics from the hard drive itself. My experience in recent years is that drive failures are more likely to happen in the USB or FireWire interface than in the drive per se. Two or three years ago, I bought an external drive bay that allows me to plug in a bare IDE or SATA drive and interface to the computer via USB. In three out of three cases where an external drive appeared to have failed, I removed he "failed" drive from its external chassis, popped it into the external drive bay and found it was working and all data was intact. GoFlex makes it easier to determine if a problem in in the interface or in the drive itself (assuming you have at least two of them, drives or interfaces).Whenever I decide to replace my Mac Mini, it is certain that the new one will have Thunderbolt. Seagate already sells a Thunderbolt adapter for its portable drives, it's like a desktop adapter is not too far away.This is a newer design than the USB 2.0 drive I bought in December; it's a little smaller and a little more sleek and stealthy-looking than the earlier model.Sometime in the next few months, I'm going to be looking for a new 2 TB Firewire drive to hold my iTunes library; the Seagate FreeAgent GoFlex Desk 2 TB FireWire 800 USB 2.0 External Hard Drive for Mac STBC2000101 has jumped to the top of my list of candidates.

reviewText: I recently made the switch from iPhone 4 to iPhone 5, and have been struggling since because of the different cables used to power/sync with itunes (old iPhone was 30-pin). Not only that, but all the speakers, docking stations and peripherals I own for my old iPhone have been rendered useless for my new phone.One of those devices is aPhilips DC390/37 Dual-Docking 30-Pin iPod/iPhone/iPad Alarm Clock Speaker Dock, which is the one I miss the most as not only charged my device and played music, but also served as my everyday alarm clock. When I saw this iHome charging stereo it seemed like my problems were over as it offered pretty much the same I had with my Philips alarm clock. Only that it doesn't.The device is beautifully looking, seriously. The silver line at the bottom and the black matte finish make it look elegant, buttons are discreet and do not raw attention to them, it does not take much space and overall represented an improvement over my old speaker. But then I tried to use it.If you, like me, care about your phone enough to have it in a protective case, let me tell you this charging stereo is not for you, unless you are willing to remove your iPhone from its case every time you need to charge it, listen to music or use the alarm. The lightning dock was designed to be used with the bare phone, whatever space your case takes between the phone and the dock will prevent it from effectively connecting. The alternative is to use the USB slot in the back of the device, but that beats the purpose of having a lightning dock.So, can it be used with devices other than iPhones/iPods? Well, the iHome also lacks an AUX input, so no, this was obviously designed to be used with iPhone 5 in the base and other Apple devices via the USB slot included.It is probably the high expectations I had when I ordered this that made me feel extremely disappointed, but the fact remains that the design is flawed in the sense that they never considered a person would have their iPhone in a protective case when using this.
summary: If you, like me, care about your phone enough to have it in a protective case, this is not for you

reviewText: The Canon EF-S 55-250mm is a perfect choice if you shoot mostly wide angle shots and don't want to blow a ton of money on a telephoto zoom lens that you only use occasionally. This lens offers you reasonably sharp photos at a very, very good price. Here's a more indepth evaluation of this lens.- SharpnessThe sharpness is on par with that of the 18-55mm kit lens. In the right conditions, it's almost (but not quite) pro-grade. For a budget lens, it's really about as sharp as they come. I think it's safe to say in terms of sharpness this lens will satisfy all but the most fastidious of prosumers.You best bet for seeing how sharp this lens is is to seek out professional review sites that show you a 100% crop of pictures taken with this lens and then decide for yourself.- Chromatic Aberration (CA)In bright sunlight, where chromatic aberration is most pronounced, the chromatic aberration on this lens is barely noticeable and probably imperceptible to the untrained eye. In more even lighting, this lens shows no signs of CA.- Auto-Focus (AF)The auto-focus is fast enough for still subjects, but for very fast-moving subjects, it's a hit-or-miss. I gave this lens a good workout shooting cheetahs running close to their top speeds at the Animal Ark, Reno, NV (OT: cheetahs can run at speeds of 70 mph or greater). Most of my shots came out blurry (and that's not due to motion blur) because the auto-focus wasn't fast enough.Like the kit lens, the auto-focus has trouble in lowlight conditions. It also has trouble with surfaces that lack texture. The motor whirs back and forth trying to lock on to a focus. It can be a little annoying at times.- Image Stabilization (IS)The image stabilization is amazing, even at 250mm. Interestingly, you can hear a click when the image stabilization mechanism kicks in. For handheld shot, especially at the 250mm end, the IS is immensely helpful for steadying your shots. I'm very impressed. (Bear in mind, too, the rule of thumb: the shutter speed should be at least as fast as the reciprocal of the focal length.)- Internal Focus (IF)The lack of IF would not ordinarily be a problem unless you're using circular polarized filters. The turning of the barrel throws the filter out of adjustment, so you would have to readjust the filter after the subject is brought into focus.- BuildIn terns of build quality, the lens is built a lot like the kit lens. There are complaints that it looks plasticky - maybe so - but it doesn't look cheap to be sure. It's lightweight but it feels well-built and sturdy. The zoom ring feels tight, but not overly so, so there is no zoom creep.- AlternativeJust FYI, theCanon EF 70-300mmis reputed to be sharper than this lens. You might want to give this lens some consideration if the focal range is right and if you can afford to splurge a little.---I suspect the Canon EF-S 55-250mm is the best mid-telephoto zoom lens you can get at this price. For the budget conscious, and for people who need telephoto zoom only once in a while, this lens is a very good choice.

title_clean: Canon EF-S 55-250mm f/4.0-5.6 IS II Telephoto Zoom Lens for Canon Digital SLR Cameras
description_clean: Incorporating Canon's Optical Image Stabilizer technology, this Canon 55-250mm telephoto zoom lens captures long distance, low-light shots far better than many comparable lenses, helping you photograph the far-off action of athletes or zoom in for an intimate portrait with a blurred background. The high-zoom-ratio lens is equivalent to a focal length of 88-400mm in the 35mm format (when used on Canon EOS cameras compatible with EF-S lenses). More significantly, the image stabilizer effect creates an equivalent shutter speed of roughly four stops faster than the same size lens without an image stabilizer. In other words, if the slowest shutter speed you can hold a 250mm lens steadily is normally 1/250th of a second, this Canon lens will let you hand-hold shutter speeds as slow as 1/15th of a second. The lens also boasts a UD-glass lens element to correct chromatic aberration to create excellent image quality throughout the zoom range. Delivering an excellent performance at an affordable price for all photographers, the 55-250mm lens carries a one-year warranty.SpecificationsFocal length: 55-250mmMaximum aperture: f/4 to f/5.6Lens construction: 12 elements in 10 groups, including one UD-glass elementDiagonal angle of view: 27 degrees (at 50 feet) to 6 degrees (at 15 feet), with APS-C image sensorsFocus adjustment: DC motor, gear-driven (front focusing design)Closest focusing distance: 3.6 feet (0.31x maximum close-up magnification)Filter size: 58mmDimensions: 2.8 inches in diameter and 4.3 inches longWeight: 13.8 ouncesWarranty: 1 yearThis telephoto zoom lens is designed with Canon's Optical Image Stabilizer technology while retaining compactness and lightness, in response to demands of photographers. This high zoom ratio lens is equivalent to a focal length of 88-400mm in the 35mm format (when used on Canon EOS cameras compatible with EF-S lenses), and the image stabilizer effect equivalent to a shutter speed about 4 stops faster than the same size lens without Image Stabilizer. In other words, if the slowest shutter speed you could formerly hold a 250mm lens steadily was 1/250th of a second, with Canon's 4-stop stabilization correction, you could hand-hold at shutter speeds as slow as 1/15th of a second. It also uses a UD-glass lens element to correct chromatic aberration for excellent image quality throughout the zoom range. This new EF-S telephoto lens with great features delivers excellent performance at an affordable price for all photographers.

reviewText: I want to start out by saying that if saving a hundred bucks is a big deal for you, get this camera over the t3i. I am COMPLETELY happy with its camera features. It also takes stunning video.I got this camera to make room in my bag so I didn't have to have a quality camcorder as well as a digital camera. The quality of the camera and the images/movies is fantastic if you know how to manipulate the features.However, I do a lot of video blogging and self-shooting. I never realized how much I would wish for the articulating LCD screen on the t3i. If I had a team to film my stuff, it'd be different. But I just have me! To solve this, I've connected my camera to my computer to use as a monitor. THIS WORKS FINE! But It'd be one less step to have an articulating viewscreen.
summary: AMAZING CAMERA! I still might suggest the T3i though

title_clean: Canon EOS Rebel T2i DSLR Camera with EF-S 18-55mm f/3.5-5.6 IS Lens (OLD MODEL)
description_clean: The new flagship of the EOS Rebel line, Canon EOS Rebel T2i brings professional EOS features into an easy to use, lightweight digital SLR that's a joy to use. Featuring a class-leading 18.0-megapixel CMOS image sensor and increased light sensitivity for low light photography, the EOS Rebel T2i also has an advanced HD Movie mode for gorgeous Full HD movies. Able to capture up to 3.7 frames per second, it's ready to go the minute it's picked up. Advanced Live View, a new wide-area screen, plus features like Canon's brilliant Auto Lighting Optimizer and Highlight Tone features ensure brilliant photos and movies, easily. With some of the most advanced features of any digital SLR, it's simply the best Rebel Canon has ever created.EOS Rebel T2i Highlights18.0-megapixel CMOS (APS-C) sensor and DIGIC 4 Image ProcessorThe EOS Rebel T2i has an 18.0-megapixel CMOS sensor that captures images with exceptional clarity and tonal range and offers more than enough resolution for big enlargements or crops. This first-class sensor features many of the same new technologies as used by professional Canon cameras to maximize each pixel's light-gathering efficiency. Its APS-C size sensor creates an effective 1.6x field of view (compared to 35mm format).DIGIC 4 Image ProcessorThe Canon DIGIC 4 Image Processor dramatically speeds up the entire EOS Rebel T2i's camera operations for intuitive operation and offers improvements in both fine detail and natural color reproduction. It works in concert with the EOS Rebel T2i's CMOS Image Sensor to achieve phenomenal levels of performance in nearly any situation.Capture stunning shots in low light.ISO 100-6400 (expandable to 12800) for shooting from bright to dim lightThe EOS Rebel T2i features an expanded ISO range that makes shooting possible in situations previously unthinkable without flash. With an ISO rating up to 6400 (expandable to ISO 12800), along with the DIGIC 4 Image Processor's improved noise-reduction technology, creative possibilities abound. Combine the EOS Rebel T2i with one of Canon's EF or EF-S lenses with Optical Image Stabilizer and the shooting possibilities for both movies and stills expand even further.Improved EOS Movie mode with manual exposure controlDesigned for the evolving, tech-savvy user, the EOS Rebel T2i features HD Video capture technologies--manual exposure control for more creative control, for example--borrowed directly from professional Canon SLRs to capture stellar video with all the benefits of shooting with an SLR. By shooting video with the EOS Rebel T2i, photographers as well as filmmakers can take advantage of the creative features native to SLR cameras. Along with its manual controls, the EOS Rebel T2i allows for full use of Canon EF and EF-S lenses, including Macro and Fisheye, providing a plethora of shooting options once reserved only for still photography. The resulting HD video is a standout in its beautiful depth-of-field characteristics and remarkable capture capability under poor lighting conditions. In a first for EOS cameras, a Movie Crop function is included: An SD-quality movie (640 x 480) can be cropped to the equivalent of about 7x magnification of regular shooting.Video can be captured at a number of resolutions and frame rates for numerous applications. It can capture 1920 x 1080 Full HD video at frame rates of 24 (23.976), 25 or 30 (29.97) frames per second, for up to 4GB per clip. Movies are saved as MOV files and can be viewed in Full HD through the EOS Rebel T2i's HDMI output. Other recording sizes include HD at 1280 x 720 (50/60 (59.94) fps) or SD/VGA at 640 x 480 (50/60 (59.94) fps). The EOS Rebel T2i has a built-in microphone for simple mono recording and stereo sound can be recorded through a self-powered external microphone.Enhanced 63-zone, Dual-layer metering system, and 9-point AF systemThe EOS Rebel T2i features Canon's newest Dual-layer sensor, with 63-zones. By measuring not only the amount of light, but also taking into account color and luminosity, this new system delivers a very high level of accuracy for better results every time. Since the metering sensor has a color measurement function, exposure errors and focus errors caused by different light sources are minimized; the EOS Rebel T2i gives stable exposure from shot to shot in situations where light changes, such as sports on a cloudy day, or indoor holiday scenes.Additionally, the EOS Rebel T2i has a high-precision, 9-point AF system utilizing a high-precision, f/2.8 cross-type center point. The 9-point AF system uses both normal and high-precision focus depending on the aperture and available light. The 9 focus points can be chosen automatically or manually selected.Wide 3.0-inch (3:2 aspect ratio) Clear View LCD monitorThe EOS Rebel T2i has a high-resolution 3.0-inch Clear View LCD monitor that features 1.04 million dots/VGA for spectacular detail. It also has the same aspect ratio (3:2) as the camera's sensor, making for clear and easy Live View composition. An anti-reflective and water-repellant coating provides a clearer and more smudge-resistant surface and screen brightness can be adjusted in 7 steps in accordance with ambient light.New Quick Control Screen buttonThe EOS Rebel T2i's refined button layout includes a dedicated button that directs the camera immediately to the Quick Control screen, where it's simple to navigate among any number of settings, including ISO, Exposure and Flash Exposure compensation, drive mode, white balance, image quality and much, much more.Improved layout with dedicated Live View/Movie shooting buttonWithout the need to navigate through a bunch of menus, the EOS Rebel T2i transitions effortlessly between still and movie mode. By pressing the Live View/Movie button, a situation that had required menu access with other cameras, still images can change to a movie shoot and vice versa. It's literally as simple as the press of a button.3.7fps continuous shooting up to approximately 34 JPEGs or approximately 6 RAWThe EOS Rebel T2i can shoot up to 3.7 frames per second (fps) for up to approximately 6 consecutive RAW files or approximately 34 full-resolution JPEGs. Shooting at speeds of up to 1/4000 sec., the EOS Rebel T2i can capture even rapidly-unfolding scenes with ease.New compatibility with SDXC memory cardsThe EOS Rebel T2i is compatible with both SDXC memory cards for greater storage capacity and with Eye-Fi SD cards, which are outfitted with a Wi-Fi transmitter (IEEE 802.11b/g) and internal antenna for wireless, high speed transfer of images. With an Eye-Fi card installed, the EOS Rebel T2i can display the Eye-Fi's connection status and error notes with ease, for fully functional wireless uploading of images directly from the camera.*Canon cameras are not guaranteed to support Eye-Fi card functions, including wireless transfer. In case of an issue with the Eye-Fi card, please consult with the card manufacturer. The use of Eye-Fi cards may not be available outside the United States and Canada, please contact the card manufacturer for territory availability.Compatible with the full line of Canon EF and EF-S lensesEF LensesThe EOS Rebel T2i is compatible with all Canon lenses in the EF lineup, including compact and lightweight EF-S lenses, ranging from ultra-wide angle to super telephoto lenses. Canon lenses employ advanced optical expertise and micron-precision engineering to deliver outstanding performance and deliver beautiful results. Special technologies like the Canon Image Stabilizer technology in select lenses helps to minimize the effect of camera shake, effectively adding up to four stops of light. With a dizzying array of lenses perfect for travel, sports, still life and everything in between, photographers can truly maximize the quality and performance of their EOS Rebel T2i with superlative Canon optics.SoftwareCanon EOS Digital Solution Disk (Version 22.0)The EOS Rebel T2i comes bundled with a Canon EOS Digital Solution Disk, which features powerful software programs designed to extend the EOS experience to the computer. These include Canon's EOS Utility (Version 2.8.0), Digital Photo Professional (Version 3.8.0), ZoomBrowser EX for Windows (Version 6.5.0), ImageBrowser for Macintosh OS X (Version 6.5.0), the Picture Style Editor (Version 1.7.0), MovieEdit Task (Win/Mac, Version 3.4.1) PhotoStitch (Windows Version 3.1.22/Mac Version 3.2.4), Memory Card Utility (Windows Version 1.3.0/Mac Version 1.2.3), WFT Utility (Win/Mac, Version 3.5.1), and Original Data Security Tools 1.8.0 (Win). Each application is designed to perfect the captured images and streamline the digital workflow.Compatible Operating SystemWindows: Windows XP SP2 or SP3 / Windows Vista (all version except the Starter Edition) / Windows 7 32-bit and 64-bit versions. Macintosh: OS X 10.4 to 10.5EOS Utility (Version 2.8.0)for Macintosh or Windows handles the connection between the camera and computer whenever they're connected via USB. It allows remote controlled shooting from the computer, handles downloading of images from the camera to the computer, and allows seamless linking to either Canon's ZoomBrowser EX/ImageBrowser or Digital Photo Professional software once images have been copied to the hard drive. Furthermore, it's used to upload settings back into a USB-connected camera.Digital Photo Professional (Win/Mac, Version 3.8.0)is an image processing program that enables high-speed RAW image processing, high-speed previewing for real-time image adjustment and support for sRGB, Adobe RGB and Wide Gamut RGB color spaces. Because it's CMS (Color Management System) compatible, Digital Photo Professional allows for easy image layout and printing in Adobe RGB in conjunction with Easy-PhotoPrint and PictBridge printers. It also features the Dust Delete Data Detection tool for cleaner images.Picture Style Editor (Win/Mac, Version 1.7.0)Canon's Picture Style Editor enables you to create custom Picture Style profiles that can be used to customize the appearance of JPEG and RAW images captured with EOS Digital SLR cameras. Picture Style files created with Picture Style Editor can be loaded into the EOS cameras that support Picture Style and may also be used when processing RAW images in Canon software applications Digital Photo Professional, ZoomBrowser EX (for Windows) and ImageBrowser (for Mac).ZoomBrowser EX (Version 6.5.0)for Windows and ImageBrowser (Version 6.5.0) for Mac OS X are the easy, user-friendly options for viewing and editing of JPEG and even RAW image files. Both allow viewing of numerous types of images including finished TIFF and BMP files. Both also have a variety of search options for finding images, allow re-naming of single images or batches of files, and offer a variety of options for printing without using a separate image-editing program.What's in the BoxEOS Rebel T2i BodyEF-S 18-55mm f/3.5-5.6 IS LensEyecup Ef (Not shown)Wide Strap EW-100DBIIIUSB Interface Cable IFC-130UAV Cable AVC-DC400STBattery Pack LP-E8Battery Charger LC-E8EOS Digital Solution Disk and Instruction Manuals"Great Photography is Easy" Booklet and "Do More with Macro" Booklet (not shown)

Picture Style files created with Picture Style Editor can be loaded into the EOS cameras that support Picture Style and may also be used when processing RAW images in Canon software applications Digital Photo Professional, ZoomBrowser EX (for Windows) and ImageBrowser (for Mac).ZoomBrowser EX (Version 6.5.0)for Windows and ImageBrowser (Version 6.5.0) for Mac OS X are the easy, user-friendly options for viewing and editing of JPEG and even RAW image files. Both allow viewing of numerous types of images including finished TIFF and BMP files. Both also have a variety of search options for finding images, allow re-naming of single images or batches of files, and offer a variety of options for printing without using a separate image-editing program.What's in the BoxEOS Rebel T2i BodyEF-S 18-55mm f/3.5-5.6 IS LensEyecup Ef (Not shown)Wide Strap EW-100DBIIIUSB Interface Cable IFC-130UAV Cable AVC-DC400STBattery Pack LP-E8Battery Charger LC-E8EOS Digital Solution Disk and Instruction Manuals"Great Photography is Easy" Booklet and "Do More with Macro" Booklet (not shown)

reviewText: I already have 1 Crucial M4 256GB SSD. Saw a good offer US$159.99, could not resist it and order one. I intend to put them into Raid 0 to speed up the already fast performance.My system:Intel Z75 chipset16GB 1600MHz RAMIntel i-3770 CPUCrucial M4 256GB SSD x 2 RAID 0 using Intel RST latest as of 13 Jan 2013GTX 660 1.5GB GPUMake sure both SSD are connected to SATA 0 and 1 for 6Gbps transfer rate each.1) Go to bios change setting to RAID and shut down.2) Connect both ssd to sata 0 and 1 port, existing 2TB HDD to sata 3.3) Boot up using 2TB HDD to windows 8 and install intel RST, raid the two ssd to raid 0, 128KB stripe (other stripes are space efficient but lower performance, tested many times)4) Use Macrium Reflect free edition to clone windows 8 into the raid 0 volume. You may have to leave out the recovery partition as the software will claim insufficient space. Clone took 2h 6 min.5) Shut down, remove 2TB HDD from system and boot up again.6) Enter windows 8 smoothly, system may need to update and tune for ssd, reboot a few times and it will be working perfect.7) Download any benchmark to test ssd speed and you can easily get reading speeds of 1 to 1.2 GBytes per second! Writing is around 550 to 600 Mbytes per second.Read speed is more important for most applications, especially gaming. Boot up windows less than 15 s, shut down less than 5s.Remember to backup essential stuff before raiding the ssds. Do all these at your own risk.After using for sometime, no event crop up. Crucial is known for their reliability. They cater more towards reading speed and reasonable write speed. For real world applications, they shine.
summary: EXTREME FAST FOR RAID 0 FOR WINDOWS 8

reviewText: I am not new to the Solid State Drive, and was running an updated 128GB solid state drive in my Windows 7 laptop until I got tired of not having much storage space on the drive. So, when I saw this hybrid drive I thought it was worth a shot to see how quick it was. I got the 500GB version, so I increased by storage by about 4x. This drive is not as quick as my Solid State drive. My old boot time was about 12 seconds, where as this hybrid drive takes about 30-45 seconds. However I do find that the applications open very quickly (Firefox, thunderbird in 2-3 seconds, Photoshop in about 7 seconds). Maybe not as fast as under the SSD, but pretty close. So, my decision has been to keep this 500GB hybrid drive instead of going back to my smaller Solid State Drive. For now this drive is a great value until the pricing drops substantially on solid state drives.
summary: Great Value - Great Choice Until SSD Prices Drop

reviewText: UPDATE: After hearing some other Bluetooth speakers, we've come to realize the SOLEMATE MINI probably has the best sound quality in the miniature speaker class, and better than some larger speakers. Also, after pairing with multiple sources, we noticed that the Bluetooth pairing process was truly brainless. So I'm updating my rating from four to five stars. That annoying voice isn't really that annoying, and he doesn't come on that often.ORIGINAL REVIEW:The most important issue with a speaker is sound quality. In the MINI bluetooth speaker class, this unit has Very Good sound. Five stars. If you need party volume, don't buy a mini speaker.Build quality/survivability is also Very Good. Five stars.But the darn thing is haunted. There's a voice that comes on with instructions. I don't like my gadgets talking to me unless I ask. I wanted to deduct a star for this, but the voice is only for special circumstances, so this review ALMOST stayed at five stars...Until we used it for a while and noticed that you cannot adjust the sound level until a music source is connected and playing. If you have a teenager, she will play the volume at maximum. When you next use it, the volume is still at maximum. It does not turn down by itself when you re-pair it to a new device, nor does it give you the ability turn down the volume without a source connected. You will be blasted unless you remember to turn down your source first. Turning down the volume when switching to an external input is a well known user interface practice, and even a safety issue. Minus one star.Summary: Very good product, recommended. Be prepared to be blasted if you have a teenager.
summary: UPDATED: Very Good Sound for a Mini Speaker, but haunted with the WORLDS MOST ANNOYING VOICE!

reviewText: I tested out four pair of earphones in the last year, including the set that came with my iPhone. Out of all the earphones I've used, The Ultimate Ears Noise-Isolating Earphones are among the best for a under $100. I find the sound quality very good, and because the earphones come with various sizes of soft silicone ear cushions, the earphones are pretty comfortable in my ears. They are not as comfortable as the iPhone earphones, but the noise-blocking or noise-isolation feature is much better than Apple`s earphones.There are two problems, however, that I have with these earphones. While it includes a case for the earplugs, I think it would have been better to design a case in which you can wrap the cable around for travel. There is also no remote volume control for the unit, which is a big let downer for me.Other than that, though, I think the Ultimate Ears 500 will be very useful in relatively noisy situations. And as the price of earphones go, these are pretty affordable.

reviewText: This device does just about anything you would want out of a GPS unit..it is BASIC and does not have a lot of the bell's and whistles that the more expensive units do.  However, for the cost, it is a 5 STAR product.  Simply put..it gives you voice guided navigation with traffic and allows for you to update the maps and software of the device from the internet.  This is where the fun starts...usually most of these types of devices have problems running on the MAC platform...and in the past I have run into such issues.  The TOM TOM was the first device that had MAC software that WORKED and worked flawlessly.  I was able to setup the device, run the software, and do a full firmware/map update in minutes....naturally you will want to make sure you have broadband so it can download the files it needs.Tom Tom is also one of the few out there that lets you download different voices for your device...really FUN...it includes a few but you can purchase more as you see the need to make the experience like nothing else out there.Pros:Price, functionality, design, software.Cons: None for me.5/5 for me considering a BASIC easy to use GPS system that has traffic and the lovely interchangeable voices.
summary: Excellent value, great GPS, and MAC friendly too...

reviewText: Because in my non-scientific real world comparison of the Sanyo 2000mAh Eneloops and Duracell pre-charged 2400mAh rated AA batteries in a Pentax X-5 hybrid camera, the Duracell batteries were a competitive underperformer. I bought the Duracells locally because I couldn’t wait the two days for Prime delivery of the Eneloops. I wouldn’t call it a mistake but in the long run the Duracells are not likely to be as efficient or cost effective.Over a two week period, I alternated sets daily and in every instance while the Duracell batteries could meet the demands of 100 to 150 shots per day, in terms of charge depletion as indicated by the camera, the Eneloops maintained about a 25% more capacity in each instance.  I know there are sources out there that contend the Japanese manufactured Duracells are actually rebranded eneloops (the set I have also reflects Japanese manufacture) but if that is the case, the Duracells I purchased must have been the Sanyo rejects. Both sets take nearly hours to recharge (at about 75% battery depletion) with the Sanyo NiMh charger. Depleted batteries must be charged in pairs.I’ll continue to use the Duracells because as noted they are adequate (and I paid for them) but the reality is they will be relegated, eventually, to the emergency back-up set.
summary: Hopefully I’ve learned my lesson about impatience

Depleted batteries must be charged in pairs.I’ll continue to use the Duracells because as noted they are adequate (and I paid for them) but the reality is they will be relegated, eventually, to the emergency back-up set.
summary_clean: Hopefully I’ve learned my lesson about impatience

reviewText: Size: approximately 2 1/2" X 3 1/2", and about an inch wide, this case will accomodate only the small and thin digital cameras (or a cell phone). The camera case has a great finish to the leather and a very nice sueded inner lining -- all of this reminding me of the older types of European camera cases.The long front flap is secured by a strong magnetic fastener, giving great frontal protection to the camera -- and is easy to open and close with one hand.The belt loop in the back is a bit stiff, but will soften with usage. The stiffness however works against its security when the velcro belt loop fastener is adjusted -- however, if your belt is thin, and you make sure that hook velcro is contacting all of its opposing loop velcro, the staying power should be sufficient.The inner card holder, however -- is only able to hold one card, which for some may be quite enough.Altogether, this case is flat, unobtrusive, attractive and very functional -- a pleasant way to carry a thin digital camera in style.

reviewText: It's an okay product, based on the hour or so I spent experimenting with it. As others have noted the feel of the plastic is sort of "cheap" in some hard to describe way - it's built solidly enough, it just has some "off" sort of hollow tactile quality to it, akin to the feel of a plastic sunshade when removed from the lens. But it's pretty minor, I wouldn't even notice it after using it a while.What I didn't like was that time lapses are inexplicably limited to 99 frames. I've been looking at this product off and on for three months, and until checked before writing this review did NOT see that fact listed (it is, I should have seen it). Since that number of frames limits time lapse clips to 3-4 seconds at 24-30fps, it is so restrictive that it renders the function useless, at least for my interests.The function (non-shutter) buttons were very difficult for me to push. I have large hands, but I don't think that's the only reason - each is recessed in a dimple, and has to be pushed further than I was able to do without careful application of the corner of a fingernail. Such buttons would be fine for setting date and time on a clock, but not for functions requiring frequent adjustments - they need to be larger or have a shorter travel distance. This only compounds the frustration one experiences with trying to experiment with the function settings while deciphering the instructions. It took me nearly ten minutes just to get the internal clock set. One then has to cycle through all the functions in the unit to set up a time lapse shot, and the settings are not stored when the unit is powered off (meaning the settings have to be painstakingly and frustratingly set again each time).PROS: stores removed battery cover, pretty stout internal mechanisms for battery and AA-clip retention and release, pretty simple to install, fits the camera body tightly and neatly, changed grip of camera as a whole feels natural right off, inexpensive.CONS: limitation of time lapse function to a useless (for me) 99 frames, nearly indecipherable instructions, difficult to access main buttons, poorly laid out and non-intuitive user interface in function access (too many buttons to push, too many settings to cycle through), vaguely "plasticky" tactile quality, dials feel clunky (but may just need some use to smooth out), need to manually turn the unit on and off (why can't this be linked to the body's power switch?).
summary: Note the 99-Frames Limitation on Time Lapses

reviewText: Two great things about the Squeezebox Radio:1. A very broad range of commercial radio stations all over the US, not just wannabees. The buttons for presets make it easy to switch stations.2. Excellent, robust networking. After a power outage my printer and computers needed to be re-added to the wireless router, re-entering WEP passcodes and restarting. All I had to do with the Squeezebox was turn it back on and it was working.The user interface is pretty easy to use, though what you need to do isn't always obvious. Haven't added Sirius yet, but I might. I will definitely get the battery.It's not perfect. Added playlists in iTunes can take a long time to show up as options in the menu structure, which is a bit clumsy. Having to hit the play buttone after turning the radio on seems odd. Annoying enough to give it just 4 of 5 stars, but I do love this thing.

Crucial is a top notch manufacturer and their products just work.

reviewText: The first failed on second use and was, as always, replaced by Amazon without question :)That replacement failed after about 14 months. It was only being used in my netbook as additional storage - and so was not subjected to the wear and tear of removal and insertion. Nor does my netbook have heavy use (being only used on vacation) It went in, and remained there until failure - which only amounted to about 5 weeks of actual use.During that time period I had bought another of these Transcend 16 GB Class 6 SDHC cards to use in a camera. As I use a card reader to transfer images to the computer this SD card was removed and reinserted several times a month. It failed after about 8 months.In January of this year I had bought another of these, and it failed last month - 5 months of light use in a different digital SLR.I have Kingston and SanDisk 16 GB cards, none of which have failed.Additionally, I have over a dozen Transcend 2-8 GB SDHC cards, none of which have failed either.I can only conclude that either I have experienced a highly improbable event with this 100% failure rate, or that there is a flaw in the Transcend 16 GB cards.This latter seems much more likely, and I will avoid Transcend cards of more than 8 GB capacity.Today I just bought a SanDisk 32 GB SDHC - though more expensive than the Transcend 32 GB, I have the expectation that it is not as likely to fail.Caveat emptor: Let the buyer beware.
summary: Four out of Four have Failed

description_clean: Approximately the size of a postage stamp, SDHC cards offer greater capacity than standard SD cards while maintaining the same form factor.SDHC Class 6 cards offer more capacity and faster transfer rates.Display thousands of high quality photos on SDHC enabled digital photo frames.Ideal for expanding storage capabilities of netbooks and mini laptops with SDHC slots.Store More PhotosWith most point and shoot digital cameras quickly climbing the megapixel ladder, 6,8, and even 10 megapixel ratings are beginning to be commonplace. With Transcend SDHC cards, you can keep up with the larger files these high resolution cameras produce. With 4 GB, 8 GB, and 16 GB capacities, you can store more photos without having to delete old photos on the card before you have the chance to save them to a PC or print them out.Store More of EverythingThe larger capacities of SDHC cards make them more versatile than ever. Use them in all your mobile devices that support the SDHC standard. All that is required is an SDHC compatible slot or reader. SDHC is an extension of the original SD standard that enables capacities greater than 2 GB. It uses the same physical form factor as SD, but SDHC cards only work in SDHC compatible devices. Standard SD cards work in both SD and SDHC devices (backward compatible).Enjoy Faster Transfer SpeedsBasic SD cards transfer data up to six times (6x) the data rate of the standard CD-ROM speed (900 kB/s). Transcend SDHC class 6 cards offer a minimum of 6 MB/s write speeds under the most demanding storage conditions. Some cameras require a high speed card to be able to record video smoothly or capture multiple still photographs in rapid succession. Check your device for maximum compatibility for your intended usage patterns.FeaturesFully compatible with SD 2.0 StandardsSDHC Class 6 compliantCompatible with all SDHC-labeled host devices (not compatible with standard SD)Easy to use, plug-and-play operationBuilt-in Error Correcting Code (ECC) to detect and correct transfer errorsComplies with Secure Digital Music Initiative (SDMI) portable device requirementsSupports Content Protection for Recordable Media (CPRM)Allows In System Programming (ISP) for updating firmwareSupports auto-standby, power-off and sleep modesMechanical write-protection switchRoHS compliantLifetime WarrantyEnsure Your Device is SDHC CompatibleSDHC devices can use both older SD cards and SDHC (high capacity) cards. However older cameras and other devices that were released before the SDHC standard may not support the new SDHC cards. Please check your device documentation to verify compatibility before purchase. If your device is fairly new or states support for 4 GB or greater SD cards, then you already have SDHC support.Digital Camera Storage Capacity TableMemory cards should be purchased according to how high the resolution or DPI (dots per inch) of your digital camera is (i.e. how many megapixels it has), and how many pictures you plan on taking at a time. Transcend has provided the following graph to assist you in buying an appropriate capacity card for your camera:Storage CapacityCamera Type / Approximate Number of Pictures2 MP3 MP4 MP5 MP6 MP8 MP10 MP4 GB4550341220481638128010488168 GB9100682440963276256020961632*The "File size" represented here assumes that the highest resolution (DPI) your camera supports is used and that pictures are stored in standard JPEG format. The actual number of pictures you can take will vary depending on your digital camera's resolution and compression settings, composition (complexity) of the images taken, as well as lighting and exposure factors.

reviewText: This Gorillapod Medium Size Flexible Tripod is handy to easily positioning dSLR cameras with short lenses, point and shoot digitals, and mid-sized video cameras. We do a lot of product photography for my wife's small business and this tripod gives us additional flexibility to get just the right angle.The tripod is all plastic but plenty sturdy for most of my camera equipment, excluding my dSLR with a telephoto lens or a large GL2 video camera. The flexible legs allow this to be wrapped around a poll, hung from a branch, attached to a wire shelving unit, or used as a standard table top tripod. The mounting plate is somewhat simplistic, but works just fine.This will not replace my regular tripods for daily use, but the flexibility of this tripod allows us to get the occasional specialty shot that we require.Recommended!CFH

reviewText: This RAM is 1066 rated and if used in a PC rated for DDR3-1333 (as many current models are) then the computer's memory access speed will be throttled back to match the slower memory. This would mean a 25% performance hit on memory access, every time memory is accessed, while using your computer. Yes the computer will run OK but its performance will be reduced unnecessarily by using these modules if in fact your computer is rated for the faster 1333 RAM.
summary: Check your PC speed rating before buying

reviewText: This charger has the wattage to charge.  Each port has up to 2.4A charging capabilities.  So that means you can charge your smartphone which uses 1.0A, or an iPad that needs 2.1A and the Belkin will automatically defect what amperage it needs to charge.  For example you can charge 4 iPads and the charging speeds will be not be reduced, they will charge as though only one was charging.The unit in total has 10A, is 250V and a whomping total of 2500W!  With that much power no wonder it chargers faster.  Has an auto-shut feature and over-current protection.  It also is backwards compatible to 2.0 USB.  Lays nicely flat on any desk.  It does come with a power adapter and AC power cord, so not really meant for travelling purposes.  If you have multiple devices that take 2A and higher to charge, then this charger is made for you.
summary: Charge up to four 2.1A devices at once!

reviewText: Most anybody looking at this is probably thinking that it's kind of cool to start streaming content (or watching saved content) on a large HDTV using a wireless phone as a source, and they're right. It's pretty cool, and if your device does HDMI-out, this is exactly what you need.My only contention is that the build quality really isn't very good. If the HDMI end was USB, this cable would cost next to nothing at any online reseller that deals in bulk cables (including third-party Amazon sellers). I'm sure once HDMI-out becomes more ubiquitous on mobile devices, the price will come down. Even today, the price is certainly better than your wireless carrier would soak you for. But if producing HDMI -> Micro-HDMI cables scaled like HDMI -> HDMI or USB -> Micro-USB, I'd expect this to cost no more than a couple of dollars.

reviewText: The Seagate Wireless Plus 1 TB Mobile Device Storage with Built-In Wi-Fi Streaming is a massive storage device with the convenience of its own WiFi Network. Out of the box, getting setup and running is a breeze. The quick start guide is short and to the point. Included is a standard power supply/charger, and USB 3.0 cable. The charger is not needed if you're connecting via USB, but the proprietary USB cable is ridiculously short.The first thing I noticed is how bad the Seagate Android application is. It functions as little more than a file browser for the Seagate device, and adjusting some of its settings. Luckily, it's limitations are easily overcome by using the "ES File Explorer" application which I have installed on my Android devices. It makes transferring files to and from he Seagate device easy and fast.Connecting the Seagate drive to my devices via WiFi is easy and works well. One thing I do not like is that by default the drive's WiFi is configured as an open network. In order to password protect it, you need to change the settings in the Seagate application. In my opinion, password protection should be on by default. A lot of people may forget to turn it on, or not know any better.Once connected and setup properly, the performance was very good. The drive's WiFi range is excellent, and I had no problems connecting to it from throughout my house. My file transfer rate when connected via WiFi was about 9MB/s. When connected directly to my Windows computer via USB (2.0 in my case), I was getting 25MB/s. I think this is pretty impressive.Pros:Easy to setup.Has its own WiFi Network.Excellent performance and transfer speed.Massive amount of portable storage.Up to 10 hours wireless usage between charges.Moderately priced for what you get.3 year warranty.Cons:Android application is almost useless.Included proprietary USB cable is only about 18" long.WiFi Network is "open" by default.No travel case included.

reviewText: I was lucky enough to try out two outstanding mice (is that the correct plural for more than one computer mouse?) recently the Microsoft Wireless Mobile Mouse 6000 (reviewed here) and the Microsoft Wireless Mouse 5000.  The 6000 is a Mobile (and therefore much smaller) mouse with a tiny transceiver that barely extrudes from the side of your laptop, while the 5000 is a much larger, and therefore more comfortable, mouse with a transceiver that sticks much further out.  Both are extremely nice and I strongly recommend either of them.  For myself, I prefer the 5000 both for home and mobile use.  My hand tends to cramp up using a smaller mouse, while I can use the 5000 for several hours with complete comfort.  Obviously, it is the mouse that I prefer.  However, these things have to be adapted to the particular individual.  I like a very large mouse, but others might like much smaller ones.  Those who travel a lot, like smaller mouses and smaller transceivers, may well prefer the 6000.I have not had this mouse long enough to verify the claims about batteries lasting 8 months, but I can say that the batteries definitely last longer than the Microsoft Bluetooth Mobile Mouse that I was using previously.  I was changing batteries weekly with that mouse.  The Bluetooth mouse was also less responsive.  The only thing I miss about the Bluetooth mouse was freeing up another USB port.  All three are superb accessories, however.  At work I've used Logitech mice, but for myself, I will definitely go with Microsoft.Oh, one other thing.  Both the 5000 and the 6000 are both extremely comfortable to the hand and amazingly symmetrical.  Most mice are curved with a right-handed bias.  But for those who want to use a mouse in left-handed mode, they will find that the mouse works as well as in right-handed mode.  They are both real bargains for the price.
summary: An outstanding mouse for people who like a smaller mouse

reviewText: In unpacking this drive a few things quickly caught my attention. The charging cable is unique to the device, so if you want to travel with this drive you'll need to carry that cable in addition to all your other cables. (Although the transformer is a standard USB transformer so you don't need to use the one that comes with the drive.) There is a plastic end cap on the drive that you need to remove and replace with an adapter to attach the drive to a USB port, and the attachment cable isn't standard. So there are a lot of pieces to keep track of. There is also no manual included; I strongly suggest you download a copy before continuing.I tested the drive with my Kindle Fire, as using it as a tablet accessory seems to me to be its best niche. I really don't see carrying a drive twice the size of my phone to provide extra storage for my phone. And, while they suggest using it with a laptop, I can't see using a Wi-Fi drive with anything you can use a USB cable to plug a (smaller, cheaper) drive into.The drive comes with test documents on it, but I used the USB cable to transfer some additional files to it from my desktop. That generally went smoothly. After attaching the drive to my computer I got a message saying I needed to reboot before using the drive, but I didn't and it worked fine. After downloading the appropriate, free, app* to my Fire I had no trouble attaching to the drive. Doing so knocked me off my home Wi-Fi network. In theory you can then have the drive attach to the internet via Wi-Fi, but I wasn't able to do that with my encrypted network. It probably works with an open, public network that only requires a password. Once attached to the drive I was able to access the files on it, and even run the test videos. So that all worked.You have the option of password protecting the drive, which I strongly recommend. If you don't password protect it, anyone who has the app and is within range can attach to the drive when it's turned on. Unfortunately, the password can only include alphanumeric characters. I wouldn't store anything very sensitive on this drive.If you have a need for a lot of storage in a fairly small package, your only access mode is Wi-Fi, you don't mind a bunch of non-standard parts, and you can live with weak password protection, this drive will do the job for you. If it's not obvious to you that you need this drive, you probably don't.*Seagate Media (Kindle Tablet Edition)
summary: It does what it advertises, but with some shortcomings

reviewText: Past 2 weeks has been dropping connection everyday, pages take minutes to load- also affecting my DVR. TW refreshed the signal 3x but said translation of signal was not being picked up when it reached my Motorola. Looking for a new WG... I am giving 3 stars as it lasted 2 years with no problems until recently.Previous review:Install instructions were incredibly simple, I had it hooked up, entered my WEP security password into my laptop in less than 7 minutes. The hard part was with my cable company  (TW). I had to call them to give them the MAC address and for some reason had to be transferred 3 times before an internet tech could correctly enter in my 13 digit MAC i.d. Finally I was up and running. Have had no interruptions or problems.If you have internet cable best to call your cable provider to ask if they support this model ( and if they use DOCSIS) before purchasing.
summary: Update: lasted 2 years, now is dropping connection everyday

title_clean: Mini-DVI to VGA Female Monitor Cable Adapter
description_clean: Use this cable adapter to connect your Mac to an external monitor with VGA input. Plug the Mini-DVI end into your Mac, and connect the VGA connector to a VGA (male to male) cable, then plug the cable into your monitor's VGA input jack. Compatible models: 12-inch PowerBook G4, Intel-based iMac, the MacBook Intel-based laptop, the Intel-based Xserve, and the 2009 Mac Mini. Helpful Notes: This device is intended to function more as an adapter than as a cable, meaning its short length WILL NOT reach from your Mac to the monitor. It will need to be used with a VGA cable (sold separately). In addition, this adapter works only with Mini-DVI ports, not with Micro-DVI or Mini Display Ports. To quickly check what port you have: this adapter has a U-shaped connector that will match the U-shape found on Mini-DVI ports. Highest resolution supported: 1920x1200 @60Hz.

reviewText: My Dad got a NetFlix subscription for Christmas and I bought him this Roku box to hook up to his TV to stream his subscription. reviewText: My everyday in-ears are custom molded Futuresonics Atrios. They sound great but I needed an earbud/mic setup to replace the horrible sounding stuff Apple included with my iPhone 3G. The Sennheiser CX400 earbuds combined with a 3rd party in-line mic do the trick. They don't come close to the Futuresonics in sound quality, but at this price they are practically disposable -- very important for the rugged use my iPhone gets.Pros:1. Price2. Short cord (I changed out the included extension for a 3rd party in-line mic)3. Unoffensive sound with decent bass (Futuresonics Atrios sound like subwoofers in my head)Cons:1. Ridiculously difficult to open packaging. Frustration can easily lead to accidentally cutting through the accessories hidden in the packaging.

reviewText: Wireless keyboards with built-in trackballs, trackpads, or other pointing devices have developed very slowly. They have not been made by very many manufacturers which has kept the prices high, and the quality has been surprisingly low. Finally it seems as though the prices are coming down and the quality is on the rise. Exhibit A: this product. This product was exactly what I wanted for my home theater PC setup but could not find. It looks great and works great and it is the perfect size. Other models I have tried in the past were too small, too large, too hard to use, to easy to lose their connection or too expensive. So far so good; this item seems to fit the bill in all areas. 5/5 stars.
summary: Price and quality are finally headed in the right direction!

reviewText: I own two of the 3TB Seagate Expansion 3 TB USB 3.0 Desktop External Hard Drive STAY3000102. I use one to backup a nas and the second one for encrypted (using TrueCrypt) offsite storage. Setup was flawless on both Windows 7 and a ReadyNas. Read and write performance over USB 3.0 is lightning fast and will easily saturate my 1000 Mbps network when I use it for network backups.The drive has a built-in sleep mode so no on/off button is required and it comes with a USB 2.0/3.0 cable. Construction quality is fine and the drive looks to be solidly built. As with all drives only time will. One of my drives has been used on a daily basis for nas backups for 2months now with no hiccups or problems.If I experience any problems I'll come back and update this review but for now this is a five-star product.

reviewText: Ill try a little different twist on this and not totally repeat what others have already said.I have a SoundDock Portable and was looking forward to the bluetooth function of the SoundLink. I was hoping the two units would sound the same (or close) but they don't. The SoundLink is smaller, and it sounds smaller. It is a beautiful, well built unit and would compliment any decor. It sounds great for its smaller size, but cant compete with the SoundDock.The SoundLink is best for casual listening at moderate levels. It needs to be against a wall or in a corner for the full effect of the bass to show up. It sounds beautiful on a kitchen countertop, in a corner. There are enough EQ adjustments in the Iphone/Ipod to tweak it to your individual tones and taste. It does ok out in the open, but looses what little bass it has to offer.For me, I'm going to hang on to my SoundDock (which I reviewed years ago, and it still ROCKS btw) I'll consider an Apple Airport Express to add some convenience when on the wifi at the house.For me, an updated version of the SoundDock with added bluetooth, would have been a grand slam. The SoundLink is a home run!

reviewText: I set up this router about a month ago, and I've had absolutely no problems with it. It works great. It's a very fast router, that's optimized for gaming and video streaming, and is extremely easy to set-up.First of all the setup couldn't possibly be simpler. The instructions had me unplug my modem, connect the router via the provided ethernet cable, turn on the modem and then turn this on, and, as simple as that, it was connected. There's a simple routerlogin to change the settings, and the initial network name and password are written on a removable protective sheet on the router itself.It is automatically set up with two different bands, one at 2.4GHz that's optimized for gaming, and one at 5GHz optimized for high definition video streaming. The signal is a lot stronger than any router I've used, and as far as I can tell it transmits strongly throughout the house with no deadzones. You can adjust the antennas for optimal performance.I've been able to watch Netflix while my son plays his massive multiplayer game with friends online and it works just fine. It's also got two USB inputs, one that is USB 2.0 and one that's USB 3.0, and you can hook up an external hard drive or thumb drive to share content throughout your network. That's a great way to share music throughout the house and I can imagine would be very useful for sharing files in a small office without its own server.This is an easy-to-install, fast router that works great out of the box and has a lot of options. I'm very happy with it. (I had a chance to try this out through a Netgear trial program.)
summary: Easy-to-install, very fast, and optimized for gaming and video

reviewText: I'm a gadget freak, and this gadget hits pretty high on my favorite's list. Love all the ways to record things, and I love the portablility of it. It's a great fit for a shirt pocket. Although I'm not a serious audiophile, I find the earbuds give very good sound. On the down side, I find the interface a bit tricky to use. Changing channels and accessing menus could be easier. This is solved by using the remote, but it's still a bit of a challenge on a motorcycle. The antenna for the car kit doesn't pick up quite as good as my old SIRIUS radio, but it's very good if it's put on the roof. This one has a time keeping the satellites when you have it on the dash and you travel north.

reviewText: This is the second Belkin case I've tried for my mini.  The first was this model:Belkin Quilted Cover with Stand for the New iPad mini (Black).  The Belkin cases tend to be a little thicker than some of the cases offered by other manufacturers and a lot thicker than going with Apple's smart cover. If you're looking to keep the mini sleek, slim, and low profile, this probably isn't the case you're looking for.  If you want adequate thickness to protect the mini during transport or inside of a bag or briefcase, these cases are perfect.  The tab cover has a smooth simulated leather finish with a soft microfiber interior and elastic corner holders for the mini.  It has a magnetic closure that stays pretty secure when closed but the case does not have the smart cover sleep/wake feature.  The magnet is solely for securing the case closed.  It also keeps the back secured out of your way when the case is open.  The case has adjustable slots that enable the mini to stand in landscape mode. The mini feels very secure when propped in landscape mode.  Overall quality of material and construction appears to be very good.  The iPad fits perfect.  I'm not sure why none of the Belkin cases have the smart cover feature but if that's not a deal breaker for you, they are good quality cases.  In all honesty, I've always used the power button, even with my full-sized iPad with a smart case installed, so that's not a deal breaker for me.
summary: Adequate protection but no smart functionality

reviewText: I used this to replace a very old D-link b/g router that was on its last legs. I was curious to see how this would compare with my old router, and it led to interesting results. At any given time I have 8 or more devices on my network, including a blu-ray player, my AppleTV, laptops, NAS and desktops.Setup:Easy - the included CD made things pretty straight foward. No manual, but if you have a decent enough technical background you really don't need it. WiFi configuration made it a bit interesting - if you wanted to set up two different SSIDs for your network, you could. In my case I moved my AppleTV and other Apple proudcts to one SSID and kept the other the same as my old SSID.Network speeds:To be honest, I didn't see any real improvement over my transfers between my NAS, my desktops or anything else. That was a bit disappointing, but unless you've got everything at Gigabit Ethernet and Jumbo Frames, you probably won't notice anything. Same with Wifi - I was streaming the same as before.Network drive:The sharing of a USB drive was pretty easy to do - plug in, map the drive and go to town. No DLNA support means game consoles can't see it, and remember that if you have Macs and PCs coexisting, having a NTFS partition on your USB drive means Macs can't copy files to it.Overall I'm torn. This router is pretty slick, and I like having the dual band option so I can segment the network. If you have a poweruser household, that's probably a good option. The Gigabit Ethernet is pretty good as well. The router is slick-looking as well. Would I recommend this to mom? Probably not. Would I recommend this to someone who had a decent sized area to cover and a family with lots of wireless gadgets? Definitely. But in order to make this valuable and worth the investment, some planning and tweaking will be required. 3.5 stars.
summary: Decent high end router, but not for everyone

reviewText: I bought this machine because it could play MORE digital files than the competition (i.e. mkv, mp4, divx/avi, etc) via wireless from my Vista Desktop machine or USB.  This machine is truly a step above the competition in many regards that are important to me.When you receive the machine and setup the built-in wireless (I have ATT uVerse with the router in my room), it immediately does a firmware search to find the file.  It takes approximately 10-15 minutes for it to reboot with the new firmware.  Then you're golden.  You login to the Netflix account and and any other service and you're good to go!The desktop streaming takes a bit to figure out and the instructions are lacking on how to do this after you install the Nero software disc that's supposed to hook you up.  Eventually a pop-up screen user ID/password has to match your computer's and then you have to click into it from the menu.  I had to Google it to find out how to do the desktop to player set-up (apparently there's lots out there with the same problem!). Anyways, once set-up, the streaming is SMOOTH and FLAWLESS with large multi-GB files.  Quality of the digital file seems to be upconverted as the image looks great.  In addition, it works with multichannel files, so if you have 5.1 in the AVI file, it'll play back all channels.  The only issue with streaming in general, (i.e. desktop or Netflix on any disc machine), is that the FW/REW is slow to implement (several seconds lag), but this is "normal" for streaming functions these days me-thinks.  Mp3 songs also stream nicely.The Bluray and DVD playback quality is great.  Saturated colors and sharp.  The DVD discs upconvert brilliantly and look almost bluray level!I've read that a few users have had the player burp between chapter breaks on DVD/Bluray playback, but this is not the case with my player.  It plays SMOOTH from beginning to end.  I would suggest anyone that gets a player that does this to EXCHANGE it immediately (hopefully from a different batch!).  I suspect that LG uses different drives/chip from different mfgrs. and thus some may be getting a player with frazzly parts.  I wouldn't wait for some "oft-promised" firmware fix (as LG has told some who have this problem) if I knew other users were getting machines that work 110% (like me).Amazingly enough, there's nothing I can really ding this player on except the shoddy instructions on how to set up Desktop computer streaming wirelessly...which can be a PAIN(!!) if you've never done it before.In all, the fact that it can play a host of files from my computer and do everything else very competently sets this model lineup a step above Panasonic and the rest for its feature richness (and is a DAY and NIGHT improvement over the previous buggy Samsung wireless player I had!).  Remember to just do a chapter break test on your new unit and exchange if it stutters on you....then, once you have nag-free player, you should be golden!A word of advice on firmwares.  Once you have a firmware that WORKS, don't download any new ones until you know from other users (avsforum.com) it works 110% and adds something of real value to YOU (i.e. such as Hulu+, etc).  Too many times, the newer firmware is addition by subtraction--you get something naggy to work, but then messes up something else.  Just keep that in mind before looking down the barrel of the firmware gun!

reviewText: ultimately i like this router...i gave it a "5", because it has improved my wireless coverage throughout my home...1600 sgft...router is in one corner of my home...at opposite corner WiFi signal is now more than capable of Video Streams from NetFlix, whereas it wasn't before...(replaced an aging N-Draft LinkSys WRT350N)...i also like the Web Interface direct to the router (not Smart interface back to cloud)...it is very granular in a good way...you can tweak the 2.4, and the 5ghz bands independently...control the SSID...and especially select the band mix...i.e., i was able to set band mix for 5ghz to "N-Only", vice mixed...noticable inprovement in signal strength...you also have the ability to control the "Guest-NetWork", control it's SSID, password etc.,...now for the part i did not like!...the setup was gruelling...took me several hours, and many interations of combinations on the setup software...down-loaded vs. CD...i gave up on the CD and was eventually successful of using the down-loaded version of setup...which allowed me to access the web-interface...i was able to turn off the auto update...do a manual update to the latest "Non-Smart" version...everything is now OK...one exception, i still cannot change the login name of the router...the password yes, but not the login name...this is nimby, however it rankles-me-unendingly that i am not in control as i would like...the bottom-line is that it is now done and working quite well (praise-the Lord!)...I am curious, LinkSys calls this device a "Smart Router"...is that a description of the Router, or a requirement for the user?...i personally hate stuff that tries to make things so-easy you have no manual control, that constantly tries to anticipate your moves...so don't beat yourself up if you, like me, find this an exasperating set-up experience...i had to walk-away several times and have a bowl of ice-cream, in order to avoid smashing the blasted thing to smithereens...in the end it was worth the effort...remember, "...just breathe..."...good-luck & GodsSpeed in your endeavors...jo'c
