reviewText: I set it up to allow my Windows 8 PC, my ChromeBox and my Mac Mini to share  a single digital display monitor.  I use this device to switch manually between the three computers.  The switch worked perfectly, right away.  It even comes with an infrared remote control.  Remote?  I did not think I needed the remote since the switch is right next to my keyboard.  However, the switch automatically switches off an input which has been inactive for too long.  The only way to force the switch to keep an inactive input connected is to use the remote control.  Pushing the button manually does not override the switch's faulty decision to turn off an inactive input.  The switch will not keep open the input I want to use if the switch detects it as inactive.  For some reason, the infrared remote does override the switch's faulty inactive-input sensing logic while the push button does not.  Go figure.
summary: great little HDMI 3-input to 1-output switch, with just one glitch

reviewText: After just over one year of gentle use, this two hundred dollar DVD player suddenly quit working. After getting no joy from Toshiba (Verbatim: "I apologize for the inconvenience, however you are outside of your warranty period and we would be unable to assist."), I bought theAudiovox D1718 7-Inch Portable DVD Player(specifically theAudiovox D1718PK 7-Inch Portable DVD Player with Bonus Headphones and Car Kitwhich includes two sets of headphones, a car adapter, and padded travel case) for ninety-nine bucks at Wal-Mart, and we have been using it ever since. Toshiba wanted me to pay for parts, labor, plus shipping to fix the broken unit. That would have cost way more than the new Audiovox!The main thing I needed on a portable DVD player was dual headphone jacks. While you can use a splitter to allow the use of two sets of headphones from one jack, sound quality is degraded. Aside from the fact that both the Toshiba and the Audiovox both have dual jacks, almost every other feature favors the Toshiba. Except the fact that A) it cost twice as much, and B) it died.The Toshiba SD-P1850 was nice while it lasted, but I learned my lesson: portable DVD players are disposable. Buy the cheapest one that fits your needs, don't expect it to last forever, and just buy another if, or rather when, it breaks.

title_clean: Toshiba SD-P1850 Portable DVD Player with 8-Inch Widescreen LCD
description_clean: Take your favorite entertainment on the road with you and keep your kids entertained during long car trips with the slim-profile Toshiba SD-P1850 portable DVD player with 8-inch LCD screen with 180-degree flip and swivel functionality. Its active matrix TFT LCD has a 480 x 234-pixel resolution with a 16:9 widescreen aspect ratio for watching movies in the format they were made to be watched, built-in stereo speakers, and a single headphone jack. You can view movies on an external TV set via either the AV or S-Video output connections. It also provides Dolby Digital surround sound decoding via the digital coaxial audio output connection.It includes dual headphone jacks so you can share your movie experience with a partner, a rechargable battery with up to 4 hours of battery life, and a cigarette lighter adapter for powering the player while in the car. In addition to DVD movie and CD audio discs, it's also compatible with DVD-R, CD-R/RW and VCD discs. You can play discs burned with MP3 and WMA digital audio files, and it's also DivX Home Theater Certified--meaning that it's compatible with video burned to disc using both the DivX video format. You can also view photo slideshows from Kodak Picture CDs with JPEG images. The integrated multi-format memory card slot is compatible with Secure Digital (SD), MultiMedia (MMC), Memory Stic, and XD Picture Card formats, enabling you to view JPEG images and unencrypted MP3/WMA audio.With the Digital Picture Zoom interactive feature, you can select an area of the picture you want to zoom in on and magnify it. It can also be used to expand letterbox-only films to increase the viewable area on-screen. Other convenience features include slow motion (1/8, 1/4, 1/2), parental locks, and 3D virtual surround sound. It includes both input and output composite AV jacks.Tech TalkDivXis a compressed digital video format (like MP3) that's based on the MPEG-4 video compression standard. It can reduce the video from a DVD (MPEG-2) to around 10 percent of its original size while still retaining good video and audio quality, enabling you to store several two-hour length movies on burned DVD media.What's in the BoxPortable DVD player, remote control (with battery), car power adapter, AC adapter, AV cable, rechargable battery, printed operating instructions

It can reduce the video from a DVD (MPEG-2) to around 10 percent of its original size while still retaining good video and audio quality, enabling you to store several two-hour length movies on burned DVD media.What's in the BoxPortable DVD player, remote control (with battery), car power adapter, AC adapter, AV cable, rechargable battery, printed operating instructions

title_clean: Transcend 4 GB Class 6 SDHC Flash Memory Card TS4GSDHC6
description_clean: Approximately the size of a postage stamp, SDHC cards offer greater capacity than standard SD cards while maintaining the same form factor.SDHC Class 6 cards offer more capacity and faster transfer rates.Display thousands of high quality photos on SDHC enabled digital photo frames.Ideal for expanding storage capabilities of netbooks and mini laptops with SDHC slots.Store More PhotosWith most point and shoot digital cameras quickly climbing the megapixel ladder, 6,8, and even 10 megapixel ratings are beginning to be commonplace. With Transcend SDHC cards, you can keep up with the larger files these high resolution cameras produce. With 4 GB, 8 GB, and 16 GB capacities, you can store more photos without having to delete old photos on the card before you have the chance to save them to a PC or print them out.Store More of EverythingThe larger capacities of SDHC cards make them more versatile than ever. Use them in all your mobile devices that support the SDHC standard. All that is required is an SDHC compatible slot or reader. SDHC is an extension of the original SD standard that enables capacities greater than 2 GB. It uses the same physical form factor as SD, but SDHC cards only work in SDHC compatible devices. Standard SD cards work in both SD and SDHC devices (backward compatible).Enjoy Faster Transfer SpeedsBasic SD cards transfer data up to six times (6x) the data rate of the standard CD-ROM speed (900 kB/s). Transcend SDHC class 6 cards offer a minimum of 6 MB/s write speeds under the most demanding storage conditions. Some cameras require a high speed card to be able to record video smoothly or capture multiple still photographs in rapid succession. Check your device for maximum compatibility for your intended usage patterns.FeaturesFully compatible with SD 2.0 StandardsSDHC Class 6 compliantCompatible with all SDHC-labeled host devices (not compatible with standard SD)Easy to use, plug-and-play operationBuilt-in Error Correcting Code (ECC) to detect and correct transfer errorsComplies with Secure Digital Music Initiative (SDMI) portable device requirementsSupports Content Protection for Recordable Media (CPRM)Allows In System Programming (ISP) for updating firmwareSupports auto-standby, power-off and sleep modesMechanical write-protection switchRoHS compliantLifetime WarrantyEnsure Your Device is SDHC CompatibleSDHC devices can use both older SD cards and SDHC (high capacity) cards. However older cameras and other devices that were released before the SDHC standard may not support the new SDHC cards. Please check your device documentation to verify compatibility before purchase. If your device is fairly new or states support for 4 GB or greater SD cards, then you already have SDHC support.Digital Camera Storage Capacity TableMemory cards should be purchased according to how high the resolution or DPI (dots per inch) of your digital camera is (i.e. how many megapixels it has), and how many pictures you plan on taking at a time. Transcend has provided the following graph to assist you in buying an appropriate capacity card for your camera:Storage CapacityCamera Type / Approximate Number of Pictures2 MP3 MP4 MP5 MP6 MP8 MP10 MP4 GB4550341220481638128010488168 GB9100682440963276256020961632*The "File size" represented here assumes that the highest resolution (DPI) your camera supports is used and that pictures are stored in standard JPEG format. The actual number of pictures you can take will vary depending on your digital camera's resolution and compression settings, composition (complexity) of the images taken, as well as lighting and exposure factors.

reviewText: It's a shame that Western Digital saddled this portable hard drive with software that is cumbersome at best and potentially destructive. This product, at its core, can be very useful because it packs 500gb into a tiny case. The picture makes it look bigger than it actually is. It's smaller than my wallet.The biggest problem, as many have mentioned, is the software. So here is how to get rid of it (for Windows users):1. Disable Autorun. Instructions at [...]2. Plug in the drive. I didn't have problems with the cord being loose but other reviewers did, so be careful about that.3. Open Windows Explorer. The drive should show up under My Computer.4. Right click on the drive and format it. I'm pretty sure you manually delete all the files too, but you would need to make sure the folder properties are set to show hidden files.That's it. Now you have a tremendous amount of storage in a *tiny* package. Once you format the drive you can't get the software back, but you wouldn't want to anyway.full disclosure: I received an apparently open-box hard drive (the box was closed with scotch tape) for free to review but was not paid or otherwise compensated for this review.
summary: **Instructions for getting rid of troublesome software**

reviewText: Update for Trip Planning:I used the Tyre trip planning software that comes with the TomTom for a 1 day 300 mile winding back road drive last week. This software actually worked pretty well. It was easy to quickly plan the trip by using Google maps thru Tyre and transfer it to the TomTom. However, I don't like dirt roads and I could not get Tyre/Google to identify and avoid the dirt roads as I prepared the trip on the computer. Once I downloaded the itinerary to the TomTom, the TomTom told me that several parts of the trip were on dirt roads. I found myself modifying the itinerary just as I was getting ready to leave. I also found that if I placed a waypoint on the wrong side of a divided highway, the TomTom would hit me with an unexpected U-Turn, forcing me to backtrack. It is possible to delete the erroneous waypoint, but I could not find a way to easily relocate it while underway. I learned that one should closely review the trip (and map) created once it is downloaded to the TomTom. Be sure you put way-points on the correct side of the road.Original Review:I bought this after getting disgusted my last GPS's inability to quickly recalculate routes after a missed turn.  I've tested it commuting and on short trips around the area. My previous GPS units have included: the TomTom Rider 1; the Tomtom Rider 2; the Magellan RoadMate and the Worldnav. I ride about 10,000 miles a year, about 75% commuting and driving around northern Virginia in heavy traffic for work and play.What I like about the TomTom Rider 2013- It calculates a route quickly and it recalculates quickly. I won't be driving past the next exit as I wait for the unit to recalculate.- It is easy to see, day or night.  The larger screen is easy to read and it is bright enough to view 95% of the time.- It has very good routing software for a unit without traffic. It calculates the route knowing historical traffic jam patterns, but won't know about any immediate crash or incidents that a live traffic update would have. Unless there is a major crash, the calculated trip arrival times are amazingly accurate -- much more than any previous unit I've owned.- It is amazingly glove friendly. Bogus menu choices are a thing of the past.- I can record and correct errors in map data and I can mark them for future correction as I ride. I have already corrected the speed limit on a highway near my house. This is a longstanding error. The speed limit on this section of highway was increased to 65 MPH about 15 years ago, following a major rebuild and expansion, yet everyone's map software still has the speed limit at 50 MPH -- which is what it was during the construction project. With this unit the stupid speed limit warning is gone.What I don't like:- The mount. Simply put, mine is defective. I've tested the unit with a voltage tester and there is simply not enough power coming out of the contacts on the mount to power up the GPS or charge the battery. Mine is wired directly to the battery and I know it is getting full power. Over the years I've had several GPS units and I've had trouble with the mounts on all of them, but usually the problems appear after a couple of years of vibrations and moisture, not right out of the box. So I have wired mine to the bike by opening the door at the bottom and wiring that to the bike. I have done this to other units, but not immediately. This would be a 5 Star review if not for this issue.

However, I don't like dirt roads and I could not get Tyre/Google to identify and avoid the dirt roads as I prepared the trip on the computer. Once I downloaded the itinerary to the TomTom, the TomTom told me that several parts of the trip were on dirt roads. I found myself modifying the itinerary just as I was getting ready to leave. I also found that if I placed a waypoint on the wrong side of a divided highway, the TomTom would hit me with an unexpected U-Turn, forcing me to backtrack. It is possible to delete the erroneous waypoint, but I could not find a way to easily relocate it while underway. I learned that one should closely review the trip (and map) created once it is downloaded to the TomTom. Be sure you put way-points on the correct side of the road.Original Review:I bought this after getting disgusted my last GPS's inability to quickly recalculate routes after a missed turn. I've tested it commuting and on short trips around the area. My previous GPS units have included: the TomTom Rider 1; the Tomtom Rider 2; the Magellan RoadMate and the Worldnav. I ride about 10,000 miles a year, about 75% commuting and driving around northern Virginia in heavy traffic for work and play.What I like about the TomTom Rider 2013- It calculates a route quickly and it recalculates quickly. I won't be driving past the next exit as I wait for the unit to recalculate.- It is easy to see, day or night. The larger screen is easy to read and it is bright enough to view 95% of the time.- It has very good routing software for a unit without traffic. It calculates the route knowing historical traffic jam patterns, but won't know about any immediate crash or incidents that a live traffic update would have. Unless there is a major crash, the calculated trip arrival times are amazingly accurate -- much more than any previous unit I've owned.- It is amazingly glove friendly. Bogus menu choices are a thing of the past.- I can record and correct errors in map data and I can mark them for future correction as I ride. I have already corrected the speed limit on a highway near my house. This is a longstanding error. The speed limit on this section of highway was increased to 65 MPH about 15 years ago, following a major rebuild and expansion, yet everyone's map software still has the speed limit at 50 MPH -- which is what it was during the construction project. With this unit the stupid speed limit warning is gone.What I don't like:- The mount. Simply put, mine is defective. I've tested the unit with a voltage tester and there is simply not enough power coming out of the contacts on the mount to power up the GPS or charge the battery. Mine is wired directly to the battery and I know it is getting full power. Over the years I've had several GPS units and I've had trouble with the mounts on all of them, but usually the problems appear after a couple of years of vibrations and moisture, not right out of the box. So I have wired mine to the bike by opening the door at the bottom and wiring that to the bike. I have done this to other units, but not immediately. This would be a 5 Star review if not for this issue.
title_clean: TomTom RIDER Motorcycle GPS Navigator with Lifetime Maps

reviewText: After years of trying various "universal" remotes like the Pronto and Sony options, I finally decided to plop down the big bucks and go for the new Logitech 1100.The device is small and very contemporary in design.  It will fit nicely in your hand and the user interface is easy to use.Pros:1 - Stylish2 - Provides truly universal remote functions3 - Works as advertiseNegatives:1 - Expensive.  For $350, it should be able to do much more than just control your devices2 - Slow.  The device runs slowly and is no speed demon.  Again for the price it should be faster.3 - Bad setup software.  It uses a browser to connect to Logitech to download the configurations for your devices.  Slow but relatively reliable.4 - Device user interface is nice but sometimes hard to understand5 - Screen is small.  Again for the price I expect a bigger screenEven with more negatives than Pros, the device is worth it if you choose to spend the money.  It worked with all my devices even a legacy Replay DVR.  My only major complaint is that it feels as if it runs slowly.  In other words, it feels sluggish.There are better ways to spend almost $400.  Get an Apple iTouch with the universal remote software.  that may be a better option.  It may also be the route that I go next time.

reviewText: My wife and I have many iPod docks, it seems like one in every room by now.  We use them, but it's also hard to use them sometimes when your ipod is another room.  Enter the squeezebox.Essentially this connects wirelessly to the internet or to your computer and plays music.  I was hoping for native integration with iTunes streaming, but instead you need to install the Squeezebox server.  I haven't used it on Windows, but on Mac it's a pretty easy install, adding itself as a Settings Preference Panel.Other than that there are many additional things you can add.  For music there is Last.fm and Pandora, among many others.  Plus apps for other little things (display twitter/facebook/flickr photos).Sounds quality is decent, nothing superb, but for the volumes we listen to it at it sounds very acceptable.  One tip is to setup your [...] account and add/setup all your apps there, much much easier than entering usernames and passwords via a clickwheel.Couple of downsides.- If you have a secured wireless network, entering the key in via clickwheel can be frustrating.- If the computer that it's connected to turns off, it stops working.  No indication of what happened.  (Pandora also stops, but that might be a setup issue on my part).Either way it's a great little addition to a room, throw on pandora and have nice background music.Update:A couple of things.  I had a downside that if a computer it's connected isn't on nothing works, well if you leave it connected to the squeezeplay network (the main one) you'll never have problems.  However you won't be able to stream your music from iTunes either.  Also if you have an iPhone/iPod Touch, get iPeng, it's $9.99 but you can easily manage the squeezebox, turn it on/off, adjust volume, what it's playing etc.  If you have multiples it easily connects to multiples.  If you have a squeezebox server running on your computer, you can easily move the device between that and the squeezeplay network.

reviewText: As many others have noted, these headphones are comfortable, adaptable (multiple ear pieces to fit different size ears), have what looks like a strong/sturdy cord, and do what they say they'll do - block out external noise.  For all that I'd give these headphones at least four stars.  But I'm simply not impressed with the bass response.  I tried every song I could think of on my iPod and even tweaked the settings to maximum bass and the music was still, to my ears, tinny sounding.If you're buying these for noise isolation, comfort and reliability then they're a good buy.  Thumping bass, no.  I personally didn't need the noise isolation feature as much as I wanted some high end sound.  Thus, I have to give these three stars.  Your mileage may vary.  Or maybe there's something wrong with my ears.
summary: Noise isolation most definitely YES.  Bass response . . . no

reviewText: I received a 'for review' unit fro HooToo but I did not promise or hinted that a 'good review' was forthcoming. However, I found no fault whatsoever to this adapter.If you need a wired network connection and your computer lacks an Ethernet port but has a USB 3.0 or 2.0 port, this does the job perfectly. On my Windows 7 it was a quick install and it did not interfere with my Wi-Fi or my other Ethernet port. According to the specs, you get 10/100/1000 Mpit/s in full duplex and 10/100 in half duplex. Gigabit Ethernet, of course, is only possible over USB 3.0 because USB 2.0 is limited to about 480 Mbit/s.It's an easy 5-stars because I am unaware of any defects.
summary: The Solution (if lacking an Ethernet port is your problem)

reviewText: THE GOOD: I first tried aWinegard Company FL-5000 FlatWave HDTV Indoor Digital Flat Antenna - Made in USAwith little success.  There are two stations close to me in southern New Jersey (WNJS and WMGM) that I expected to receive with the antenna, but I had difficulty getting these both to come in at the same time - adjusting for one station caused the other to be marginal or gone altogether.  By comparison, the Terk FDTV1A got both of these stations in strong and clear.In addition, with the Terk I was able to get a usable signal for KYW (CBS), WTXF (Fox), and WPSG (CW) even though these are all over 55 miles away.  (KYW reception was pretty consistent, other distant stations dependent on the weather.)  Very impressive performance for a small antenna sitting flat on top of the TV cabinet.The flat design makes this antenna easy to hide and unobtrusive.  And the external amplifier means it can be removed from the signal path if you are in an area with strong signals, or easily replaced in the future if it ever fails.THE BAD: this antenna is not designed to get low-VHF signals, such as WPVI (ABC).  But this appears to be a limitation with most indoor antennas.  In addition, the antenna is not really omnidirectional, because the signal strength does a fair amount if I rotate the unit (without moving it).One other bad thing is that the lead from the antenna to amp is fairly long piece of RG-59 and not removable.  I'd have preferred a short lead of RG-6 to minimize added noise / interference between the antenna and the amp.  (I'll probably do this mod myself in the near future.)OVERALL: happy with the purchase.  I'm still considering a larger unit like theWinegard MS-2002 HDTV Antenna without Cablefor the attic, but for a small indoor antenna the Terk is really impressive.EDIT: So I tried out the Winegard MS-2002 in the same location, and surprisingly it didn't do any better than the Terk, despite its much larger size and higher price.  Now I'm even more impressed with the Terk FDTV1A and have upped my rating.EDIT 2: So I did the mod mentioned above, removing all but about 6 inches of the RG-59 lead from the antenna so I could get the preamp as close as possible to the antenna.  I also replaced the RG-59 output of the preamp (which was too short) with a longer piece of RG-6.  I think this did make a *small* improvement in performance, as my reception of KYW-CBS went up a few percent.  But I wouldn't suggest this mod as I'm sure it voided my warranty and didn't make a dramatic difference.
summary: The good and the bad (mainly very good)

reviewText: Right off the bat I recommend this even if you don't have USB 3.0. No screws to mess around with. I needed an external hard drive adapter for my new laptop with USB 3.0. The ORICO is nearly perfect for my needs. Pop in a nice cheap bare 2.5 inch hard drive, plug it in and go. Perfect, almost. Closing the latch when inserting a drive requires a bit of a special touch. Be sure to press DOWN on the latch button as it is pushed into place. Do this also when opening. I thought there was a problem with Windows image backups but it turned out to be a known problem with Windows 7 and USER files that backup is looking for that are not actually there. I might buy a second one. This is the best 2.5 inch external enclosure known to me and I have had most of them at one time or another. Right now I have 6 different other types minus one that failed.4/2/13: I am experiencing some performance problems with the ORICO. I am not sure if it is the adapter or the Western Digital Blue 640 GB drive inside. The drive is partitioned into 2 partitions. At random both partitions autoplay as if the cable had been inserted. I have used this drive extensively in a different USB 3.0 external adapter with no difficulty whatever. I have used a large number of external 2.5 inch drive enclosures and I have never seen this behavior before.
summary: Loved it at first but issues are developing.

reviewText: I bought this mount to use with my 26" Samsung Touch of Color monitor that doesn't have it's own VESA mounts. It's a shame I had to pay nearly $40.00 to buy a mount when the monitor should have the mount by default, but that isn't the fault of this mount which works exactly as it should. It's relatively easy to install (just remove the base of the monitor and it pops right in). I used this to attach my monitor to a monitor arm in my office. So far so good. I do wish the mount attached closer to the center of the monitor (it attaches towards the lower third of the monitor and makes the monitor slightly top-heavy when mounted to the arm).If you want to mount your Samsung Touch of Color monitor, you pretty much don't have any other choice but to buy one of these.

reviewText: Outstanding lens on a Canon 5D Mark II. Excellent in low light. I felt that it was a bit long for my 7D and found that a better choice for that camera was the EF 85mm f/1.8. From time to time you may run across a review that states that this lens, 135mm, is soft. I feel it is not soft, but it is more flattering than other excellent lenses when it comes to portrait photography. I'm comparing this lens to a Canon EF 70-200mm f/2.8L IS II and a Canon EF 85mm f/1.8 lens. Each of these are excellent portrait lenses but in my opinion the 135mm is outstanding. I do not like to spend time trying to improve images with software and there is very little to do when this lens is used. It's a good shot or a delete shot depending on the choices I made before I pushed the shutter button.

reviewText: I love this lens. It is one of my favorite Nikon primes for FX. This 35mm lens is a little wider than a standard 50mm lens, which lets you add more context to your shots or get closer indoors. Yet it's not so wide to distort people's faces like 24mm and below. It is sharp in the center at all f-stops, starting right at f1.4. It and the 85mm f1.4G are the only lenses that are sharp enough at f1.4 for me to voluntarily choose to shoot at that aperture. It is very sharp in the corners starting at f2.8 and peaking at f5.6. And here's a big surprise - this lens focuses closer than the 24mm f1.4G, the 50mm f1.4G, or the 85mm f1.4G. It's close-focusing prowess results in a useful 0.2x magnification, which works well for pictures of flowers or textures. My only complaint is that this lens' autofocus is too slow to capture moving subjects on my D3s. Nonetheless I wish I had purchased it sooner.*Update*.  When I purchased this lens in September 2011, it was the best 35mm lens available for Nikon bodies. Recently Sigma has released aSigma A 35mm F1.4 Lens for Nikonthat has generated astounding test scores and rave reviews from two reputable reviewers (lensrentals.com and lenstip.com). According to Szymon Starczewski at lenstip, the new Sigma A 35mm f1.4 has better resolution at all apertures, less distortion, less chromatic aberration, better coma correction, and faster and more accurate autofocus. Not only does the new Sigma greatly outperform this Nikon 35mm f1.4, but it is roughly half as expensive! Wow. Were I to purchase a 35mm lens today for my Nikon body, I would get the new Sigma instead.

reviewText: I often buy a new updated mouse because the features are better, or the technology of the older mouse is outdated. Or, I need it to go with a new system. I've got a few mice. None of them have actually failed until the Microsoft 6000 wireless.First, lets get what I loved about the 6000 out of the way. Wireless nano transceiver stows neatly in the bottom slot. Power switch, also on the bottom. Lightweight and free moving. A perfect fit for my hand - I love notebook sized mice and can never go back to a full sized mouse. Rubberized grip on both sides of the mouse. Easily usable by righties or lefties, and I am ambidextrous.However the left button simply lost the ability to click correctly. The right button still has the spring and response of a new mouse. I've had it less than a year. I game with it, as I have all my previous mice. But this one failed under the constant spastic clicking of online game play.No, it's not a gaming mouse, but neither were the half dozen mice that preceded it. I actually brought back an old mouse, theMicrosoft Wireless Mobile Mouse 3500, which I was using at work because the 6000 became unusable. The grip might be falling off my 3500, but it clicks as responsively as it did when brand new.I'm actually considering purchasing a new 3500, 4000 or 5000... but I'd never buy the 6000 again.
summary: My first mouse failure in... ever.

reviewText: This is about as cheap as worthwhile lenses get.  There are only two lenses in Sony's lineup that are cheaper than this (the 50mm F1.8, and the 18-55 zoom, which I've also reviewed).  As a very low-cost lens, it gets plastic construction, the SAM (Smooth Autofocus Motor) focus system instead of screw drive or SSM (the best focus drive around), and the most basic focus markings.  The SAM focusing motor means you have to deal with two focus mode switches; one on the lens, and one on the camera.  I could live without that, really; if I had my way, this lens would just use the body-driven focus and ditch the SAM.  But putting motors in lenses is the trendy design these days.  As I said, this is an all-plastic body; it doesn't feel nearly as solid as something like a Minolta metal body prime or a Tamron 17-50.So those are the drawbacks of this lens.  Let's talk about its good points.  This is going to take a lot more space.  Remember those cheaper lenses I mentioned?  Well, the 18-55 has (or really lacks, depending on how you look at it) one feature that's rather annoying; the front element turns with the focus ring.  So if you use something like a graduated filter or polarizer, you have to focus, and then adjust that filter.  Well this ultra-low cost 35mm doesn't do that.  Turn the focus ring, and the front element stays put.  So you can set up your filter, and then move on to focusing - a much better process.  And speaking of focusing, if you're a manual transmission kind of shooter, the ring on this lens has a good long range of motion, so you can do a good job of getting just the right focus.  Good thing, too, because this lens has a very shot minimum focus distance (MFD), and when you're right up on a subject at F1.8, the depth of field is pretty darn thin, so the focus had better be spot on in a shot like that.  I like lenses with short MFD; it's nice to be able to right up to some subjects.  Back to the focus ring; it turns a bit too easily for my taste.  That's being pretty nitpicky for a lens that costs around $200, though.  So, remember the all-plastic construction?  Well, it makes this lens light as air.  If you worry about weight in your bag, you'll absolutely love this lens.  It feels good on the camera, though; I have an A700, which is about the beefiest body short of a full frame body, and it handles well with this lens in place.  The autofocus works well (with the A700 body, anyway); I've taken a couple of thousand pictures of dancers in a dark theater, and every time the focus point was set on something focusable (i.e., pretty much anything but the plain backdrop or a solid black area) the lens focused fast and accurately.  The images are sharp in the center even wide open.  Stop it down just a bit, and it's sharp all the way across.  I'd say at least F2.8 to enjoy corner to corner sharpness.  There's a bit of distortion, but not much and it's easily fixed.  And the flare control is great.  I've put the blazing sun just off center, wide open, with a slightly overexposed shot, and only gotten one tiny dot near the center of the shot.  Stop it down a bit, and even that goes away.  Very impressive.  The lens comes with a good hood (that almost doubles the apparent size of the lens), a pinch cap on the front (so it's easy to take off or put on within the hood) with a big orange alpha symbol, and your regular old rear cap, proudly telling the world that this is a Sony lens.  Well, they should be proud of it.  It's an amazing lens at this price.  Another clue that it's a great lens; I toyed around with the idea of buying one for many months, and in that time, I only saw one used copy for sale.It takes 55mm filters; this is one of the smaller sizes, so the filters cost a bit less (or a lot less, depending on the quality level you go for).This lens is a keeper.  If you've got a Sony DSLR/DST, you should have one of these.Update; I've now had this lens for over six months, and am even more convinced that this is one of the best lens values you can possibly find for a Sony DSLR.  If you only own one prime lens for your Sony DSLR, it should be this one.
summary: You get a lot more than you pay for

reviewText: I'm an IT guy, and I go through hardware like crazy. In the past year I've tried out over 8 different routers and there is one thing that I have never had to replace and have always been happy with its performance. And that is the cable modem attached to my router. I've had this little cisco cable modem for a few years now and it's been plugged in, online non-stop since day 1. I've finally started to have issues and believe I may have to retire this little guy but it's been extremely dependable and I've never had any issues out of it until now and it's been a few years. This is a great modem, wish that all companies made products as solid as this one.

reviewText: I've always been curious what my dogs do while I'm not at home.  The DCS-5020L finally ended my curiosity.Setting up the camera was a lot easier than I expected.  I plugged it into an ethernet port and my computer quickly found it on the network.  I logged into the camera itself and played around with some settings.  From there, I created a Mydlink cloud account so I could easily log into the camera remotely.  I estimate the set-up took about 20 minutes.  The 5020L comes with screws so you can permanently install it somewhere, but I opted to just set it down in the location where my dogs usually sleep.The fun part of this camera is that I can login from work and see what my dogs are doing during the day.  The software also sends me an email when noise or movement is detected.  I found out what I long suspected - my dogs sleep almost the entire day.  The fun part about this camera is what when my dogs do walk around, I can follow them with the pan/tilt feature.  I can also zoom in to get a clearer idea of what they are doing.The image quality of this camera is an issue for me though.  The camera has a very difficult time picking up the details of my black dog.  She just looks like a black blob.  I can't make out her eyes or nose or anything else.  With my red and white dog, I can see her face clearly.  I know cameras of all types have difficulty with black dogs, but the lack of detail in this case is extreme.My other concern about this camera has to do with privacy.  I unplug the camera when I'm at home.  I couldn't find anything on the Mydlink Cloud site that specifically addresses privacy when it comes to the camera.  Specifically, does anyone at Dlink have the ability to login and see anyone's camera?Overall, I recommend this camera.  It offers a lot of interesting features - such as pan/title and email notifications of motion/noise.  It's also simple to set-up and access remotely.

reviewText: This MP3 player is simply awful! This is the third made-in-China mp3 that I ordered from Amazon in 2 weeks. The first two (Sandisk) were also total junk. Thing is, are there even any more things that aren't made in that place? SAD!

reviewText: This is the second Cowon device I've tried, based on reviews of their audio prowess. The first turned into a brick when I attempted a firmware upgrade (I'm a computer professional with 49 years of experience developing and managing software projects large and small; not a novice). Among the first things I did with the Z2 upon unpacking, charging and bringing it up was to insert a Kingston 8 GB microSD card. After FAT32 formatting, I was informed that I had something less than 2 GB of space on the card. Hmm. So I unmounted the card and physically removed it. I inserted it into both a Motorola phone that I have, running Froyo, as well as a Nokia N8. Both formatted the card correctly, reporting almost 8 GB.The user manual of this thing must be Cowon's idea of a joke. If so, it's a bad one. Yes, it sounds a bit better than my five-year-old iPod Classic and a lot better than the Nokia N8, but at the price Cowon gets for this thing, it simply isn't worth it. They deliver good audio, plus bugs, no documentation, and from what I've read, horrible support. This thing goes back to Amazon tomorrow.
summary: Cowon: at least they are consistent

reviewText: I love that Amazon is making a line of inexpensive, nice quality, basic cases for a multitude of electronics. I just wish that they would step it up a notch and make the hard cases truly hard cases!This case is similar to others available from Case Logic and other brands, the canvas-like shell has some sort of plastic inside top and bottom for rigidity, but the sides and zipper areas are relatively soft.This type of case would probably protect an item from a drop, but would never protect against crushing, because with even medium pressure, the front and back of the case can easily be pressed together due to the soft sides.I'd pay extra for a true hard case with these same dimensions - something with a similar external design, but taken a step further with hard corners and sides added. This would be a great intermediate option between the standard cases and seriously burly options made by Pelican and Vanguard, and an incredible selling point for the AmazonBasics brand.Overall, this Amazon case is much better quality than other similar cases in this price range, has a smoothly operating zipper, and will protect your Passport from falls.
summary: Nice for the price, but not brilliant

reviewText: I was prodded to buy this little thing by my wife, who heard it demonstrated at a trade show... At first, reading the numerous reviews I assumed the *Emperor's New Clothes*  effect had overwhelmed everybody- i.e. that nobody wanted to say that a 2" x 5" speaker they had shelled out this much money for was stupid. I was wrong- it is an astounding piece of engineering, providing room-filling volume (small rooms) and conveying the sensibility of the music so that it emerges quite beautifully, leading to toe-tapping and happiness.I have never heard any laptop internal speaker come close to this, despite the claims implied by the audiophile brand names; to significantly exceed the Soundmatters' capability would require fairly big external speakers. It  seems particularly suited for voice intelligibility, rendering NPR news crisply and clearly.We travel, often for extended times, and this avoids the pain of carrying speakers along. They thoughtfully provide overseas plug adapters for the charger. Does it replace my home music system? No, but it will serve us well for the times we're on the road.A word of caution: the Soundmatters can be overdriven by the output of my PC and Mac laptop headphone jacks, the resulting distortion is ugly and you wouldn't want to destroy it by sustained distorted levels.

title_clean: Soundmatters foxLv2 Purist Pocket-sized Portable Audiophile Speaker System, Black, Non-Bluetooth
description_clean: Soundmatters introduces foxLv2, a worthy successor to the first and still only portable pocket-sized stereo speaker system good enough for an audio purist. Sound+Vision Magazine called the foxL, “the absolute best gift of all time for audiophiles.” Powered by its built-in lithium ion battery, its included wall-charger, or USB connection, foxLv2 provides shockingly good fidelity (and bass) for its size. Its patented battery system actually doubles as a bass woofer and its patented left and right channel "Twoofer" drivers are built much like an audiophile tweeter with the twist that they can also woof. foxL and foxLv2 were designed by physicist, former NASA engineer and audio design legend Dr Godehard Guenther. His new V2 version providing smoother deeper bass, even more open/”airy” highs, along with the ability to play a bit louder. Anti-motion acoustic mat now included. foxLv2 accepts stereo 3.5mm audio input and has battery life of 12 hours. A second model, the foxLv2 Bluetooth is also available, which along with all the foxLv2 performance/features adds wireless music streaming (from iPhone, etc.) and hands-free speakerphone capability. Dimensions: 5.6-Inch x 2.2-Inch x 1.4-Inch. Weighs 9.5 oz. US Toll-free product/tech support 800/698.soma (7662) ext. 2.

reviewText: I got the iPad stand assembled in less than 10 minutes. The instruction is very brief but should be enough to put it together. The iPad holder is already assembled so all you have to do is screw it on top. If you have one of those Versalux floor lamps, the neck to adjust the iPad holder works the same way. The only challenging part is putting the screws on the three legs which are a bit tight. You will need an Allen key, but no worry it is included in the box.Securing the iPad is easy although at the beginning I had to resort to the picture to figure it out. You may need to remove the case if it has one to make it fit. The iPad rests using the two supports diagonally. It can accommodate different sizes of tablets as you can slide one of the corner holders for proper fit. Once adjusted, tighten the black knob at the back to hold the device secured. Now you can position the angle of the iPad by bending the neck wherever you need to.If you are not using the stand to hold an iPad, you can use the built-in LED lights as a reading light or a nightlight; it is dimmable. This is what I do if I am not watching movie, YouTube videos or surfing the internet handsfree while on my bed. A USB outlet is located on the top which you can use to charge you iPad, tablets or phone. BTW, this stand is USB only as you cannot directly plug it on a house outlet. You would need a USB power adapter like the one that came with the iPad.Overall, The iPad stand is a very decent product. My only gripes are the legs that fold up whenever you lift the stand to move around and the screw knob to tighten/secure the iPad which feels a little flimsy. The short cord also limits where you can place the stand.I was provided a sample of this product, so I could use it and write my unbiased review.
summary: Nice bedside stand for browsing or watching movies.  Very decent iPad stand.

reviewText: For the price, this is perfect. However, to be fair comparison against higher grade products, the feeling when you touch the switch is not that great (cheap switch), and the look is not that great either. LED indicator is too bright to my taste. This is the reason I gave it 4 stars instead of 5.This works perfectly for us sharing the same set of keyboard/mouse between 2 computers. It's even better than some higher end KVMs. Why? Because we don't need to switch the monitor through it anyway, so being able to use standard USB cables is a big benefit. Most monitors have multiple inputs, besides, we are using digital interfaces, so VGA switch doesn't help. Sometimes, we don't even need to switch monitor when using a laptop. We just need to keep our desks tidy and clean. So sharing keyboard/mouse is sufficient.Tip for Windows users: if you use this with your laptop, make sure you always use the same particular USB connector on it. Otherwise, the system considers it as a new device and tries to install driver, which takes a lot of time. So using the same connector saves time after your first usage.Update on March 13, 2013:It seems that this device was causing problem on one of the PC running Windows 7 premium. The machine freezes sometimes after waking up from suspension.
summary: Great gadet for sharing USB devices

reviewText: This is without doubt the easiest case I've ever worked with.  SilverStone has definitely put a lot of thought into how to make life easier for system builders.  Some of the advantages:1) The fans are all pre-wired and come with really long cables so that you won't have any trouble connecting them to your motherboard.  There's also a panel on top of the case that has speed switches for all the included fans.  By the way, all intakes also have removable filters over them for easy cleaning.2) The 5 1/2" drive slots have plastic covers that clamp directly to the case.  This means you can remove one from the middle and not have the others slide down.  There are also no metal plates behind them to make opening a slot a royal pain or cut your fingers.3) There's an astonishing amount of room behind the motherboard and ample holes surrounding the board.  This makes it very easy to route all your cables behind the motherboard.  In most cases, I was able to connect a cable with about a half inch of cable visible from the front of the system.  This makes cable management a dream and helps your system stay cooler.4) They included all sorts of helpful hardware.  Want to use liquid cooling?  There are brackets enclosed to attach the radiator directly to two of the 140 mm bottom fans.  Want to use an SSD?  A bracket is included for that and mounts behind the drive bays where it's out of the way.  There are also a number of very wide cable ties that slide through special slots on the back of the motherboard, helping make the easy cable management even easier.5) Since the motherboard is rotated 90 degrees (a brilliant innovation in case design that drastically improves airflow and cooling) your various wires and connectors are all going to be on top of the case.  The Raven has extra space up there, topped off with a vented cover so that you can route these wires out the back.  An improvement in the Raven 2 vs. the original Raven is that the motherboard is also actually dropped down about 2 1/2 inches from where you would expect it to be, with indentations for where the expansion slots and I/O plate go.  The end result is that you have a solid 4-5 inches to work with before the cable has to bend in order to feed out the back.  This makes the case much more compatible with the cable adapters that you might occasionally need.6) The side panels are very, very easy to remove and put back on.7) I doubt there is a power supply made that won't fit in this case.  It can accommodate way more length than my 1200 watt PSU.  The PSU can also be rotated 180 degrees.  The end result is that whether your PSU has its air intake on the top, bottom, or back end the Raven case will allow you to orient the supply so as to get the best air inflow.At the end of the day, this case provides exceptional cooling and runs very quietly.  You will get noise from your graphics cards, of course.  There's really no way around that.  But because air flowing through the system only passes one hot component before exiting the case the cards stay cooler and that means that their fans don't need to work as hard.  This results in them being quieter.I have definitely found my new favorite case.  On top of that it pairs exceptionally well with the Rampage 3 motherboard due to the fact that this board puts dual SLI graphics cards in the #1 and #3 slots rather than #1 and #2.  The extra space between those cards then means that they don't heat each other up and can really benefit from the enhanced airflow of the Raven case.Update:Now that I've finished building my system and have had the opportunity to do some benchmarking and high-end gaming I am even more impressed.  As others have noticed, the thermals for the Raven are absolutely amazing.My new system replaces one I'd had built and then returned to the manufacturer due to hardware issues.  That system had used theAntec High-End Performance Case P183 V3andASUS P6X58D Premium - LGA 1366 - X58 - DDR3 - USB 3.0 SATA 6 Gb/s - ATX Motherboardwhich I changed out on this new system with the Raven 2 case and theASUS LGA 1366 - Intel X58 - Republic of Gamers - ATX Motherboard Rampage III Extrememotherboard (which is very unusual in that it doesn't put the graphics cards right next to each other when running two-way SLI -- a very smart move.The Antec case is very well known for being a quiet machine and indeed when it was at idle it was completely silent.  The Raven is able to be heard at idle, even from a few feet away.  It's very quiet (more so than my last two computers, in fact) but you know it's running.  The story changes when you actually start gaming, though!  With the P183 case the other board my GPU's were hitting as high as 97C, making the fans speed up to 87%.  This made it a fairly loud system, easily able to be heard over my games.By comparison, the GPU's in the Raven case never got over 68C and the fans topped out at 69%.  I can't hear the system over my game at all.  (I have the fan switches all set to the "low" setting, by the way.  Setting them to high would undoubtedly keep the system even cooler when gaming, but it's extra noise that I don't want the rest of the time.)  So when it matters, the Raven 2 case is actually quieter than one supposedly built for quiet!SilverStone has an absolute winner with the Raven 2.  I could not be happier.  It's easier on my ears and because everything runs so much cooler I expect the components to last a lot longer as well.

The Raven has extra space up there, topped off with a vented cover so that you can route these wires out the back. An improvement in the Raven 2 vs. the original Raven is that the motherboard is also actually dropped down about 2 1/2 inches from where you would expect it to be, with indentations for where the expansion slots and I/O plate go. The end result is that you have a solid 4-5 inches to work with before the cable has to bend in order to feed out the back. This makes the case much more compatible with the cable adapters that you might occasionally need.6) The side panels are very, very easy to remove and put back on.7) I doubt there is a power supply made that won't fit in this case. It can accommodate way more length than my 1200 watt PSU. The PSU can also be rotated 180 degrees. The end result is that whether your PSU has its air intake on the top, bottom, or back end the Raven case will allow you to orient the supply so as to get the best air inflow.At the end of the day, this case provides exceptional cooling and runs very quietly. You will get noise from your graphics cards, of course. There's really no way around that. But because air flowing through the system only passes one hot component before exiting the case the cards stay cooler and that means that their fans don't need to work as hard. This results in them being quieter.I have definitely found my new favorite case. On top of that it pairs exceptionally well with the Rampage 3 motherboard due to the fact that this board puts dual SLI graphics cards in the #1 and #3 slots rather than #1 and #2. The extra space between those cards then means that they don't heat each other up and can really benefit from the enhanced airflow of the Raven case.Update:Now that I've finished building my system and have had the opportunity to do some benchmarking and high-end gaming I am even more impressed. As others have noticed, the thermals for the Raven are absolutely amazing.My new system replaces one I'd had built and then returned to the manufacturer due to hardware issues. That system had used theAntec High-End Performance Case P183 V3andASUS P6X58D Premium - LGA 1366 - X58 - DDR3 - USB 3.0 SATA 6 Gb/s - ATX Motherboardwhich I changed out on this new system with the Raven 2 case and theASUS LGA 1366 - Intel X58 - Republic of Gamers - ATX Motherboard Rampage III Extrememotherboard (which is very unusual in that it doesn't put the graphics cards right next to each other when running two-way SLI -- a very smart move.The Antec case is very well known for being a quiet machine and indeed when it was at idle it was completely silent. The Raven is able to be heard at idle, even from a few feet away. It's very quiet (more so than my last two computers, in fact) but you know it's running. The story changes when you actually start gaming, though! With the P183 case the other board my GPU's were hitting as high as 97C, making the fans speed up to 87%. This made it a fairly loud system, easily able to be heard over my games.By comparison, the GPU's in the Raven case never got over 68C and the fans topped out at 69%. I can't hear the system over my game at all. (I have the fan switches all set to the "low" setting, by the way. Setting them to high would undoubtedly keep the system even cooler when gaming, but it's extra noise that I don't want the rest of the time.) So when it matters, the Raven 2 case is actually quieter than one supposedly built for quiet!SilverStone has an absolute winner with the Raven 2. I could not be happier. It's easier on my ears and because everything runs so much cooler I expect the components to last a lot longer as well.
title_clean: SilverStone 0.8 mm Steel SSI CEB / ATX Full Tower Computer Case with Side Window RV02B-EW (Matte Black)
description_clean: The RAVEN RV02-E is an evolution of the original RV02 case that aims to provide even more accessible performance and utility. Making a debut for the first time in a tower chassis, SilverStone’s own "Air Penetrator" 180mm fans are included in the RV02-E for improved air intake efficiency and flexibility. The fan frame of the Air Penetrator fans provide enough fan blade protection and increased air focusing ability that they no longer require installation of fan grille. Hot-swappable hard drive cage was also implemented to facilitate installation at the expense of losing the 8th expansion slot. However, all other features are intact such as fully filtered intake system, 90 degree motherboard mounting, all black interior, liquid cooling support, and fan speed switches. For enthusiasts not looking to use more than two or three graphics cards, the RV02-E should be a great alternative to the fantastic original RV02.

reviewText: This amp is even better than the s-video model I purchased 6 years ago. Has very little effect on the source signal, though you might want to ensure that you keep this warmish-running unit in a ventilated area (please. NEVER put a precision amp like this in a smothering corner. If necessary, get a small cooling fan. It will last years longer). In calibrating its output into both of my tv's I noted a slight depression in very, very dark (near zero IRE) blue. Easily solved, but if your tv has RGB controls you might want to shove dark blue upward a mere notch to avoid greenish blacks. Very even color transmission, no loss of contrast or resolution, very little noise if any. A far cry from the second-rate results I've seen with similar products at or near this price. I do have a $750 unit with slightly (I said slightly) better performance, but my tv and two DVD recorders shows this unit is first-rate. Test screens on associated equipment show that the amplified image and audio are not overloading my components. Apparently each output amplifies the input just enough to avoid signal loss (i.e, intelligently designed unity gain). What goes in is what comes out, not over-powered. You often see a lot of visible brightness pumping with this sort of amp, but not here. Another good design from CE Labs.
summary: stellar performance; $1000-plus might get something better (?!)

reviewText: This product helps stabilize the smaller body X-E1.  The only thing I don't like is that I need to tighten it using an allen wrench.  Unfortunately I have to remove the thumb grip when I want to use flash which luckily doesn't happen too often.  The build is decent as so far I have not seen any brassing or anything of such nature.  It's got a nice solid heft to it. Comes in a petite blue box with the wrench which I keep in my camera bag with my other gear.I would buy this again due to an excellent price even with the small screw limitation.  Speaking of the allen screw, I've heard of some of these being tightened down too much and damaging the flash hot shoe.  I just tighten it enough to feel some tension and leave it at that. After my last session shooting with external flash, when I removed the thumbs grip I inspected the hotshoe and found zero damage or any marks whatsoever.  So I will continue to keep it just tight enough, but not too tight to cause any problems with the hot shoe of the Fuji X-E1.  Definitely would buy again.
summary: Fits nicely, Helps stabilize and hold the Fuji X-E1

reviewText: This is the lightest "lightweight" tripod that I could find, and it folds down to the smallest size for easy transportation. I am aware that this will not suit for a lot of video panning, nor will it keep my camera steady in a high wind. But, I will have this tripod with me wherever I go, because it's small and fits in the side of my LowePro camera backpackLowepro SlingShot 102 AW. This will suit me for nature shots, long exposures, and some video work. I also plan to use it for shooting video in a miniature studio. I'll post updates as to how it works out.Tripods are like cars... there are thousands of models on the market. Only YOU can decide on the right one for you, based upon your proposed use, budget, weight, size, needs.I gave this one five stars because it is the best in the class that I was looking for.I am using this tripod with a Panasonic FZ200, a bridge camera that weighs just over one pound.

reviewText: I don't have Windows 8 and I don't know if I even want it, but that didn't stop me from getting this shwank wireless mouse with a wide zone touch pad. It allows you to move your cursor fluidly without those pesky wires getting in the way and it allows you to move the page up or down with a swipe of the finger.The responsiveness isn't as accurate as theMicrosoft Arc Touchand the touch pad functionality isn't as good either, but it's fine as an upgrade from a trackball mouse if you're on a PC (it was really slow on my 2007 iMac). The main problem I have with it so far is actually this mouse's claim to fame--the middle button (pressing the touch pad). I accidentally hit it all the time and it brings up the start menu on Windows. I rarely want the start menu (even if I don't have Windows 8 yet), so this is fairly annoying. I'll learn to avoid hitting it, but until I do, I'll have to suffer through accidental menus. This would be remedied if there was an easily accessible options program for the mouse, which I couldn't find.All in all- this is a solid mouse, Windows 8 or not.

reviewText: I was pleasantly surprised by how comfortable, noise-isolating, and good sounding these Arctic over-ear headphones are. That said, I normally cannot listen to full volume iTunes music on any of my devices because it's too loud, but with these Arctic over-ear headphones, I can boost the volume to maximum without any listening discomfort. If I were (more) hard of hearing, these would frustrate me, but because I'm not and because I don't like to blast music, these headphones are great.They are lightweight enough to wear for hours, and the adjustable headpiece ensures that I get a fit that keeps them in place. The sound quality is not bass-heavy, although it picks up the lower ranges nicely, giving the sound a balanced quality that headphones built specifically for rock often lack. The one criticism I have of the sound quality is that it lacks the depth of more expensive sets and even the company's other Bluetooth headphones, the ARCTIC P311 Bluetooth Stereo Headphones. Despite this, the sound -- instrumental and vocal -- is clear. These are definitely more comfortable and more noise-isolating than the P311 -- as I write this, there's a vacuum running in the next room, and I can't hear it. This is a huge plus.The Bluetooth range is about 30 unobstructed feet or 24 with a wall between. Most people won't range that far from their devices while listening, although if you plan to, make sure you don't need to range farther than the preceding.The controls are a little difficult to locate while wearing them because they don't stick up enough to locate by touch. I can answer calls, thanks to the built-in microphone, and use the voice activation (Siri) feature of my iPhone.Although I enjoy listening to music through these, I prefer (somewhat) the P311 unless I need to block out noise. They are a great mid-price option for those who love the cordless operation of Bluetooth headphones. Note: I received a sample for review.-- Debbie Lee Wesselmann
summary: Great Sound Quality -- With Some Muted Volume (4+ stars)

description_clean: ARCTIC P402BT is Bluetooth v2.1 compatible wireless stereo pro DJ-style headphones with an integrated microphone. It can be paired with the most popular Bluetooth-enabled devices such as portable music players (MP3), Smart Phones as well as computers using VoIP applications. Balanced linearity produced true sound reproduction for different genre of music. Integrated 850mAh rechargeable battery provides over 30 hours of continuous play time and over 300 hours of standby power, giving you plenty of time to enjoy your favorite music tracks or movie titles without bothering with tangled wire. ARCTIC P402BT features a hidden microphone that has no problem in picking up your voice in normal conversational volume during a phone call. P402BT intelligently alerts you with a ring tone when there is an incoming phone call; put the music on hold while you answer the call and resume playing exactly where you left off once the call ended. It is extremely easy to operate P402BT: pairing with Bluetooth-enabled device takes minutes to accomplish. The intuitive user control allows you to skip forward, backward or pick up a phone call with a simple push of a button. Ultra-soft cushion are designed for extended wearing comfort that do not pin down your ears and are suitable even for people wearing glasses. Large ear cups covered your ear completely and effectively cancel out most of the background noise. You can enjoy true stereo music for hours comfortably at home, at work or on the road. reviewText: As this drive is a bit small for my production computers, I installed it in my Linux (Ubuntu) based home theatre PC. For this purpose, I have 3 needs: durability against high operating temperatures, quick wake up times, and quiet operation. This drive is satisfactory for all three requirements.As I learned just this month when theSSD in my basement serverfailed, SSDs can fail catastrophically. One minute, you have all your data, the next minute you have none.  Luckily, I had backed up critical files, but it was a pain rebuilding. Thus, I was somewhat interested in the durability of this SSDNow drive, obviously, I don't have time to run it for a couple years and get back to you, but I did run it for several weeks in my little HTPC, where the output fan is pushing out 70C air, and the GPU is always well over 80C. Since the datasheet for this drive lists its maximum operating temperature at 70C, I think I'm safe to say that it was running in a challenging environment, and it's still running, so pretty good there.Previously, I had been using a standard 5200 RPM laptop drive in this HTPC, and that was fine performance-wise, except that when waking from sleep it would take an annoying amount of time--perhaps 10 seconds--to fully wake up. With this solid state replacement, wake up is imperceptibly instantaneous, and I can immediately start browsing through recordings. I should point out that I don't record video streams to this disk, which has a limit on total lifetime bytes written of 36TB according to its spec sheet; recording is done on another computer onto a traditional spinning disk. Because of this lifetime limit, Linux users should tweak their settings to minimize writes to disk such as when paging memory out to the swap partition. Googling around you'll find the proper settings for your fstab file, and choosing a disk scheduler.As for quiet, well it's an SSD. It's incapable of making noise.In my particular hardware setup, which I believe has an SATA II controller, I'm getting competitive numbers on benchmarks. The IOZone benchmark (4kB records, 4GB file size) gives a peppy 181 MB/s write and 209 MB/s read throughput.So, if the drive was satisfactory on everything I threw at it, why the three stars? Mainly because, there is nothing about this particular drive that stands out from any other 128 GB SATA III drive. It doesn't excel in any particular way over competing brands I've looked at. It didn't make my boot times instantaneous (at this point booting UBuntu in 20 seconds does not knock me off my seat). If it had some extra feature, like an integrated USB interface, or was particularly low power then maybe I could have given it more than the "It's OK" standard of three stars. But it doesn't and I won't.Recommendation is feel safe buying one if you get a competitive price.

reviewText: I have an old computer upstairs where there is no ethernet wiring.  The computer does not have a built-in wi-fi adapter.  This gadget fit the bill perfectly.  Not only does it work very well off USB (I didn't even bother connecting it to the included AC adapter) but it has very good range reception.  The previous wireless device I had connected to this computer worked very poorly in this location -- the Netgear adapter works great.  It is also much smaller than you might think from its picture.  It is about the size of a deck of playing cards.My only criticism of this adapter would be the somewhat poor instruction sheet.  Anyone unfamiliar with computers and wi-fi connections would have a tough time setting this up if their router has wi-fi security enabled and you do not have a WPS-type router.  If using WEP security you need to specify if it is 64 or 128 bit encryption. You also have to specify your router's HEX key.  To set up other wireless devices in my home, like my wi-fi enabled bluray players, the connection is made with an ASCII key.  But this Netgear device requires a HEX key.  It took me a little while to figure this out because it also asks for a password, but once I entered my router's hex key and used the ASCII key for the password I was in business.This is a very low-cost way to add wireless internet access to another room in your home.  It is highly recommended, and I would not hesitate to buy another one if the need arose.

title_clean: NETGEAR Universal N300 Wi-Fi to Ethernet Adapter (WNCE2001)
description_clean: Connect any Ethernet-enabled device to your wireless home network with the NETGEAR WNCE2001 Universal WiFi Internet Adapter. The adapter is perfect for home theater devices such as the Xbox 360, PS3, TiVo, Blu-ray player, and more. And thanks to its elegant, compact design, you'll save space and have a lot of flexibility in choosing where to place it.Universal WiFi Internet AdapterAt a Glance:Adds wireless capability to any Ethernet-enabled deviceWorks with Xbox 360, PlayStation 3, TiVo, Internet-enabled TVs, and moreWireless-N for fast performancePush 'N' Connect provides easy securityThe easy-to-setup WNCE2001 brings wireless-N capability to any Ethernet-enabled device.View larger.Dynamic LEDs display real-time network connection status.View larger.Wireless Connectivity for Your Ethernet-Enabled DevicesMore and more of today's home theater devices are Ethernet enabled, including TiVo, VUDU, Blu-ray players, Xbox 360, PlayStation 3, Internet TVs, and more. With this NETGEAR adapter, you'll be able to cut the cord and use a wireless connection to network your devices.Universal CompatibilityWith the WNCE2001 Universal WiFi Internet Adapter, you will no longer need to buy individual proprietary WiFi dongles for the TV, Xbox, etc. because WNCE2001 works with all of them. You can simply plug it into the device when you need to and share it among multiple gadgets.Wireless-N Technology for Fast PerformanceThe WNCE2001 adapter supports Wireless-N (2.4 GHz 802.11n) technology for outstanding speed and performance, keeping pace with your home theater devices. In addition, it is also backwards compatible with 802.11g and 802.11b networks.The adapter can also repeat 2.4 GHz WiFi signals from devices made by NETGEAR and other brands, and it features dynamic LEDs that display real-time network connection status.Push 'N' Connect for Easy SecuritySetting up a secure connection couldn't be easier with NETGEAR's Push 'N' Connect technology. Push 'N' Connect using WiFi Protected Setup (WPS) offers true plug-and-play simplicity by requiring you to simply push the Push 'N' Connect button on your router. In addition, the adapter also supports WiFi Protected Access (WPA2-PSK, WPA-PSK) and WEP encryption.Compact, Smart Design Can Use USB for PowerThe Universal WiFi Internet Adapter is a compact device that measures just 3.2 x 2.4 x 0.7 inches, giving you flexibility in choosing where to place it. In addition, the adapter can be powered by either the included power adapter or with the USB port. reviewText: I've had many small 2.5" hard disk enclosures that run off USB port power on a notebook computer.  This is the best-made and fastest one that I've used and it's very nice.  The eSATA performance and connectivity was welcome.I was able to run the hard disk reliably from the power available on a single USB port although the enclosure does come with additional cabling for extra power.  A nice accessory to netbook systems and probably a decent approach to backing up small to medium-sized business sytems overnight.

reviewText: Had to update this review as I have also experienced the broken plastic piece that holds the headband, so you can't wear it on your head without repairing it.  I was able to do so with a couple of wire ties, but it looks a bit sad.  Poor quality plastic was used and it fractures with regular uses.  now that I've repaired it, it will probably last.  Still very happy with the quality of the sound both send and receive.Plugs into the wall jack so it is a stand alone device, but you need to have another phone in the house to make outgoing calls.  I use my other phones to make the call, then join the call with this headset and hang up the other phone.  This may link to DECT 6 remote phones, but I didn't try that.  Didn't seem to be a need to do that and tie up another station on my phone system.  The incoming volume is widely adjustable.  The outgoing voice is clearly heard on the other end.  Only downside is that it is hard to tell when you have pressed the mute button.  I sometimes have to walk back to the base station to see the indicator since people talking loud can cover the small beep that happens when you put the device on mute.

reviewText: I bought this tuner and had many of the same issues that others mention in the reviews. I returned it and ended up buying a PCI-E card from Hauppauge that works great. But that isn't very helpful if you're wanting something for a laptop...Based on the reviews on Amazon alone, it sounds to me that it's hit or miss with this tuner. It either works or it doesn't. People who get a working one seem to be happy. On the flipside, sounds like Hauppauge is sending out a lot of lemons... apparently their quality control is as good as their customer service. For anyone considering buying this product, I would suggest making sure to buy from a reputable retailer where you can return for a full refund and without return fees if yours doesn't work. I'd also only purchase knowing there's a good chance it won't work and don't spend too much time trying to troubleshoot if you can't get it to work. Based on others reviews, it will either work out of the box, or it won't work at all.
