reviewText: Pros:+ Includes remote control+ Uses DLNA for local network playback+ Built-in weather app+ USB inputCons:- Controls often unresponsive- No WiFi Protected Setup- Won't play Apple Lossless .m4a filesThe Grace Digital "Mondo" is clearly an attempt to copy the popularLogitech Squeezebox Radio. The two products are very similar in size, shape and configuration, right down to the handle recess in the back. The Mondo is an inch taller and wider than the Squeezebox Radio, but close enough.  Both have a color LCD screen, large rubberized knob that pushes in for selection and buttons for favorite stations.There are some physical differences: the Mondo has a separate volume control knob that sticks out the top, which when pushed mutes the audio, whereas the Logitech has its volume/mute knob on the front. The Mondo also has a snooze/sleep-timer button on top for the alarm function - while the Logitech can also serve as an alarm clock, it has no dedicated snooze button.There are some differences in the Mondo's favor. A significant one is that, unlike the Squeezebox, it can play from any DLNA server on your network without the need to run a dedicated server program. I keep my music on aNETGEAR ReadyNAS Ultra 4 Plus Network Attached Storage Boxand it operates as a DLNA server.  However, a Squeezebox Server program is also available for it so this advantage is muted for me.  (And no, I didn't mean "mooted", though I suppose that also applies.) However, if you don't have a DLNA server on your network, you'll need to run one. There are many free servers available for various platforms. Recent versions of Windows Media Player have this capability.Unfortunately for me, the Mondo will not play Apple Lossless high-bitrate .m4a files.  It sees them, but when you ask it to play they are just skipped over.  This is not just a DLNA issue as the Mondo won't play them from a USB stick either.  The Squeezebox Radio will play them, however. Luckily I don't have a lot of those, but I have been choosing that format for ripping CDs recently and that shuts them out of playback on the Mondo. [After my initial review was posted, Grace Digital said that they would add Apple Lossless support in the future.]Another annoyance is the method of entering the wireless network password.  The Logitech Squeezebox Radio supports Wi-Fi Protected Setup (WPS), where you push a button on your router (and select an option on the Radio) and the wireless information is exchanged automatically.  The Mondo makes you enter the password manually by scrolling through the characters one by one.Both products share a wealth of features.  Of course they'll both play Internet Radio and have searchable and categorized lists of stations. Both can identify "local" stations with streaming broadcasts. Both can access a variety of services such as Pandora, SiriusXM, last.fm and many more.  Both can serve as clock-radios, have adjustable dimmable displays and both support WiFi connectivity.  The Mondo will also support wired Ethernet if you buy an optional USB adapter, but the Squeezebox Radio has an Ethernet jack built in.  Both let you do some customization on a web site and both offer smartphone apps that can control a box on your local network.The Mondo includes an infrared remote control; Logitech makes you buy that separately. The Mondo also comes with a stereo line-out cord for connecting to a hi-fi system - the Squeezebox Radio does not have line out capability.  Both include a 1/8" stereo phone jack for connecting an iPod or other music player. You can get an optional rechargeable battery for the Squeezebox Radio - the Mondo has a compartment for one (at least that's what I think it is) on the underside, but Grace Digital doesn't list one for sale that I can see and there is no mention in the manual. (Edit: Grace Digital informs me that a battery is now available.)So what is the Mondo like to use?  Frustrating.  The first unit I received played fine - for about 15 seconds.  Then it went mute.  A power cycle brought it back for another 15 seconds, but after that nothing I did could get it to play.  I sent it back to Grace Digital (at my expense) and they promptly replaced it. I do commend Grace Digital's tech support - they were very communicative and one rep told me she had my replacement unit playing for an hour on her desk just to make sure it worked.The Mondo's controls feel "cheap" compared to those of the Squeezebox Radio, and the buttons sometimes are unresponsive.  For example, to set a station memory you push and hold one of the memory buttons. (The Mondo has 10 memory positions with a "shift", the Squeezebox Radio has 6.)  The manual says that you will see an indication on the screen that the station was saved, but, except for a brief flash once, I don't get this.  It did save the station, however.  There is a single button that serves as pause and play, but often it is ignored and the music just keeps playing.  There's a button with the square "stop" icon on it, but when playing a stream, it just gives an error message.  The sound quality isn't bad, but the Logitech's is noticeably better, with more bass and better "presence".If I didn't have a Logitech Squeezebox Radio to compare it to, I'd perhaps think better of the Grace Digital Mondo.  It is by no means a bad product, but it is mediocre, hampered further by firmware glitches (which might get ironed out - both products have the ability to auto-update over the Internet.)  But as it is, I find the Mondo a poor runner-up to the Squeezebox Radio. If you account for having to buy a remote control for the Logitech (if you want one, that is), the two products cost about the same.  My recommendation would favor the Logitech.
reviewText_clean: Pros:+ Includes remote control+ Uses DLNA for local network playback+ Built-in weather app+ USB inputCons:- Controls often unresponsive- No WiFi Protected Setup- Won't play Apple Lossless .m4a filesThe Grace Digital "Mondo" is clearly an attempt to copy the popularLogitech Squeezebox Radio. The two products are very similar in size, shape and configuration, right down to the handle recess in the back. The Mondo is an inch taller and wider than the Squeezebox Radio, but close enough. Both have a color LCD screen, large rubberized knob that pushes in for selection and buttons for favorite stations.There are some physical differences: the Mondo has a separate volume control knob that sticks out the top, which when pushed mutes the audio, whereas the Logitech has its volume/mute knob on the front. The Mondo also has a snooze/sleep-timer button on top for the alarm function - while the Logitech can also serve as an alarm clock, it has no dedicated snooze button.There are some differences in the Mondo's favor. A significant one is that, unlike the Squeezebox, it can play from any DLNA server on your network without the need to run a dedicated server program. I keep my music on aNETGEAR ReadyNAS Ultra 4 Plus Network Attached Storage Boxand it operates as a DLNA server. However, a Squeezebox Server program is also available for it so this advantage is muted for me. (And no, I didn't mean "mooted", though I suppose that also applies.) However, if you don't have a DLNA server on your network, you'll need to run one. There are many free servers available for various platforms. Recent versions of Windows Media Player have this capability.Unfortunately for me, the Mondo will not play Apple Lossless high-bitrate .m4a files. It sees them, but when you ask it to play they are just skipped over. This is not just a DLNA issue as the Mondo won't play them from a USB stick either. The Squeezebox Radio will play them, however. Luckily I don't have a lot of those, but I have been choosing that format for ripping CDs recently and that shuts them out of playback on the Mondo. [After my initial review was posted, Grace Digital said that they would add Apple Lossless support in the future.]Another annoyance is the method of entering the wireless network password. The Logitech Squeezebox Radio supports Wi-Fi Protected Setup (WPS), where you push a button on your router (and select an option on the Radio) and the wireless information is exchanged automatically. The Mondo makes you enter the password manually by scrolling through the characters one by one.Both products share a wealth of features. Of course they'll both play Internet Radio and have searchable and categorized lists of stations. Both can identify "local" stations with streaming broadcasts. Both can access a variety of services such as Pandora, SiriusXM, last.fm and many more. Both can serve as clock-radios, have adjustable dimmable displays and both support WiFi connectivity. The Mondo will also support wired Ethernet if you buy an optional USB adapter, but the Squeezebox Radio has an Ethernet jack built in. Both let you do some customization on a web site and both offer smartphone apps that can control a box on your local network.The Mondo includes an infrared remote control; Logitech makes you buy that separately. The Mondo also comes with a stereo line-out cord for connecting to a hi-fi system - the Squeezebox Radio does not have line out capability. Both include a 1/8" stereo phone jack for connecting an iPod or other music player. You can get an optional rechargeable battery for the Squeezebox Radio - the Mondo has a compartment for one (at least that's what I think it is) on the underside, but Grace Digital doesn't list one for sale that I can see and there is no mention in the manual. (Edit: Grace Digital informs me that a battery is now available.)So what is the Mondo like to use? Frustrating. The first unit I received played fine - for about 15 seconds. Then it went mute. A power cycle brought it back for another 15 seconds, but after that nothing I did could get it to play. I sent it back to Grace Digital (at my expense) and they promptly replaced it. I do commend Grace Digital's tech support - they were very communicative and one rep told me she had my replacement unit playing for an hour on her desk just to make sure it worked.The Mondo's controls feel "cheap" compared to those of the Squeezebox Radio, and the buttons sometimes are unresponsive. For example, to set a station memory you push and hold one of the memory buttons. (The Mondo has 10 memory positions with a "shift", the Squeezebox Radio has 6.) The manual says that you will see an indication on the screen that the station was saved, but, except for a brief flash once, I don't get this. It did save the station, however. There is a single button that serves as pause and play, but often it is ignored and the music just keeps playing. There's a button with the square "stop" icon on it, but when playing a stream, it just gives an error message. The sound quality isn't bad, but the Logitech's is noticeably better, with more bass and better "presence".If I didn't have a Logitech Squeezebox Radio to compare it to, I'd perhaps think better of the Grace Digital Mondo. It is by no means a bad product, but it is mediocre, hampered further by firmware glitches (which might get ironed out - both products have the ability to auto-update over the Internet.) But as it is, I find the Mondo a poor runner-up to the Squeezebox Radio. If you account for having to buy a remote control for the Logitech (if you want one, that is), the two products cost about the same. My recommendation would favor the Logitech.

reviewText: I bought the T3i after carefully comparing a number of similar cameras from Nikon and other manufacturers.  I've been totally happy with the camera and the rest of the package.  There are plenty of reviews of the camera itself, so I'll just comment on this entire bundle.  The lens is sharp and easy to use.  I would like to have more f-stop ranges, but that gets expensive no matter who makes the lens, and this one is a good balance of cost/performance.  The bag is excellent quality.  The tripod is a bit flimsy - I'll get a heavier-duty one eventually, but this one works fairly well.  The 16GB card works well for me - I download my photos after every session and clear the card, so I never come close to filling it up.  The DVD is a decent introduction to digital SLRs for newbies.  I recommend that you get a book dedicated to using the T3i.  The manual tells you what the buttons do, but it doesn't tell you why you would want to use them.  I bought the David Busch guide to T3i's and can recommend it as a great way to learn what this wonderful camera can do.
summary: Far more capability than the average consumer will ever use

reviewText: I don't know what it is with built in card readers on computers, but they always seem to be the very first thing to wear out on them. Just last summer I bought another brand new desktop PC, and this summer my built in card reader stopped recognizing cards when I would insert them. This seems to be about the luck I've had in the past with other built in card readers as well. They work a year or so, then one day they just don't recognize the SD cards being plugged in anymore. That's where this memory card reader comes in.I use both SD and Micro SD cards for my different cameras, and this reader has slots for both. So I don't need to use a Micro SD card adapter to download my files from the card to my PC. It plugs into it's own slot just like the full size card does. So to download your files, you plug the USB end of this reader into an open USB port on your computer, wait for your system to recognize it (when doing this for the very first time, your computer will automatically install any needed hardware drivers), then once it's ready to be used, plug your memory card into the correct slot. It's just like using a built in card reader on your computer, except that it's going through your USB port to download the data.I've used cards as small as 2GB with it and I regularly use my 16GB HC card with it, and it recognizes it without any problems. It's the perfect solution for downloading your photos from your memory cards when your built in card reader stops working!
summary: When your card reader stops working on your computer, this is what you need

SDHC is an extension of the original SD standard that enables capacities greater than 2 GB. It uses the same physical form factor as SD, but SDHC cards only work in SDHC compatible devices. Some cameras require a high speed card to be able to record video smoothly or capture multiple still photographs in rapid succession. Standard SD cards work in both SD and SDHC devices (backward compatible).Enjoy Faster Transfer SpeedsBasic SD cards transfer data up to six times (6x) the data rate of the standard CD-ROM speed (900 kB/s). Transcend SDHC class 6 cards offer a minimum of 6 MB/s write speeds under the most demanding storage conditions. Some cameras require a high speed card to be able to record video smoothly or capture multiple still photographs in rapid succession. Check your device for maximum compatibility for your intended usage patterns.FeaturesFully compatible with SD 2.0 StandardsSDHC Class 6 compliantCompatible with all SDHC-labeled host devices (not compatible with standard SD)Easy to use, plug-and-play operationBuilt-in Error Correcting Code (ECC) to detect and correct transfer errorsComplies with Secure Digital Music Initiative (SDMI) portable device requirementsSupports Content Protection for Recordable Media (CPRM)Allows In System Programming (ISP) for updating firmwareSupports auto-standby, power-off and sleep modesMechanical write-protection switchRoHS compliantLifetime WarrantyEnsure Your Device is SDHC CompatibleSDHC devices can use both older SD cards and SDHC (high capacity) cards. However older cameras and other devices that were released before the SDHC standard may not support the new SDHC cards. Please check your device documentation to verify compatibility before purchase. If your device is fairly new or states support for 4 GB or greater SD cards, then you already have SDHC support.Digital Camera Storage Capacity TableMemory cards should be purchased according to how high the resolution or DPI (dots per inch) of your digital camera is (i.e. how many megapixels it has), and how many pictures you plan on taking at a time. Transcend has provided the following graph to assist you in buying an appropriate capacity card for your camera:Storage CapacityCamera Type / Approximate Number of Pictures2 MP3 MP4 MP5 MP6 MP8 MP10 MP4 GB4550341220481638128010488168 GB9100682440963276256020961632*The "File size" represented here assumes that the highest resolution (DPI) your camera supports is used and that pictures are stored in standard JPEG format. The actual number of pictures you can take will vary depending on your digital camera's resolution and compression settings, composition (complexity) of the images taken, as well as lighting and exposure factors.

reviewText: This product arrived quickly. I found the enclosed instructions difficult to understand, but was able to find a PDF file on-line with clearer and more complete instructions, and those instructions were very helpful.With the instructions in hand, programming is relatively straight forward, although not intuitive. I needed to manually enter many blocked numbers because I had them documented from when I had "selective call blocking" from Cox - a service I am now able to cancel and save a monthly fee!In order to program in these numbers, it's necessary to have a phone hooked up directly to the Blocker and the Blocker hooked up to a live phone line.The only issue with this is that to get into the programming mode, you must be attached to a live phone line and the dial tone - which means that in the process of programming, you are actually dialing numbers! This could result in inadvertently calling numbers you don't want to call. This is an annoyance, but not a show-stopper.If you have answered (picked up) a call and determined you don't want to hear from that number again, it's easy to just push one button on the Blocker to add that number to the blocked list. But like most people, I have many phones in the house, and the chances that I am at the phone with the Blocker attached is very small. No worries. After hanging up from the undesired call, you just use the left-right buttons on the Blocker to call up the Caller ID of the offending call, then press the BLOCK button.I also followed the instructions to automatically block all "out of area" or PRIVATE or UNKNOWN incoming calls.I've now seen the product successfully block several "out of area" calls; the phone rings once (during the initial period it takes to send through the Caller ID), and then the call is blocked - no more rings.It's also possible to program blocking all calls from certain area codes. For example, lots of political calls come from Washington, DC, so you could block all area code 202 incoming calls. Of course then you'd miss that important follow-up contact from the President! I haven't used this feature, but based on the unit's performance, I trust it works.It also can block outgoing calls. Having only two relatively mature adults in my house, this is a solution in search of a problem, but if you had kids this might be a feature.Removing blocked numbers is quite easy (with the downloaded instructions).I believe the folks who gave this unfavorable ratings fall into one of three categories:1) They might be on a phone provider not compatible with this device. I didn't have that problem, so it wasn't an issue for me.2) They might have gotten frustrated trying to program the device. Even though I consider myself reasonably tech-savvy, the programming wasn't a no-brainer, and I understand that many people would have given up in frustration.3) They may have received a defective device. This is cheaply made, mass-produced item and I wouldn't be at all surprised if many people did actually receive defective units. I was lucky and got a good one.But if you receive a working unit, if it works with your phone provider, and if you have the patience to program it, it does what it promises.So in short -+ It works!- It's a bit kluge-y to programOverall, this is a big hit in my household, and as an added bonus it is saving us the former monthly "selective call blocking" fee I used to pay to Cox, my internet and phone service provider.
summary: So far, it works great, but non-intuitive interface makes it a tad unfriendly to program

The Rokinon 85mm lens is made with mostly glass and aluminum components and the build quality is superb. Its focusing is silky smooth with an internal focusing (IF) mechanism so that the physical size remains constant during focusing. There are little or no chromatic aberrations and Bokeh is just about perfect. The lens comes complete with a removable lens hood, lens caps, lens pouch, instruction manual and one year warranty. The lens is available in the following mounts: Canon, Nikon, Pentax, Sony & Olympus 4/3. reviewText: I bought a new UV5R from Etekcity but received a used UV5R radio. I received a used one with both front labels scratched up beyond what could have been caused incidentally from shipping, even with the radio packed in tight as if it were new. It's apparent the radio had been used and laid face down a few times on a hard surface which caused the scratching on the two front plastic labels. I'm not bothering with refund or exchange since the radio seems to work OK. Minus one star for receiving a used radio.

reviewText: Disclosure: I was contacted by Brainwavz and asked if I would like to receive a product in exchange for a review.  They decided on the product; I promised a fair and honest review in exchange.First of all, is it supposed to come across as "brain waves?"  I think that's what they're after, but phonetically it's incorrect, the pronunciation actually "brain wavs."  Sorry, that's just the niggling editor and linguist in me.In the box: a small hard case in a snappy red and black and inside the ear buds, an airline adapter (nice), a small bag with 7 additional pairs of differently sized earphone tips (silicone, bi-flange, tri-flange, etc.), and a separate baggie of one pair of Comply(tm) "premium" isolation memory foam tips.Out of the box it's a nice picture, the full set in the case.  The hard case is nice, and holds everything well, with two elastic inside pockets for storage of extra gear.  And it's even got a double zipper, so you can zip north or south, up or down, whatever zippin' direction you choose, even both at once!The memory foam tips are like squishablefoam earplugs; you squish them down and insert them in your ear canal, and their slow expansion fits them snugly into place while blocking outside noise.  This is a good concept but in my experience in testing these with the earbuds, it didn't work too well, at first.  The foam squishes down just fine, but by the time you've got left and right figured out, the earbud oriented correctly, the cord snaked up and over your ear with the bud aimed right for a correct fit, the bud tip is already foamed back out, which kind of defeats the intent of getting it in while it's squished down.  And you start over.  I'll admit that after a few awkward tries I got the fit pretty much right, and I did detect a significant lessening of external sound with these memory foam bud tips in use.  No, they did not block all sound, not even close, but compared to the rubber/silicone tips they block much more outside sound.The cord, coming in at 1.3m (51.2") is an interesting flat design, much like wide fettuccine.  It's got a wide split for the buds, plenty of room to get around your face and head, with a little slider that can tighten it up for you if snug is what you're after.I do have one niggling observation: the L/R indicators.  Usually you find the "L" on that one end, and you're all set.  It took me some dedicated inspection to detect that "L," a tiny, and I do mean really teeny-tiny little mark in the molded plastic of the earbud frame (check it out in the main product image).  And it's not in a contrasting color; it's the same color as the plastic it's molded into.  I recommend a slight change to make it easier to find that "L."The earbuds themselves feel good, a good metal feel in your hand, not some feather-light plastic.  The feel hefty, which implies quality.Performance: I own a pair of Sennheiser HD 570s, so I'm into headphone sound.  And these were impressive from the outset.  Excellent sound reproduction across the entire spectrum.  The box promises "rich details," and I agree fully.  They promise "deep bass," and I also concur.  I thought the bass response was particularly good, with good bottom-end thrum and pop, but not overshadowing the mids and high end.  Treble response is also excellent, with all manner of traditional and modern jazz coming through beautifully, brushwork very clear and distinct.  The Talking Heads' original "Born Under Punches" was a test song, and was absolutely delightful.Sound separation was very good, with the sound visually centered inside my head, not one side or the other.Safety note: with all earbud tips in I was more than able to hear my surroundings, even with the buds at very high volume.  While it's never a good idea to ride or bike or run with buds or phones in, these do allow the outside to come in, somewhat.I note that for this sound to come through these have to be properly fitted and snug in your ears.  It took me a few tries with the different earbud tips to finally get it right and have the sound to its full potential.  Make sure you get the fit perfect with these; once you do you'll get that great sound coming through.Documentation: the only documentation is a single card, one side being the one-year warranty card and the other side being the instruction manual.  Okay, they're earbuds; there's just not that much instruction to give for this kind of product.  One of the true gems: "do not cut the cable."  Now that's some valuable instruction.Price: After testing these buds, I think the price for this product is in keeping with its performance and my assessment of its quality.  You are getting what you're paying for.Bottom line: I've tested a few of these in the last few years, and so far these are the best I've come across.  They are well made, offer a wide range of fit options, and produce some really good sound, clear and distinct and solid.
reviewText_clean: Disclosure: I was contacted by Brainwavz and asked if I would like to receive a product in exchange for a review. They decided on the product; I promised a fair and honest review in exchange.First of all, is it supposed to come across as "brain waves?" I think that's what they're after, but phonetically it's incorrect, the pronunciation actually "brain wavs." Sorry, that's just the niggling editor and linguist in me.In the box: a small hard case in a snappy red and black and inside the ear buds, an airline adapter (nice), a small bag with 7 additional pairs of differently sized earphone tips (silicone, bi-flange, tri-flange, etc.), and a separate baggie of one pair of Comply(tm) "premium" isolation memory foam tips.Out of the box it's a nice picture, the full set in the case. The hard case is nice, and holds everything well, with two elastic inside pockets for storage of extra gear. And it's even got a double zipper, so you can zip north or south, up or down, whatever zippin' direction you choose, even both at once!The memory foam tips are like squishablefoam earplugs; you squish them down and insert them in your ear canal, and their slow expansion fits them snugly into place while blocking outside noise. This is a good concept but in my experience in testing these with the earbuds, it didn't work too well, at first. The foam squishes down just fine, but by the time you've got left and right figured out, the earbud oriented correctly, the cord snaked up and over your ear with the bud aimed right for a correct fit, the bud tip is already foamed back out, which kind of defeats the intent of getting it in while it's squished down. And you start over. I'll admit that after a few awkward tries I got the fit pretty much right, and I did detect a significant lessening of external sound with these memory foam bud tips in use. No, they did not block all sound, not even close, but compared to the rubber/silicone tips they block much more outside sound.The cord, coming in at 1.3m (51.2") is an interesting flat design, much like wide fettuccine. It's got a wide split for the buds, plenty of room to get around your face and head, with a little slider that can tighten it up for you if snug is what you're after.I do have one niggling observation: the L/R indicators. Usually you find the "L" on that one end, and you're all set. It took me some dedicated inspection to detect that "L," a tiny, and I do mean really teeny-tiny little mark in the molded plastic of the earbud frame (check it out in the main product image). And it's not in a contrasting color; it's the same color as the plastic it's molded into. I recommend a slight change to make it easier to find that "L."The earbuds themselves feel good, a good metal feel in your hand, not some feather-light plastic. The feel hefty, which implies quality.Performance: I own a pair of Sennheiser HD 570s, so I'm into headphone sound. And these were impressive from the outset. Excellent sound reproduction across the entire spectrum. The box promises "rich details," and I agree fully. They promise "deep bass," and I also concur. I thought the bass response was particularly good, with good bottom-end thrum and pop, but not overshadowing the mids and high end. Treble response is also excellent, with all manner of traditional and modern jazz coming through beautifully, brushwork very clear and distinct. The Talking Heads' original "Born Under Punches" was a test song, and was absolutely delightful.Sound separation was very good, with the sound visually centered inside my head, not one side or the other.Safety note: with all earbud tips in I was more than able to hear my surroundings, even with the buds at very high volume. While it's never a good idea to ride or bike or run with buds or phones in, these do allow the outside to come in, somewhat.I note that for this sound to come through these have to be properly fitted and snug in your ears. It took me a few tries with the different earbud tips to finally get it right and have the sound to its full potential. Make sure you get the fit perfect with these; once you do you'll get that great sound coming through.Documentation: the only documentation is a single card, one side being the one-year warranty card and the other side being the instruction manual. Okay, they're earbuds; there's just not that much instruction to give for this kind of product. One of the true gems: "do not cut the cable." Now that's some valuable instruction.Price: After testing these buds, I think the price for this product is in keeping with its performance and my assessment of its quality. You are getting what you're paying for.Bottom line: I've tested a few of these in the last few years, and so far these are the best I've come across. They are well made, offer a wide range of fit options, and produce some really good sound, clear and distinct and solid.

reviewText: Really, this is a 5 star product with 10 star customer service from Cheetah Mounts.This cable is high quality with gold ends and full audio return capabilities. It will definitely hold up for many years of use. Being such a strong cable, it is a bit difficult to "twist" and hide behind things. Ah, this is where the included Velcro straps do help. This kit includes a right angle (90) adapter for better installation if needed. An added bonus (not mentioned in description) is this kit also includes a TV/monitor microfiber cleaning cloth and a little LED lighted key chain.For me, a 20' cable would have been 10 stars. After inquiring if a 20' cable was available, Cheetah Mounts customer service contacted me directly to apologize that they do not have a 20' cable and wish they could have accommodated me more fully. Again, 10 star customer service!

reviewText: This is about the size of an iphone 4. It doesn't come with a case, which it should, so I cut out the square recessed area of plastic that it came in, and I store it in there with a rubber band around it.  Also, I would have better leverage if I had a small handle to clasp, rather than having to scrunch my hands over the flat surface.IPAD 2--Adequately removes dust and smudges, but not as quickly or easily as my microfiber cloth. Doesn't remove the little crud areas at all, though.MAC BOOK PRO (2010)--Adequately removes dust, but not very well at removing smudges. Does not remove crud.TV SCREEN-- 51" Mitsubishi, circa 2009. Adequately removes dust, quasi-removal of smudges.LG PHONE (not a Smartphone)--Useless on this screenFinal evaluation: I don't see the point, really, of switching from my microfiber cloth (even without the wet solution) to the iEraser, because the iEraser takes up more room transporting, it doesn't have a case, and it is more awkward to use--and takes more time.I think this is a case of creating a market that isn't there, convincing buyers that we need it, when we don't. If this did a swifter and better job than a cloth, I'd probably buy it, with the caveat of it including a case.

reviewText: This product is designed to remove fingerprints and smudges, if you never clean any of your devices and smear your breakfast on them every morning then don't expect miracles. Microfiber cloth and special spray will work better on those issues but for daily clean up of your phone, your laptop screen, tablet etc. this will work, it's a fun little product that will take care of most screen issues. It works well in combination with the cloth you can get at an eye store or computer store to get a deeper clean if you're cleaning a large TV screen for example, overall it's a good item to have, I use it daily to prevent buildup and it only takes a few seconds to slide through each screen I'm using.
summary: Good little item for screen maintenance

reviewText: Wow, we were really impressed with this device.  We wanted to replicate our TV (media) signal in the kitchen on a 24" LCD monitor and this delivered with flying colors.What we like:- Extremely clear signal.- Easy Setup! (EASY, Under 10 mins for even non tech types)- Smallish/unobtrusive.- DOESN'T HOG OR IMPEDE WIFI SIGNAL (I can't stress this one enough)Room for improvement:- Signal occasionally cuts out a bit, and that's only from one room away.  Could be worse from farther apart.- Kind of cheesy looking, design features were meh.- Could use an IR repeater/blaster in the back since it can block signals from the DVR/Cable remote.- Short power cord.4.5 Stars, rounding down since there's still room for a bit of improvement.  Highly recommended.

reviewText: Oh my goodness, I love this thing! I've used three different regular cases, a mini bluetooth keyboard, and a keyboard/case combo. I did not expect this to be vastly different from the other keyboard case that I tried.First of all, this is a hard case. It does not flex. The other keyboard case that I tried was rigid/stiff, but it could flex a tiny bit. That means that when closed, part of the keyboard could make contact with the iPad screen. Maybe that's nothing, but I don't like anything that isn't soft touching the iPad's screen. This case was built with close tolerances. When closed, the keyboard comes very close to the screen, but does not touch it. If you hold it up to the light, you can see the tiny separation. If you don't believe your eyes, you will find that you can slide a sheet of paper between the keyboard and iPad when the case is closed.The bluetooth syncing/linking was easy. Also, there is no physical switch to turn the keyboard off and on like there was on my other keyboard case. The keypad is engaged when the keyboard is in one of its three possible reclining positions. The case magnetically "snaps" into one of the three reclining positions. Snap it out and bluetooth goes off. No more worrying that you forgot to turn off the bluetooth switch.There are two trade-offs. A trade-off is not a flaw. It is a feature whose existence means that something else is necessarily lost or diminished. For some, trade-offs are good, and for others not so good. For me, both trade-offs are good.Trade-off #1: The sound deflector over the speakers directs sound toward the user. It amplifies it a little and also makes it quieter for those who are not in front of the device. A larger deflector (including your own cupped palm) does the job better, but then it would look ugly and get in the way. I prefer a deflector that does a moderate job but is unobtrusive and looks good. That's better than one that works great but looks like a bullhorn stuck on your case.Trade-off #2: The case is not hinged. That means it does not open predictably like a book. The two portions of this case are "tethered" together by a strong, wide, and thin material. This makes it easier for butterfingers to fumble with, but it allows the case to do something that a hinged case cannot do. You can flip the keyboard section in back of the iPad section with the keys facing away from you or toward you. In this configuration, the sections are "stacked". It's like folding a magazine so that the rest of the magazine is behind the page you are reading. But a magazine is hinged. The part folded back is always facing away from you. Another way to say it is that you can flip the keyboard directly behind and parallel to the iPad, with the keys facing away from or toward the iPad. I much prefer the keys to be facing toward the iPad. That way, my fingers are contacting the smooth outer case instead of the keys on the keyboard. Bravo. I like this tethering feature, even if it does require one to be a little more careful.How about the feel of the keyboard? No complaints.Scratching? I tend to treat my electronic stuff with care. But I'm not a fanatic about it. I do a normal amount of sliding it around (metal side down) on tables and such. There is no scratching that I can see.While in the library using my iPad to do word processing with Pages 09, I felt like taking a break and browsing a bit. I wondered if I could stand it up in portrait orientation. I expected it to utterly fail as it was not designed to do this. But much to my delight, it can stand up on its side. Sure, it stands vertically (can't tilt the screen), but I tend to slink down in my chair when I relax so it was no problem!Finally, this case looks good. It looks cool. It's slimmer than even the non-keyboard cases I've used. The smooth finish and the perfect way it mates up with the iPad is something to admire. I have an urge to show it off. OK, it's more than just an urge - I show it off whenever the I get the chance :-)

The keypad is engaged when the keyboard is in one of its three possible reclining positions. The case magnetically "snaps" into one of the three reclining positions. Snap it out and bluetooth goes off. No more worrying that you forgot to turn off the bluetooth switch.There are two trade-offs. A trade-off is not a flaw. It is a feature whose existence means that something else is necessarily lost or diminished. For some, trade-offs are good, and for others not so good. For me, both trade-offs are good.Trade-off #1: The sound deflector over the speakers directs sound toward the user. It amplifies it a little and also makes it quieter for those who are not in front of the device. A larger deflector (including your own cupped palm) does the job better, but then it would look ugly and get in the way. I prefer a deflector that does a moderate job but is unobtrusive and looks good. That's better than one that works great but looks like a bullhorn stuck on your case.Trade-off #2: The case is not hinged. That means it does not open predictably like a book. The two portions of this case are "tethered" together by a strong, wide, and thin material. This makes it easier for butterfingers to fumble with, but it allows the case to do something that a hinged case cannot do. You can flip the keyboard section in back of the iPad section with the keys facing away from you or toward you. In this configuration, the sections are "stacked". It's like folding a magazine so that the rest of the magazine is behind the page you are reading. But a magazine is hinged. The part folded back is always facing away from you. Another way to say it is that you can flip the keyboard directly behind and parallel to the iPad, with the keys facing away from or toward the iPad. I much prefer the keys to be facing toward the iPad. That way, my fingers are contacting the smooth outer case instead of the keys on the keyboard. Bravo. I like this tethering feature, even if it does require one to be a little more careful.How about the feel of the keyboard? No complaints.Scratching? I tend to treat my electronic stuff with care. But I'm not a fanatic about it. I do a normal amount of sliding it around (metal side down) on tables and such. There is no scratching that I can see.While in the library using my iPad to do word processing with Pages 09, I felt like taking a break and browsing a bit. I wondered if I could stand it up in portrait orientation. I expected it to utterly fail as it was not designed to do this. But much to my delight, it can stand up on its side. Sure, it stands vertically (can't tilt the screen), but I tend to slink down in my chair when I relax so it was no problem!Finally, this case looks good. It looks cool. It's slimmer than even the non-keyboard cases I've used. The smooth finish and the perfect way it mates up with the iPad is something to admire. I have an urge to show it off. OK, it's more than just an urge - I show it off whenever the I get the chance :-)
title_clean: Belkin QODE Ultimate Wireless Keyboard and Case for iPad 2, 3rd Gen and 4th Gen with Retina Display
product_text: Belkin QODE Ultimate Wireless Keyboard and Case for iPad 2, 3rd Gen and 4th Gen with Retina Display

reviewText: I received this DVD recorder for Christmas 2009.  It was the one I had researched and requested.  It was available at Walmart for around $250.  I wanted something that was just the digital version of a VCR.  I watch OTA tv signals and needed something to record to a DVD.  I needed something that I can save sporting events and transfer to my computer for formatting to an external hard drive.  The process is somewhat cumbersome and takes a while.  But since I am only interested in sports then it's worth the effort.  I have no need or interest to save regular programming to a DVD.I do not take advantage of all its features nor do I notice all of its shortcomings.  I really don't watch any tv shows regularly, except sports and news (which is why I don't subscribe to cable either).We do record on occasion regular shows, but delete them shortly after viewing them (my wife only has to watch any reality show once - in my case NEVER).  Anyways I have saved movies for months if not over a year to be viewed later, or even reviewed if its a good movie.  I'm starting to run out of space, so now I'm recording the good movies onto DVD's.Don't really care about an integrated tv guide, that's what our ipod apps are for.  I like the simplicity of it and probably under use its functions and abilities.  It plays every DVD I've ever stuck in it.  I actually will use this player to play all our DVD's because our other Sony 5 DVD player cannot play burned DVD's.Only negative is it records in standard def and on a big screen that is noticeable, the quality is good not great.  I do not know of any HD recorder that can save recordings easily to a computer.  DVD's are cheap, slingbox is not.  That feature alone puts this above all the HD recorders out there.
summary: Digital OTA Capable - MAGNAVOX H2160MW9 HDD and DVD Recorder

reviewText: The Belkin anti-static wrist band offers a decent level of quality for the price.this wrist band is approx. 18" in length when fully coiled, and approx. 4 feet in length when fully stretched.the velcro is of high quality and secures firmly to your wrist.the velcro strap is a bit short in length (9.5") - yet it still fits okay.there is a swivel connector that allows for more free movement while maneuvering.that swivel connector is attached by a button snap that functions as a quick release (sort of).while the alligator clip opens approx. 1/2", it'll only securely fasten to metal objects that are 3/8" thick or less.the alligator clip is detachable and is secured by a pressure clip.
summary: decent quality w/ some little extras

description_clean: Performing maintenance or upgrades inside your computer? Belkin's anti-static wrist band (part number F8E093) provides reliable static control and 360-degree protection--a simple but important safeguard against computer-killing static electricity. Just slip it around your wrist and affix its rugged alligator clip to any bare metal surface and you're protected--with two hands and one easy mind ready for work. The Velcro wrist band adjusts to varying sizes, and the attached self-coiling grounding cord grants freedom to move and freedom from tangles.

reviewText: Update as of 3/30/2013The device has been malfunctioning with it being very difficult to catch a GPS signal.  In doing a recent update for the latest the maps, the device "bricked" and has been rendered useless.  I have been unable to load the maps and the existing maps were lost.  Now as the device is out of warranty, TomTom is unable to help.  I am working with Visa (since it was purchased with the Amazon card and warranties are extended by 1 year) for a possible repair or replacement.  I did initially like this device due to the high end features you get for the low price, but its unreliability and now breakdown makes it a device that should not be bought.Update as of 8/12/2011There has been a couple of software updates for this device which makes the device more reliable...I do now notice that bluetooth calling clarity has improved a bit, directions with traffic is calculated faster and lastly voice recognition has greatly improved.  It was unfortunate that TomTom initially released a buggy device, but they are fixing it, so the first thing that everyone should do with this device after getting it, is to update the software.The TomTom Via series of GPS Navigators replace an aging line of TomTom One derived models.  The Via adopts the "new look" maps and interface as adopted from the Go series navigators which sell for well over $200 and adopts much of their features too (like traffic, bluetooth, voice recognition, etc).I've never owned a Garmin device so I am not able to compare it to one...but I'm a loyal TomTom user with this being my 3rd navigator in 5 years.Let's start with the mount.  This is the first TomTom navigator to have a functional mount.  My two previous models TomTom XL and TomTom One 140S featured mounts that kept on falling off the windshield, beanbag mount or the dashboard ring disc.  I ultimately had to purchase 3rd party mounts which then worked flawlessly.  This particular model has the suction cup mount built in to the device and is not removable (thus a 3rd party mount will not work).  However the suction cup mount attaches perfectly to my windshield or ring disc and seems to be able to stick (except for a couple times where I probably didn't tighten it enough).  And also this device has no upside down or rightside up...it will work in any direction as the screen always flips to the correct position.The first thing most users do with a GPS Navigator is install updated maps and software.  TomTom users may be familiar with the TomTom Home program...but this and other newer devices do not work with that software.  It uses the MyTomTom software, which runs within a web browser.  There's very few things you can do with the program...pretty much all you can do is download updates.  Other users seemed to have fits with downloading/installing updates and also entering in the lifetime map update code.  I had no such problem.  Updated software and maps were quickly installed in one try (took about an hour) and I was able to enter the code (and confirmed with TomTom that it was set-up on my device).  So as of now, problems with updating and entering code must have been resolved.Next is the quality of maps and interface.  Everything is much improved from the previous iteration.  Maps look modern (rather than cartoonish) the status bar is slick and the setting/menus are less cluttered.  Again I can't compare to Garmin but I always found TomTom's interface and maps to be good and the new look is even better than the old.The voice recognition system is pretty limited but for entering addresses, I found it pretty accurate.  Turn off your radio and speak in the address clearly before mounting the navigator...then it should work fine.  There are other commands you can use while driving, but much are unnecessary.  I concur with others complaining how slow the list of cities get displayed when inputting by hand...there definite is some lag time, but not too bad.  As for the talking voice...there is only one voice (default) that is able to read out all the street names.  Custom and other voices (like Darth Vader/Homer Simpson will not support reading street names) and as of now it appears like MyTomTom doesn't support adding new voices.  This device's voice certainly reads much better than previous models.  Unlike my 140S which used to read 405 and 105 as 4 WEST 5 and 1 WEST 5, this device speaks properly and its pronunciation of most cities are correct.Satellite Capture & Directions...most of the the time a satellite will be locked in within 45-90 seconds on average, slightly faster than older models and on par with others.  Quality of directions...due to the IQ Routes feature, sometimes it'll try and be a little too cute and fancy and direct you through residential streets for a strip mall that is located on a big street.  The directions aren't wrong but are a bit obscure at times.  But for the most part it will find you the best route.  And also it tells you if the business is on the left or the right, which is very helpful (something previous TomToms did not do).Traffic...the traffic monitor is a godsend for those living in high-traffic areas like LA as the device will direct you to the best route based on traffic.  Those heading east and west from and to Los Angeles have many choices (5, 60, 10, 210) freeways.  This will accurately tell you which one is best to take.  Also it constantly monitors the traffic at all times and updates your estimate time of arrival and if traffic gets too bad, it could redirect you.  You could also direct the device to redirect you.  The traffic antenna is built in on the power DC cable, so running on battery or a 3rd party cable will disable this feature.  This feature is a bit slow at times, and can keep the device preoccupied for like 5 minutes...wish it had a faster processor.Bluetooth...I bought the 1435 over the 1405 because of bluetooth.  It was set-up very easily with my phone (Samsung Focus).  It should work fine with most modern phones like Samsung Galaxy S derived phones, iPhone, blackberries, etc.  Some older and cheaper phones may not work, so check with TomTom before buying.  It easily connected, imported my phonebook and is able to call out, receive calls and text messages while on.  The sound isn't crystal clear...but I can hear them but they can't always hear me.  This is where I'm taking away a star from the review.Appearance/Display...the device is very attractive looking with a metallic-like finish.  I prefer the 4.3" over the 5" (bigger is not always better) but older people with bad vision may want to go with the 5".  The display is by no means high-def and can be very difficult to see during strong sunlight.  But it's very easy on the eyes and is crisply visible at most times (always during nights).  As with most GPS navigators, the touch response can be annoying (resistive display versus capacative of smartphones).  You may have to tap the screen multiple times to get a reaction, so try pressing firmly and on the proper spot.  Also when picking businesses from a list, it may take several presses to pick.  This is the same annoying thing that applies to all TomToms.  This device's list of businesses is pretty impressive, even obscure small businesses were found.  And with lifetime free updates, this database gets updated quarterly alongside the maps.Advanced Lane Guidance...this is a feature that you can't live without.  It tells you which lane you should be in to stay on the existing freeway or to junction into a new one.  It will warn you by voice and visually by mimicking road signs and also with arrows.  Love it.Remember this is not a $300 or $400 device, don't expect the world...reviewers apparently want a GPS device to be a smartphone.  But for the price it currently sells for, I'd be hard pressed to find another navigator that has more features and is as modern as this one.  Garmin's equivalent models are a bit dated...released 2009, so I'd go with the Via if you want the latest device under $200.Pros:  Lifetime map updates (save $50 a year/$70 per one-time update) and Lifetime traffic (no subscription fees), bluetooth, voice recognition, advanced lane guidance, iq routes and premium maps/interface.Cons:  Touchscreen is sometimes not too responsive...may have to keep pushing, display is pretty low def, sometimes gives obscure directions, satellite lock could be faster, MyTomTom software could implement more features.  Power button needs to be held on to for a couple of seconds to work and suffers from a lag (in turning off and on)...not a big issue but appears to be annoy a lot of users.  The device also has a tendency to sometimes ask you to stay on the right, and then make you make a left turn soon after...hopefully this gets fixed in a future update.

reviewText: I bought the Genius SW-G2.1 1250 speakers as a replacement for some Logitech S120's, which I'd purchased on the fly, so to speak, in a kind of "emergency" situation.  The S120's were pretty decent speakers for $10, but just didn't cut it for any truly "serious" listening to music, movies, etc.  I really didn't expect much out a pair of $50 speakers, either, but again, I really just needed some speakers to get me by that were a step up from the Logitech.  After reading some promising reviews as well as some highly critical reviews, I decided to go ahead and take a chance with the 1250's.  Am I ever glad I did!  These little things are outstanding for their price point!  Just bear in mind, you are NOT going to be getting the equivalent of a $300+ set of speakers here.  You are getting $50 speakers.  Keep that in mind, and as such, they are flat unbelievable.  Now I will say this:  you absolutely MUST have some kind of equalizer on your system to really get the most of this system.  That is true of most speaker systems.  My Asus computer has a pretty powerful RealTek HD audio manager installed that can really tweak these little things to a high degree for any style of music or other sounds that I can throw at them.  I have played rock, jazz, classical, acapella vocal music through them and it all sounds fantastic.  I will say, however, that these speakers are not designed for a larger room.  If that is your need, I would look elsewhere.  In my case, I simply wanted a good set of speakers to use with my computer which I use in an area of my home that is relatively small (12' x 10').One thing I absolutely love about these speakers--aside from their sound quality--is the independent volume control which handles both the subwoofer as well as the two satellite speakers.  This stand alone unit also has inputs for headphones, which I have not tried simply because I have no need to use headphones in my situation.  Yes, it takes up another small piece of my desk real estate, but I would much rather have the convenience of being able to control the volume of my speakers with this than having to either rely on software or worse, bending over to find the controls on the speakers. By the way, setup was a no-brainer.  I had them up and running in less than 10 minutes.  Some people have made mention of the design; both positive and negative.  Personally, I really don't care about such matters.  For me, it's all about performance and sound.  Having said that, I actually think they look kinda cool.  I suppose more "conservative" tastes might disagree, but I'll leave that to the individual.Is there a down side to the 1250's? A lot of fuss has been made about the bright blue light on the front of the volume controller and they aren't wrong.  While it doesn't bother me in the least while working on my computer, I do turn the unit off at night.  It is one damn bright light!  I am quite sure that there are many people out there who might choose to play music throughout the night on their computer and so could certainly be annoyed by the light, so all I can say is get some tape and cover that sucker up.  A bright light would be a pretty poor reason not to purchase these very good speakers, in my opinion.  You'd be excluding yourself from perhaps one of the better bargains around in terms of $50 speakers.I have only two real caveats that I have found:  (1) if your expectations are that these can be used for a large party or room, forget it and (2)if you don't have some decent equalizer software for your sound card, get some.  In my opinion, you will never be able to tweak ANY speaker system properly without at least having access to some basic equalization controls.  All of us have different preferences, so this is pretty fundamental.  Some of the negative reviews I read before purchasing dealt with the supposed lack in different parts of the frequency spectrum.  Several people complained, for example, of the lack of midrange, others for something else.  While I don't claim to be some sort of expert audiophile, I am a professional musician and have taught music for many years and conducted many bands and choirs, so I think I am at least qualified enough to know "good" from "bad" sounding speakers.  Which leads me to the opinion that those who made negative comments about these speakers would probably be better served by considerably more expensive and larger speaker systems.  From my point of view, I think these are probably among the best $50 speakers you're going to find.  I'm sure there are some other good ones out there as well.  After all, I am not in the position of being able to compare them all, but I will say that you will most likely be very pleased with these as long as you don't have any unrealistic expectations about them.To sum up, the Genius SW-2.1 1250 speakers are a true bargain and great little speakers at a great price.  I highly recommend them.  The true test for me now will be to see how they hold up over time.  Should anything change in my opinion, I will, of course, update this review.
summary: Great little speakers at a great price

reviewText: Ordered this to replace the head unit in my 1995 Mitsubishi 3000GT VR-4 which has a stock Infinity system with 6 speakers, 6 disc CD changer and a Bose sub added previously. I'm currently bench testing, making sure that I have all the wiring sorted out prior to doing the install as I am dealing with steering wheel volume controls, retractable antenna and adding the backup cam.Will be utilizing the stock Infinity amp by wiring the 4 channels from this head unit to a crossover I added to separate out the signal to 3 pairs of speakers (in-dash JBL tweets, door Kicker mids, rear Infinity 6x9s and the Bose sub). Will not be using the Sub input on the head unit as the crossover is where all the speakers connect, which also bypasses the comments that I read about the Sub not working in certain modes.As other reviews pointed out, there are some limitations. However, the only thing that I can't seem to get mine to do is the OSD (On Screen Display) as nothing happens when I press the button on the remote.I have viewed .jpg files off of the SD card reader, although there is no sound during that process. Music files play from SD card. I have not tried to play video files off the SD yet. DVD plays well although I did have one lockup that required shutting down to come out of. I have an old iPod mini that works great through the old style iPod cable included with this head unit - have yet to try it on my iPad 2 but it should work. The EQ is basic. The screen backgrounds are basic and not customizable. There is a "power screen" setting which allows you to select from vehicle manufacturers logos which show up on "power on". Front USB port plays music off of media other than SD card. There was no included MiniUSB cable in my packaging.The screen mechanism seems smooth and fluid. Remote works well with the exception of the OSD button which does nothing on mine. I have the Koolertron Rear View License Plate Backup CMOS Camera which works well, not the greatest but adequate at the price point. Tried in both the Cam connection and Aux1 for testing purposes.I have yet to hook up the TV and probably will not do so in the vehicle so it will remain an untested feature for now.If this one works out well, I may well get another to install in a school bus that I have where I will hook up to an external monitor for larger view.I'll report after completing the install...Additional 3/14/14 -> be careful with the "Mirror" setting under video as it flipped the screen on me, not just the camera. So then all icons appear backwards on the screen but the touch points remain un-mirrored... Had to do a reset to get it back to default, won't be touching the mirror setting again soon...

reviewText: ...unless you have experience and tech training in setting up networks.This is the 3rd camera I have ordered in the past 2 weeks and I've not been able to set up any of them. They all appear to come from the same manufacturer, have the same software and the same LAN connection problems.The Chinese manufacturers and the importers of these cameras all claim "easy to set up" but that's not true, to put it kindly. These cameras are NOT plug n' play, they require tech knowledge that many, if not most, people do not have. If the manufacturer and the importers intend to sell these cameras on the American market they're going to have to actually make them simple to install and connect to LANs and provide understandable instructions. I'm not an IT expert (as you may have guessed by now) but I CAN follow instructions, and the instructions that come with these cameras are virtually worthless to me. I'm not even expecting access from a smartphone, port forwarding, or remote alarm. All I want to do is see the video on my monitor, is that too much to expect from the people who build it and sell it? The so-called instructions tell me to simply plug it in, click through a couple pages, and enter the URL in my browser. Easy, right? Not so much.I'm shopping for a wired camera now, no more IP cameras for me.
summary: Do NOT buy an IP camera...

title_clean: Agasio M105I Outdoor Wireless Wifi Waterproof Bullet IP Camera with IR-Cut Filter, Two-way Audio, Night-Vision, Email &
description_clean: The Agasio/EasyN FS-613A-M105I Wireless IP Camera features an IR-Cut Filter for True Day/Night color images that are not washed out. Regular IP Cameras without IR-Cut filters have washed out images where the colors are not accurate and the images are blurry. This next generation of IR-Cut filter cameras provides true and accurate color representations and crisp picture quality. In addition, the EasyN M105I IR-Cut filter lens contains an Auto-Iris feature which automatically shuts the lens depending on lighting conditions to allow in only enough light to provide an accurately colored image as well as optimal brightness settings. This is a great advantage over traditional IP Cameras without IR-Cut filters because such IP Cameras allow in all the light which results in washed out images and require users to manually adjust brightness settings depending on lighting conditions. The EasyN FS-613A-M105I Wireless IP Camera features 0.3 Megapixel resolution (640x480), 6mm lens with 42 degree viewing angle. 24 IR Led's for 60 feet (20 meter) night vision, IR-Cut filter for true color images, Two-way Audio inputs (mic and speaker not included) as well as full remote control and recording capabilities. It also support DynDns as well as UPNP for automatic port forwarding. It has an easy to use graphical interface and is also smart phone compatible (Iphone, Android) as well as viewable over the internet or local network using standard browsers (Internet Explorer, Firefox, Safari and Google Chrome). The camera works marvelously as an outdoor waterproof surveillance system. What's Included: EasyN Wireless IP Camera Wifi Antenna User Manual Installation CD Mounting Bracket DC Power Supply 5v Free 64 Channel Recording Software

reviewText: This has been an excellent case so far. I replaced a Belkin messenger back with this Backpack style Swissgear bag, and I have had 0 problems so far. It definitely feels sturdy, and the zippers seem nice and strong (that was the biggest problem on my previous bag, the zippers breaking) and there is definitely PLENTY of storage space. I recently packed in two laptops (including my 17" Dell Studio with extended battery), a tablet, all supporting power adapters, extra mouse, other random stuff, and the bag didn't even flinch. Everything fit nicely. It also feels comfortable when wearing it.Overall, I'm extremely pleased with this bag. I've seen a few other folks using Swissgear bags and have gotten nothing but positive feedback from them, so these guys seem to have it together pretty well. It's pricier than some other bags, but considering I likely won't have to replace the bag every 1-2 years, it will actually end up being cheaper in the long run.

reviewerName: P. Colin McGraw "AV, Computer & EnviroTech Nut"
reviewText: In addition to this projector, I own a3M Streaming Projectorand aBenQ W7000 Cinema Quality Home Projector, so I have a decent frame of reference for writing this review.The PowerLite Home Cinema 2000 falls somewhere between those two. It's definitely a lot more powerful and fuller featured than a pico projector like the 3M, but less bright with less contrast than the BenQ W7000.Basically, the PowerLite Home Cinema 2000 is good enough to use in a budget-conscious home theater setting if you choose, but it's compact enough, light enough and easy enough to adjust that it can easily be used for presentations while traveling or for the best backyard movie watching experiences you can imagine. There are easy to adjust legs on the front and back of the projector to help aim, and keystone controls right on the projector itself to make it easy to keep the image nice and square.The brightness is enough that you can see the movie decently with the lights on so don't fear if you don't have a completely light-controlled room to project in.For that matter, you don't need a big room, either! The throw distance is ridiculously good on this thing. I sat the Cinema 2000 on a tray in front of my recliner and it was able to fill the better part of a 109" projection screen from only about 10' away (which is better than the BenQ!).Also, for those curious, the 3D is great! I bought a pair of cheapOkeba Ultralight RF glassesto try out the capabilities and, let me tell you, watching Life of Pi, Hugo, and Titanic in 3D on a 100" screen will make your JAW DROP!With the portability and 3D capabilities, I'm a little tempted to project a 3D movie on the back of my house on some warm evening!The only thing I didn't like about the projector was how hot it got. The bottom heats up enough that you'll want to let it cool off before handling it (which isn't uncommon for such projectors, but worth mentioning nevertheless).Overall this is an excellent value, and an easy choice for those wanting to enter into 1080p and/or 3D image on a large scale! At the price point, you could get a 100"+ image for about the price of a 60" TV!
summary: Stunning and Portable 3D 1080p Picture? Ohhh Yeah!

I am using a Canon EOS T3i and Canon lenses. And it doesn't have to be removed for the lens cap. It is well made for the price.One thing you should be careful of is to not squish it too much when storing it. It does hold the shape. Mine looks like a triangle after spending a month in a side pocket. I don't think it going to cause any problems. I am going to leave it out and see if it fixes itself. It wasn't like that when I got it so it was totally my fault. Just be careful not to impinge on the sides for an extended length of time and it shouldn't be an issue.The additional lens cloth was unexpected and always welcome. Another reason I chose this item was that Amazon.com offered it as an add on to purchases that qualify for free shipping. I really like this program and whenever I have the choice, I always pick the add on.I am not sure if Goja is the manufacturer or a reseller, but they put a lot of effort into making sure their customers are happy. Thank you!
summary_clean: Handy collapsible lens cowl and comes with a lens cloth

reviewText: I love this camera. It's pretty much everything the truly budget filmmaker could want. It takes beautiful stills, and the video is incomparable in its price range. The LCD is brilliant, and the low light capability is fantastic--but more on these gems later.Build Quality: This is pretty one area where I fell it could be improved. I like my cameras to feel solid, and, while it's perfectly decent feeling, it's doesn't have that impenetrable feeling. That being said, if you wanted that, you should be buying the 60D or 7D. Switches and dials are just fine and I haven't had any wear and tear issues anywhere, despite heavy use.Usability: I like it. That being said, it's a very personal preference. I would have liked to have more dedicated dials. With the button-dial combinations, it's perfectly adequate, if not optimal, though. Once again, could use a bit of improvement. Battery life is good, I've found, but you should always have extras on hand, especially when shooting video (really a necessity).LCD: I had to put this in a separate section because it's so good. Magnifique. Pictures and video look brilliant. I can even pull focus on it without needing an LCDVF.Image Qality: Stills look fantastic on this. Paired with the right lens and photographer, you are definitely looking at some good shots. Noise level is good, although in very low-light situations, RAW photos can start to look sketchy, so I'd suggest sticking to JPEG for this purpose unless you have a quality RAW convert with good noise reduction. ISO performance is really good. Paired with the 50mm f/1.8, I feel like a king, walking around shooting without a flash while the other poor people can only stand by and hope their shots don't look like they came from the floor of a Jersey shore nightclub.Video Quality: This is why I bought this camera, and it hasn't let me down. If you pair this with Marvels Cine, or Cinestyle picture styles, you get some pretty meaty dynamic range, which works very nicely in post for color correction. Noise is truly great for this price range. ISO ranges all the way to 1600 are usable for film work, especially after color correction. (Make sure to use a flat picture style!) Although this uses an APS-C crop sensor, that can hardly be avoided unless you have a few grand to drop, and I haven't found it hard to get the depth of field I'm looking for without sacrificing framing, especially with faster lenses.Audio: While you may be thinking it's impossible to get decent in camera audio, think again. If you have Magic Lantern installed, and you should definitely for shooting film, you can easily disable Auto Gain Control (AGC). This, paired with a decent mic preamp (which doesn't have to cost a lot--see the ART USB Dual Pre) can give you really excellent results. Good enough, I dare say, for festival work.Overall: Frankly, I'd like to give this camera an award for budget filmmaking. There is one Caveat though: This award-winning capability is predisposed on have Magic Lantern firmware installed. I won't explain all it can do here, but please, please look into it if you're thinking of buying a T2i/T3i. Without it, it's merely a five-star camera. With it, it's a $2000 dollar nightmaric monstrosity that will leave you saying only "Beast mode engaged!"
