title_clean: Casio EX-H20GBK Hybrid-GPS Enabled 14 MP Digital Camera with 10x Zoom and 3-Inch LCD (Black)
description_clean: The EX-H20G is equipped with a Hybrid GPS system that combines a GPS engine with autonomic positioning made possible by a motion sensor. The system sets a new standard for geotagging and offers exciting new ways to use a digital camera. With the new Exilim Engine HS, the EX-H20G features all of the essential capabilities expected from a camera. When used with Casio's Single Frame SR Zoom function, the 24mm wide-angle, 10x optical zoom lens actually offers a 15x zoom range that maintains the image quality needed for 14.1-megapixel high-resolution photography.Casio Exilim H20G HighlightsWorks EverywhereThe EX-H20G is equipped with a Hybrid GPS system that combines a GPS engine with autonomic positioning made possible by a motion sensor. Even if no signals are received from GPS satellites when indoors, the system consecutively tracks the user's location by employing an original algorithm using a three-way accelerometer and a three-way direction sensor. When the user goes back outside, the system automatically updates the positional information of the indoor location based on the exact location determined by GPS reception. Even when the camera is powered off, the GPS system continues to search for satellite signals at 10 minute intervals.Ready When You AreWhether it's turned on, powered off or on standby in your pocket, the unique tracking and power control enables highly precise positioning without the time lag common with other GPS.10,000 World-Wide LandmarksThe Casio Hybrid-GPS comes pre-loaded with world atlas data and information for nearly 10,000 sightseeing photo spots around the globe. Travelers can see photo opportunities around them and determine distance to those locations right on the LCD. Photos are labeled with the location and building name when available - making it even easier to remember where the shot was taken.Long-Lasting BatteryThe EX-H20G employs Casio's advanced low-power technology, which ensures that the camera consumes only a small amount of power. Power consumption is suited for the various situations in which the EX-H20G will be used, including power-on and power-off, satellite acquisition and even while the three-way accelerometer and direction sensor are working in the background while the camera is off. With the EX-H20G, users can rest assured knowing that they won't need to sacrifice battery life to enjoy highly precise and speedy position tracking.10x Ultra-Wide Zoom Lens (24mm)Only Casio could find a way to pack a 10x Optical Zoom lens, large 3.0-inch monitor and a CCD Shift Image Stabilization mechanism into such a slim, compact camera body, just .96" thin, convenient for travel. With Ultra-Wide Angle starting at 24mm (35mm film camera equivalent) all the way up to 10x telephoto zoom, the photographer is ready for any scene.Premium AutoPremium Auto enables the camera to automatically analyze the scene being photographed - including distinguishing night scenes, back lighting, a blue sky, green trees or a sunset - as well as sensing whether there is a face in the frame, the movement and position of the subject, and whether a tripod is being used. It simultaneously optimizes settings for exposure, ISO, sensitivity, focus location, photo blur correction, tonal range and color balance, and level of noise reduction.Dynamic Photo Automated e-Greetings: Place your subject on any backgroundThanks to the high-speed image processing capability of the new engine, a moving subject can be cut out of a number of images that have been shot and combined with a different still shot that forms the background. A unique digital camera image where only the main subject in the photo is moving can be created using just the camera, with no editing on a computer.Slide Panorama: Capture 360-degree panoramic imagesThis function makes it easy to take panoramic images, simply by panning the camera across the scene with the shutter button pressed.

reviewText: I bought this gadget to use with my Nikon D40x, and now I use it with my D5100. Once I remember how to install it - seems like there's always enough time between uses that I kind of forget - it really helps make better flash-lit photos. It's really helpful with photos of people, but also it's just good for not blowing out details of anything in the shot.It cost very little, takes up almost no room in a bag, weighs just about nothing, and takes the edge off my usual dread to use the pop-up flash on my DSLRs.

title_clean: Canon EOS Rebel T2i DSLR Camera with EF-S 18-55mm f/3.5-5.6 IS Lens (OLD MODEL)
description_clean: The new flagship of the EOS Rebel line, Canon EOS Rebel T2i brings professional EOS features into an easy to use, lightweight digital SLR that's a joy to use. Featuring a class-leading 18.0-megapixel CMOS image sensor and increased light sensitivity for low light photography, the EOS Rebel T2i also has an advanced HD Movie mode for gorgeous Full HD movies. Able to capture up to 3.7 frames per second, it's ready to go the minute it's picked up. Advanced Live View, a new wide-area screen, plus features like Canon's brilliant Auto Lighting Optimizer and Highlight Tone features ensure brilliant photos and movies, easily. With some of the most advanced features of any digital SLR, it's simply the best Rebel Canon has ever created.EOS Rebel T2i Highlights18.0-megapixel CMOS (APS-C) sensor and DIGIC 4 Image ProcessorThe EOS Rebel T2i has an 18.0-megapixel CMOS sensor that captures images with exceptional clarity and tonal range and offers more than enough resolution for big enlargements or crops. This first-class sensor features many of the same new technologies as used by professional Canon cameras to maximize each pixel's light-gathering efficiency. Its APS-C size sensor creates an effective 1.6x field of view (compared to 35mm format).DIGIC 4 Image ProcessorThe Canon DIGIC 4 Image Processor dramatically speeds up the entire EOS Rebel T2i's camera operations for intuitive operation and offers improvements in both fine detail and natural color reproduction. It works in concert with the EOS Rebel T2i's CMOS Image Sensor to achieve phenomenal levels of performance in nearly any situation.Capture stunning shots in low light.ISO 100-6400 (expandable to 12800) for shooting from bright to dim lightThe EOS Rebel T2i features an expanded ISO range that makes shooting possible in situations previously unthinkable without flash. With an ISO rating up to 6400 (expandable to ISO 12800), along with the DIGIC 4 Image Processor's improved noise-reduction technology, creative possibilities abound. Combine the EOS Rebel T2i with one of Canon's EF or EF-S lenses with Optical Image Stabilizer and the shooting possibilities for both movies and stills expand even further.Improved EOS Movie mode with manual exposure controlDesigned for the evolving, tech-savvy user, the EOS Rebel T2i features HD Video capture technologies--manual exposure control for more creative control, for example--borrowed directly from professional Canon SLRs to capture stellar video with all the benefits of shooting with an SLR. By shooting video with the EOS Rebel T2i, photographers as well as filmmakers can take advantage of the creative features native to SLR cameras. Along with its manual controls, the EOS Rebel T2i allows for full use of Canon EF and EF-S lenses, including Macro and Fisheye, providing a plethora of shooting options once reserved only for still photography. The resulting HD video is a standout in its beautiful depth-of-field characteristics and remarkable capture capability under poor lighting conditions. In a first for EOS cameras, a Movie Crop function is included: An SD-quality movie (640 x 480) can be cropped to the equivalent of about 7x magnification of regular shooting.Video can be captured at a number of resolutions and frame rates for numerous applications. It can capture 1920 x 1080 Full HD video at frame rates of 24 (23.976), 25 or 30 (29.97) frames per second, for up to 4GB per clip. Movies are saved as MOV files and can be viewed in Full HD through the EOS Rebel T2i's HDMI output. Other recording sizes include HD at 1280 x 720 (50/60 (59.94) fps) or SD/VGA at 640 x 480 (50/60 (59.94) fps). The EOS Rebel T2i has a built-in microphone for simple mono recording and stereo sound can be recorded through a self-powered external microphone.Enhanced 63-zone, Dual-layer metering system, and 9-point AF systemThe EOS Rebel T2i features Canon's newest Dual-layer sensor, with 63-zones. By measuring not only the amount of light, but also taking into account color and luminosity, this new system delivers a very high level of accuracy for better results every time. Since the metering sensor has a color measurement function, exposure errors and focus errors caused by different light sources are minimized; the EOS Rebel T2i gives stable exposure from shot to shot in situations where light changes, such as sports on a cloudy day, or indoor holiday scenes.Additionally, the EOS Rebel T2i has a high-precision, 9-point AF system utilizing a high-precision, f/2.8 cross-type center point. The 9-point AF system uses both normal and high-precision focus depending on the aperture and available light. The 9 focus points can be chosen automatically or manually selected.Wide 3.0-inch (3:2 aspect ratio) Clear View LCD monitorThe EOS Rebel T2i has a high-resolution 3.0-inch Clear View LCD monitor that features 1.04 million dots/VGA for spectacular detail. It also has the same aspect ratio (3:2) as the camera's sensor, making for clear and easy Live View composition. An anti-reflective and water-repellant coating provides a clearer and more smudge-resistant surface and screen brightness can be adjusted in 7 steps in accordance with ambient light.New Quick Control Screen buttonThe EOS Rebel T2i's refined button layout includes a dedicated button that directs the camera immediately to the Quick Control screen, where it's simple to navigate among any number of settings, including ISO, Exposure and Flash Exposure compensation, drive mode, white balance, image quality and much, much more.Improved layout with dedicated Live View/Movie shooting buttonWithout the need to navigate through a bunch of menus, the EOS Rebel T2i transitions effortlessly between still and movie mode. By pressing the Live View/Movie button, a situation that had required menu access with other cameras, still images can change to a movie shoot and vice versa. It's literally as simple as the press of a button.3.7fps continuous shooting up to approximately 34 JPEGs or approximately 6 RAWThe EOS Rebel T2i can shoot up to 3.7 frames per second (fps) for up to approximately 6 consecutive RAW files or approximately 34 full-resolution JPEGs. Shooting at speeds of up to 1/4000 sec., the EOS Rebel T2i can capture even rapidly-unfolding scenes with ease.New compatibility with SDXC memory cardsThe EOS Rebel T2i is compatible with both SDXC memory cards for greater storage capacity and with Eye-Fi SD cards, which are outfitted with a Wi-Fi transmitter (IEEE 802.11b/g) and internal antenna for wireless, high speed transfer of images. With an Eye-Fi card installed, the EOS Rebel T2i can display the Eye-Fi's connection status and error notes with ease, for fully functional wireless uploading of images directly from the camera.*Canon cameras are not guaranteed to support Eye-Fi card functions, including wireless transfer. In case of an issue with the Eye-Fi card, please consult with the card manufacturer. The use of Eye-Fi cards may not be available outside the United States and Canada, please contact the card manufacturer for territory availability.Compatible with the full line of Canon EF and EF-S lensesEF LensesThe EOS Rebel T2i is compatible with all Canon lenses in the EF lineup, including compact and lightweight EF-S lenses, ranging from ultra-wide angle to super telephoto lenses. Canon lenses employ advanced optical expertise and micron-precision engineering to deliver outstanding performance and deliver beautiful results. Special technologies like the Canon Image Stabilizer technology in select lenses helps to minimize the effect of camera shake, effectively adding up to four stops of light. With a dizzying array of lenses perfect for travel, sports, still life and everything in between, photographers can truly maximize the quality and performance of their EOS Rebel T2i with superlative Canon optics.SoftwareCanon EOS Digital Solution Disk (Version 22.0)The EOS Rebel T2i comes bundled with a Canon EOS Digital Solution Disk, which features powerful software programs designed to extend the EOS experience to the computer. These include Canon's EOS Utility (Version 2.8.0), Digital Photo Professional (Version 3.8.0), ZoomBrowser EX for Windows (Version 6.5.0), ImageBrowser for Macintosh OS X (Version 6.5.0), the Picture Style Editor (Version 1.7.0), MovieEdit Task (Win/Mac, Version 3.4.1) PhotoStitch (Windows Version 3.1.22/Mac Version 3.2.4), Memory Card Utility (Windows Version 1.3.0/Mac Version 1.2.3), WFT Utility (Win/Mac, Version 3.5.1), and Original Data Security Tools 1.8.0 (Win). Each application is designed to perfect the captured images and streamline the digital workflow.Compatible Operating SystemWindows: Windows XP SP2 or SP3 / Windows Vista (all version except the Starter Edition) / Windows 7 32-bit and 64-bit versions. Macintosh: OS X 10.4 to 10.5EOS Utility (Version 2.8.0)for Macintosh or Windows handles the connection between the camera and computer whenever they're connected via USB. It allows remote controlled shooting from the computer, handles downloading of images from the camera to the computer, and allows seamless linking to either Canon's ZoomBrowser EX/ImageBrowser or Digital Photo Professional software once images have been copied to the hard drive. Furthermore, it's used to upload settings back into a USB-connected camera.Digital Photo Professional (Win/Mac, Version 3.8.0)is an image processing program that enables high-speed RAW image processing, high-speed previewing for real-time image adjustment and support for sRGB, Adobe RGB and Wide Gamut RGB color spaces. Because it's CMS (Color Management System) compatible, Digital Photo Professional allows for easy image layout and printing in Adobe RGB in conjunction with Easy-PhotoPrint and PictBridge printers. It also features the Dust Delete Data Detection tool for cleaner images.Picture Style Editor (Win/Mac, Version 1.7.0)Canon's Picture Style Editor enables you to create custom Picture Style profiles that can be used to customize the appearance of JPEG and RAW images captured with EOS Digital SLR cameras. Picture Style files created with Picture Style Editor can be loaded into the EOS cameras that support Picture Style and may also be used when processing RAW images in Canon software applications Digital Photo Professional, ZoomBrowser EX (for Windows) and ImageBrowser (for Mac).ZoomBrowser EX (Version 6.5.0)for Windows and ImageBrowser (Version 6.5.0) for Mac OS X are the easy, user-friendly options for viewing and editing of JPEG and even RAW image files. Both allow viewing of numerous types of images including finished TIFF and BMP files. Both also have a variety of search options for finding images, allow re-naming of single images or batches of files, and offer a variety of options for printing without using a separate image-editing program.What's in the BoxEOS Rebel T2i BodyEF-S 18-55mm f/3.5-5.6 IS LensEyecup Ef (Not shown)Wide Strap EW-100DBIIIUSB Interface Cable IFC-130UAV Cable AVC-DC400STBattery Pack LP-E8Battery Charger LC-E8EOS Digital Solution Disk and Instruction Manuals"Great Photography is Easy" Booklet and "Do More with Macro" Booklet (not shown)

Combine the EOS Rebel T2i with one of Canon's EF or EF-S lenses with Optical Image Stabilizer and the shooting possibilities for both movies and stills expand even further.Improved EOS Movie mode with manual exposure controlDesigned for the evolving, tech-savvy user, the EOS Rebel T2i features HD Video capture technologies--manual exposure control for more creative control, for example--borrowed directly from professional Canon SLRs to capture stellar video with all the benefits of shooting with an SLR. By shooting video with the EOS Rebel T2i, photographers as well as filmmakers can take advantage of the creative features native to SLR cameras. Along with its manual controls, the EOS Rebel T2i allows for full use of Canon EF and EF-S lenses, including Macro and Fisheye, providing a plethora of shooting options once reserved only for still photography. The resulting HD video is a standout in its beautiful depth-of-field characteristics and remarkable capture capability under poor lighting conditions. In a first for EOS cameras, a Movie Crop function is included: An SD-quality movie (640 x 480) can be cropped to the equivalent of about 7x magnification of regular shooting.Video can be captured at a number of resolutions and frame rates for numerous applications. It can capture 1920 x 1080 Full HD video at frame rates of 24 (23.976), 25 or 30 (29.97) frames per second, for up to 4GB per clip. Movies are saved as MOV files and can be viewed in Full HD through the EOS Rebel T2i's HDMI output. Other recording sizes include HD at 1280 x 720 (50/60 (59.94) fps) or SD/VGA at 640 x 480 (50/60 (59.94) fps). The EOS Rebel T2i has a built-in microphone for simple mono recording and stereo sound can be recorded through a self-powered external microphone.Enhanced 63-zone, Dual-layer metering system, and 9-point AF systemThe EOS Rebel T2i features Canon's newest Dual-layer sensor, with 63-zones. By measuring not only the amount of light, but also taking into account color and luminosity, this new system delivers a very high level of accuracy for better results every time. Since the metering sensor has a color measurement function, exposure errors and focus errors caused by different light sources are minimized; the EOS Rebel T2i gives stable exposure from shot to shot in situations where light changes, such as sports on a cloudy day, or indoor holiday scenes.Additionally, the EOS Rebel T2i has a high-precision, 9-point AF system utilizing a high-precision, f/2.8 cross-type center point. The 9-point AF system uses both normal and high-precision focus depending on the aperture and available light. The 9 focus points can be chosen automatically or manually selected.Wide 3.0-inch (3:2 aspect ratio) Clear View LCD monitorThe EOS Rebel T2i has a high-resolution 3.0-inch Clear View LCD monitor that features 1.04 million dots/VGA for spectacular detail. It also has the same aspect ratio (3:2) as the camera's sensor, making for clear and easy Live View composition. An anti-reflective and water-repellant coating provides a clearer and more smudge-resistant surface and screen brightness can be adjusted in 7 steps in accordance with ambient light.New Quick Control Screen buttonThe EOS Rebel T2i's refined button layout includes a dedicated button that directs the camera immediately to the Quick Control screen, where it's simple to navigate among any number of settings, including ISO, Exposure and Flash Exposure compensation, drive mode, white balance, image quality and much, much more.Improved layout with dedicated Live View/Movie shooting buttonWithout the need to navigate through a bunch of menus, the EOS Rebel T2i transitions effortlessly between still and movie mode. By pressing the Live View/Movie button, a situation that had required menu access with other cameras, still images can change to a movie shoot and vice versa. It's literally as simple as the press of a button.3.7fps continuous shooting up to approximately 34 JPEGs or approximately 6 RAWThe EOS Rebel T2i can shoot up to 3.7 frames per second (fps) for up to approximately 6 consecutive RAW files or approximately 34 full-resolution JPEGs. Shooting at speeds of up to 1/4000 sec., the EOS Rebel T2i can capture even rapidly-unfolding scenes with ease.New compatibility with SDXC memory cardsThe EOS Rebel T2i is compatible with both SDXC memory cards for greater storage capacity and with Eye-Fi SD cards, which are outfitted with a Wi-Fi transmitter (IEEE 802.11b/g) and internal antenna for wireless, high speed transfer of images. With an Eye-Fi card installed, the EOS Rebel T2i can display the Eye-Fi's connection status and error notes with ease, for fully functional wireless uploading of images directly from the camera.*Canon cameras are not guaranteed to support Eye-Fi card functions, including wireless transfer. In case of an issue with the Eye-Fi card, please consult with the card manufacturer. The use of Eye-Fi cards may not be available outside the United States and Canada, please contact the card manufacturer for territory availability.Compatible with the full line of Canon EF and EF-S lensesEF LensesThe EOS Rebel T2i is compatible with all Canon lenses in the EF lineup, including compact and lightweight EF-S lenses, ranging from ultra-wide angle to super telephoto lenses. Canon lenses employ advanced optical expertise and micron-precision engineering to deliver outstanding performance and deliver beautiful results. Special technologies like the Canon Image Stabilizer technology in select lenses helps to minimize the effect of camera shake, effectively adding up to four stops of light. With a dizzying array of lenses perfect for travel, sports, still life and everything in between, photographers can truly maximize the quality and performance of their EOS Rebel T2i with superlative Canon optics.SoftwareCanon EOS Digital Solution Disk (Version 22.0)The EOS Rebel T2i comes bundled with a Canon EOS Digital Solution Disk, which features powerful software programs designed to extend the EOS experience to the computer. These include Canon's EOS Utility (Version 2.8.0), Digital Photo Professional (Version 3.8.0), ZoomBrowser EX for Windows (Version 6.5.0), ImageBrowser for Macintosh OS X (Version 6.5.0), the Picture Style Editor (Version 1.7.0), MovieEdit Task (Win/Mac, Version 3.4.1) PhotoStitch (Windows Version 3.1.22/Mac Version 3.2.4), Memory Card Utility (Windows Version 1.3.0/Mac Version 1.2.3), WFT Utility (Win/Mac, Version 3.5.1), and Original Data Security Tools 1.8.0 (Win). Each application is designed to perfect the captured images and streamline the digital workflow.Compatible Operating SystemWindows: Windows XP SP2 or SP3 / Windows Vista (all version except the Starter Edition) / Windows 7 32-bit and 64-bit versions. Macintosh: OS X 10.4 to 10.5EOS Utility (Version 2.8.0)for Macintosh or Windows handles the connection between the camera and computer whenever they're connected via USB. It allows remote controlled shooting from the computer, handles downloading of images from the camera to the computer, and allows seamless linking to either Canon's ZoomBrowser EX/ImageBrowser or Digital Photo Professional software once images have been copied to the hard drive. Furthermore, it's used to upload settings back into a USB-connected camera.Digital Photo Professional (Win/Mac, Version 3.8.0)is an image processing program that enables high-speed RAW image processing, high-speed previewing for real-time image adjustment and support for sRGB, Adobe RGB and Wide Gamut RGB color spaces. Because it's CMS (Color Management System) compatible, Digital Photo Professional allows for easy image layout and printing in Adobe RGB in conjunction with Easy-PhotoPrint and PictBridge printers. It also features the Dust Delete Data Detection tool for cleaner images.Picture Style Editor (Win/Mac, Version 1.7.0)Canon's Picture Style Editor enables you to create custom Picture Style profiles that can be used to customize the appearance of JPEG and RAW images captured with EOS Digital SLR cameras. Picture Style files created with Picture Style Editor can be loaded into the EOS cameras that support Picture Style and may also be used when processing RAW images in Canon software applications Digital Photo Professional, ZoomBrowser EX (for Windows) and ImageBrowser (for Mac).ZoomBrowser EX (Version 6.5.0)for Windows and ImageBrowser (Version 6.5.0) for Mac OS X are the easy, user-friendly options for viewing and editing of JPEG and even RAW image files. Both allow viewing of numerous types of images including finished TIFF and BMP files. Both also have a variety of search options for finding images, allow re-naming of single images or batches of files, and offer a variety of options for printing without using a separate image-editing program.What's in the BoxEOS Rebel T2i BodyEF-S 18-55mm f/3.5-5.6 IS LensEyecup Ef (Not shown)Wide Strap EW-100DBIIIUSB Interface Cable IFC-130UAV Cable AVC-DC400STBattery Pack LP-E8Battery Charger LC-E8EOS Digital Solution Disk and Instruction Manuals"Great Photography is Easy" Booklet and "Do More with Macro" Booklet (not shown)

reviewText: The WD My Passport Pro 2TB is actually a very well built piece of kit. It's quite heavy, though. The 2TB model weighs in on my scale at a hair over 1lb.Out of the box, plugged into my 2012 iMac (running Mavericks), the drive was picked up instantly, running by default in RAID 0 configuration (HFS, journaled). This is the least safe method of data preservation, but certainly the fastest available for this device. Much like the Western Digital My Book Thunderbolt Duo for desktops, this device is using software for its RAID. There are positives and negatives for hardware vs software RAID implementations, and I won't delve into this too much here. Apple's basic RAID software included in OS X isn't exactly stellar, though. (I prefer using SoftRAID, which - while pricey - is just a brilliant piece of software for OS X).A couple of minor issues:1.) If you break the Thunderbolt cable, the whole device is useless, as the cable is integrated. Be careful to tuck the cable away into its holder when you're done.2.) There's a small fan in this enclosure, and I hope it's a long-lasting one, as - again - I don't see how you could replace it.3.) If you run a RAID 1 mirror array, if one drive fails you cannot simply replace it as you can on the Western Digital dual-drive desktop 3.5" RAID enclosures. You'll have to copy the data off, send the drive in, and then wait for a replacement. Not exactly ideal... I tried to see if I could open it up, but even removing the four accessible screws - the enclosure didn't want to come apart.4.) It's not a cheap setup. Especially since it's not even using a hardware RAID implementation, I'm surprised it costs so much.5.) There's a small fan in this unit. Initially I had thought it was there as a fail-safe as it wasn't spinning, and I guess it really is there as a last resort. After about an hour of solid transfers to it from a slow, USB 2.0 drive, the fan kicked in. I seriously thought something was wrong with it. It makes this high-pitched, absolutely obnoxious noise. Thankfully, after about 5 minutes of running it turns off, but it will come on again if there's continual heat (i.e. continual transfers). If this is going to be a high-use device with a lot of transferring data from/to it, - if noise bothers you, AVOID this drive. The fan is ghastly.Overall, though, this is a solid twin-drive setup, backed by Western Digital for 3 years. If you need a fast, portable games/scratch disk, run this thing in RAID 0 for ~200MB/s read/writes. If you need data redundancy for photographic/video works, run this in RAID 1 for protection against a single drive failure (at about the speed of a single drive, ~110MB/s). Either way, make SURE to have a backup! RAID of any sort is NOT a backup solution. Please, make backups!4 stars out of 5. Recommended.
summary: Good, but quite expensive, and that fan....

reviewText: I bought the E1200 to replace a 12oN that died after about 2 years. I use a 120N at home for wireless internet to my LG SmartTV without problems.The network is simple: two computers hardwired to the router via ethernet. Both computers used to use wireless to connect to Samsung SCX-5635 Scanner/Printer. The router recognizes only one of the two hardwired computers. Neither computer can see the Samsung.There is no convenient manuals or troubleshooting.Trying to use Cisco's supposed Live Chat was totally disastrous. A jerk described only as Nova (17169) responded only with jibberish that had no relevance to the problems that had been clearly described in various posts. It was as though he/she was confusing his customers and their problems or that he/she just didn't care. Then he/she said that he/she lacked any expertise to deal with it. I asked for a supervisor's email or phone number and was given only the general corporate phone for Cisco.I could ahve spent $30-$40 to call an actual Cisco rep, but by now I ahve no faith that any of them would be able to help either.Hours of wasted time later uninstalling and reinstalling to see if it might come alive have proven futile.I cannot recommend the E1200 at all, and I find Cisco's support worse than useless. It's a total exercise in frustration and a waste of time.I'm disconnecting the unit and hauling it back to Office Depot to get anything from a competitor. No more Cisco, especially no more E1200.Happy to see that some folks had good experience.My opinion, however, is that E1200 = Total garbage.

reviewText: Jaw dropping sound.  I was going to talk about the very nice packaging, the fact that you get a huge assortment of ear tips to fit any size and shape of ear, the extra nice hard case these come with, until I tucked these into my ears and my jaw dropped open.I've been listening to the same favorite songs on a large assortment of speakers, headphones and earbuds for years.  I like jazz, rock, Bach and old school funk and this is the first time I've had to keep turning the music down because the bass and clarity were almost overwhelming.  If you want the experience of being right there at the concert this is it.First the cons.  There is only one, which I will happily put up with.  When you listen to your list of songs there may be some you have to keep turning down because the bass will be too much for your eardrums.  Most songs don't do this but occasionally one does.  The separation of the sounds, voices and instruments is like you are listening to this live.  No wonder they had to make the cord flat.  They must have used heavy duty wires to get this quality of sound in earbuds.I was concerned at first about having to hook a cord over my ears but found that, with the original ear tips that come preinstalled these tucked comfortably into my ear canals and stayed put without needing to hook the cord over my ears.  I took a walk with these and they stayed in my ears without my even being able to feel them.  There was just that amazing sound quality.  It made my walk effortless. But I had to keep reminding myself to keep my mouth closed. They seem to boost the power and volume of my songs somehow.I did try putting the cord over my ears in the recommended way for these, even though I didn't need to, as an experiment.  I always wear sunglasses outside and wanted to see if the cord over my ears was noticeable with sunglasses but I couldn't even feel it.  However for me it wasn't necessary to do it that way since they stayed in my ear anyway.And the flat cord has this going for it, aside from housing thicker wires for better sound clarity:  they won't break like I've had Bose thin cords do.  My first set of Bose earbuds snapped off where the cord meets the plug. No way that will happen with these sturdy cords.You will hear your songs like you've never heard them before.  These pick up sounds in the songs that I've never heard in them before. I've been using Bose earbuds for years.  These are better. And less expensive.Yes the small hard zippered case is extremely nice, the assortment of sizes and styles of earpads is exceptional, the packaging is impressive, the price is very competitive for audiophile quality earphones, but all I can think about right now as I'm wearing them is the sound.  It's amazing.Do I recommend these?  You bet I do.  I did receive a review sample which in no way influenced this review.  This is one of my rare ten star products.

reviewText: I've had this for a few weeks and have used it numerous times to navigate around Brevard County Florida. So far the maps (which I updated right after getting the GPS) have been spot on except for one time when I was in a wildlife conservation area (that neither Google or Bing maps has either) which wasn't mapped but it's dirt dikes in a swamp and not part of city, county or state roads. Amusingly the Garmin map did show the lakes I was driving around just not the dirt roads.I've downloaded and tried several of the voices offered for the Garmin nüvi 50LM though the only ones I've used have been the TTS voices (those that actually speak the street names). After several trials I've found, oddly enough, that the voice 'British English - Serena' is the clearest and easiest to understand.The 5" screen is great. The display is crisp and clear and can easily be read from a distance. The touch screen is quite responsive. I don't feel like I have to pound on the screen to make selections. I have mine mounted in anArkon GN047 Removable Air Vent Mountin the passenger side center console air vent to keep it off the windshield and out of the Florida sun. {See uploaded photo.}While this is a basic GPS unit the nüvi 50LM does what a GPS unit is designed to, get you from Point-A to Point-B (options for this are Faster Time, Shorter Distance or Off Road (straight line navigation)) without any extra, distracting, bells and whistles it still has some nice options:* Lifetime free map updates.* Maps can be displayed in 2D or 3D.* You can change the level of map display information shown.* You can turn on or off Map Data Layout information which adds driving direction, time of day, elevation and speed to the main map display.* The icon for your vehicle can be changed. Garmin themselves offer numerous icons to download and there are also places on the internet to download custom vehicle icons.* Automatic switching between day and night display settings.* Lane Assist & Junction View helps you (in some areas) get in the correct lane ahead of time.* Millions of Points of Interest plus the ability to add your own favorite destinations.So far I really like my Garmin nüvi 50LM and enjoy using it. It's made getting out and about a lot easier than paper maps ever did.I'll update this review, if necessary, if any durability issues arise over time. For now, this is one of my favorite pieces of technology.

reviewText: I ordered this after a friend convinced me I must have an SSD to speed up my computer.  I have a 2011 mac mini with a core i5.  I will say the drive is fast, but for me it isn't night and day.  My computer is Sata 6gps capable and I see write times of about 250mbps and read times of double that.  My spinning drive averaged about 100mbps.  I think really your mileage will very.  Now that we use so many mobile devices my computer is more of a hub for all the devices than the main workhorse.  Again it really depends on your situation.  If you did work in CAD or heavy excel work, you probably see a bigger difference than the web and email use.  Also I think older machines will pick up more of the performance boost, keep in mind though many older machines will fall back to the Sata II interface and you won't see the drive's max speed.  On which SSD to pick, I agonized and read reviews for days and this is the conclusion I came to:  The sandforce based drives are the fasted, but the firmware doesn't seem as mature, and people have more OS based problems with them, such as the OCZ drives, got take a look at the reviews and see how many people had to return them.  The marvell based drives like the crucial aren't as fast but tend to be more reliable. so thats why I recommend this one, and with the recen price drop why not splurge and get a 256!

reviewText: This is a very good quality product. Its very well packaged, the software is easy to install and the camera is easy to set up. The camera itself is quality plastic and very solid. The video quality and sound is also very good. The infrared motion sensor is great. It means that it doesn't turn on unless there is something or someone to trigger it. Unlike other cameras that seem to turn on for nothing.The night vision doesn't work at all. The manufacturer would be wise to make a new, and cheaper model, without it. Also, it does not last 10 days on standby. When the battery is fully charged you are lucky to get 7 days out of it. This feature was the reason why I bought it so I'm very disappointed.Update: I drilled a hole in the battery cover, cut the battery wires and passed them through the hole. Then, I soldered a larger battery, with the same voltage, to the wires and glued it to the back of the camera. Now the camera lasts more then 10 days on a single charge! (See Pictures)23/09/13: I had some difficulty charging camera and downloading photos. If this happens check your USB connection or change the cable.Dec.2013: I was having too much trouble accessing the memory and charging this little device so I trashed it. I think the USB port had a short or something.

reviewText: I purchased my copy from Adorama for the same price as the Amazon because they threw in free high quality UV filter and circular polarizer.  I waited a long time, hoping that Nikon would release a VR version of this lens, since it's been out since early 2008. In the meantime, I had been using Nikon 24-85mm f/3.5-4.5G VR as my primary walk about lens on a D800.  I also have an earlier version of 24-120mm, while serviceable on a DX body, was frankly dismal on D800.  Aside from some CA and distortion issues, for the price, 24-85mm lens is an excellent overall performer with truly useful VR feature.  However, I wanted a faster lens for indoor use without the flash and wanted the convenience of a zoom lens.  I also looked at the new Tamron 24-70mm f/2.8 lens with VC (vibration control) but when Nikon recently offered instant rebate on their lenses, I decided to get this one.This lens delivers everything promised on a pro lens: superb IQ with center and edge sharpness, open and stopped down, tough build quality, quick and accurate AF.  I really regret not getting this lens sooner. I had reservations because it lacked VR but in reality, I do not miss it with this lens, whereas on a 70-200mm lens, it made a huge difference.  Knowing what I know now, except for the prime lenses that I currently have, I would have skipped buying all my other Nikon DX/FX lenses and go straight to purchasing this one, even when I was using a DX body like D90 or D7000.  For video applications, I do think VR feature would certainly enhance the usability of this lens.OK, this lens is overkill on a DX body but I will take this lens on a D800 over highly rated and more expensive Canon 24-70mm version II and 5D MK III.

reviewText: If you need a robust 4 port hub, that also has a dedicated charge port for phones, tablets or other USB charge capable devices, this is a good option.I've compared hard drive speeds (I have 3 USB 3 external HDDs) to this unit and another Plugable USB 3 hubs I have. Both offer the same performance, copying files at similar speeds without any issue. The only difference is that the other hub has 4 ports but no dedicated charging option. I am definitely swapping out my old USB3 hub and putting this in. It adds the dedicated charging port, which comes in handy.The aluminum style finish is stylish and looks nice on the desk. I don't honestly care how it looks, since mine hides behind my monitor anyway, but if you want a hub that looks nice and performs fantastically, this hub might be the one you want.The dedicated charge port, for me, has a micro-USB cable hanging off of it. I fished it under the monitor and next to the keyboard. I plug my phone into this while I'm working and it charges quickly. It should, since it's capable of charging a device that can take up to 2.1 A of power.Overall, the device looks good, works well and performs exactly as you expect and want.Highly recommended.I received a free sample for review purposes from Plugable.
summary: Works well, slightly more expensive than others but worth it

reviewText: This is not the same thing as a surge suppressor. Don't be fooled by ill informed store associates into thinking a surge suppressor will protect your equipment from fluctuations in power. Most are too small to trigger a surge suppressor. Power conditioners are like water filters, they filter out all the oddities and small fluctuations in power that slowly destroy electronics. In my opinion a power conditioner is one of the *BEST* investments you can make in prolonging the life of sensitive equipment. I took a chance after moving and my equipment was without a conditioner for a short while, but have used this non stop since ordering in August of 2011 with no issues. I immediately noticed a huge difference when I started using it. My monitors immediately stopped 'humming' when no audio was playing and I stopped hearing faint static that had developed when adjusting the volume on one of my mixers. If, like me, you don't have a whole house power conditioner, this is a small and affordable unit that should save several headaches in early equipment failures down the road. I use mine for studio and computer equipment, but it will also work just as well for a home entertainment center and HDTV's.

title_clean: Furman M-8X2 Merit Series 8 Outlet Power Conditioner and Surge Protector
description_clean: A Merit Series Power Conditioner is the perfect low-cost AC power solution for any rack mount system. Install an M-8x2 in to the top slot of your rack, and the eight switched outlets in the rear panel will power up and protect all your equipment up to a 15-amp load. The M-8x2 is designed for applications where lights are not required. Instrument Rigs: You've got a rack for your effects, preamps, tuner...You're going to plug that into the wall? One big spike and your rig is up in smoke. Furman's standard level surge/spike protection defends your gear from the spikes and surges that are so common at gigs and practice spots. With Furman's standard level RFI/EMI filtration, you'll get a quieter tone without pops, crackles, and the local radio station coming out of your amp. Recording: Can't track down where that noise is coming from? Your mix sounding flat? With Furman's standard level RFI/EMI filtration you'll lower the noise floor caused by the dirty AC power coming into your console or DAW. Furman's standard level surge and spike protection keeps your sensitive digital equipment from acting funny or burning up due to everyday spikes and surges. DJ Equipment: Bars, clubs and other event venues have some of the worst power out there - from air compressors turning on and off to light shows pulling current loads up and down, the AC power can be a strain on the circuits in your rig. Furman's standard level protection and filtration keeps the bad stuff out. Pro Audio: When you're out there gigging, you never know what kind of power you're going to get. The wear and tear on mobile rigs eventually takes its toll - that's why it's smart to plug into Furman's standard level protection and RFI/EMI filtration. It keeps your equipment safe and sounding clean. Whether you're setting up a show at the local club or powering up the church band for their next service, make sure you give them power they can trust.

reviewText: Pros:I didn't know what the track pad buttons would be like, but they are raised with little dimples so you can easily feel the 9 different selections without looking.Decent range, doesn't need line-of-sight.Light weight, feels solid.Cons:Wish it had a backlight keyboard, though that would probably drain battery pretty bad.It's a little large, I was hoping it would be the size of my blackberry, it basically requires two hands to type which isn't a huge disadvantage, especially since you don't have to hold it up and point it.Seems to go to sleep quickly, you have to wait a few seconds for it to wake up.You'll probably want to turn the sensitivity up if you have a large screen resolution.  This product is decent, not amazing.  If you own a blackberry, it is possible to use as an HTPC remote via bluetooth (do a google search-up), I prefer the size of something like a blackberry because the keyboard is easier to use.  This isn't a bad device, and for the price I can't necessarily say I'm disappointed.

reviewText: This is balanced for vibrant colors tending green/blue where the 100F is balanced more for reds/yellows as in faces, Fuji calles it Natural balance.  I take and develop my own slides then scan into epson 750 scanner for prints and e-storage if necessary.  I think the slides are so nice that it pains me to degrade them by scanning.  But for small prints It seems to be OK.  The grandkids get a bang out of taking pictures then film developing, then projecting on the wall.  Nice hobby this film stuff.  Oh yes, Transparency film is pretty fussy about exposure.  Just a 1/2 stop and the pict shows it. And correcting is darn near impossible or actually impossible (since the color is gone or black)  So using an old camera and teaching metering to the grandkids has really made them sharp photographers.  Even the 6 year old gets the exposure right almost all the time.  And now she is starting to experiment with adjusting speed and stop down and compensation (flash and regular) on her own for artistic effect. That didn't happen with the DSLR before we went to film.  Starting with a manual camera, in my case a Minolta SRT 200 SRT-102 or X700 and slide film has helped the young ones understand the photographic variables and a bit of the art of photography.  I am amazed how much an interested 6 year old can pick up.  We all know they remember every act and word we say but they actually remember other things too like big opening short time means water stops and small opening long time means water is blurred.  It is exciting to see them learn and opening the development can is a bit like Christmas.  I hope they keep making the fujichrome velvia for many years.

reviewText: You know, I'm not that old, but I remember when remotes were big clunky things with beautiful computer-beige bodies and the functions on a sticker that fell off so often it might as well have been marketed as removable. Of course, the culture of design changes almost as quickly as the technology that supports it - we have sleek (dare I say artistic?) computer cases, televisions that fade into the wall, and of course, control like the Apple remote. There's no doubt that this thing looks fantastic - I've always been in love with the anodized aluminum used by Apple, but there's something different about being able to palm it in remote form. I don't care if this thing was made by Apple or by Dell - it's a killer design.I have the updated version of this remote (the one with the indented menu button), and though it could be called overly simplistic, it really does almost everything you want it to do. I use several of these remotes on a daily basis- one attached to our Apple TV, and the other for my iMac. For bedroom use, I love that it only has seven buttons - there's no fumbling around in the dark trying to remember if menu is to the left of the red button or on the right of the subtitles key - when using the Apple remote you know exactly what you're doing at all times. Integration with Apple products is of course excellent - the remotes were designed to be complimentary and they truly are.The Apple Remote takes aCR2032 3 Volts Battery, easily accessed by twisting the cover on the back counter-clockwise. I was pleased to see they had updated the design from the white remotes - they were a PAIN to replace the batteries on. Speaking of batteries - one  year of use and I have yet to replace a battery. I have no idea what expected battery life is (seeing as it will vary greatly depending on use), but for normal every day use I am very pleased.So what's the caveat? It is simply NOT comfortable to hold in your hand. I mean, it's an experience and everything, but much like the iPad 2 and 3 and the iPhone from 4 onwards, Apple doesn't seem to be too concerned with the comfort of their edges. I know, I know, they LOOK fantastic, but so did the original iPad and they had rounder edges there. Either way, I don't hold this all day like I do my portable devices, but it's worth mentioning.I'm still rating this at five stars for sheer form and function, but I would not be disappointed to see a slight rounding of the edges. Highly recommended.- DOBrien
summary: Form and function meet, with one small caveat.

reviewText: This was installed in a Chevy Suburban, and it sounds good!  Nice, solid bass, but doesn't shake the truck (or the neighborhood).  Clean bass requires power, and this has that.  Getting power to run it required a direct, fused lead to the battery, and then it was pretty easy.  I am running two 12" woofers, and getting no discernible distortion.  I took off one star because it gets pretty warm.

reviewText: This car charger is powerful enough to charge two tablets at the same time.  It has two USB ports and each one can output 2.1 Amps at the same time.  I like that the ports output the same current levels as when you are plugging something into the charger you don't have to worry if you are using the right port for your device.  This charger can output 4.2 amps total and that is ideal for use in your car, SUV, truck or mobile home to keep your smart devices fully charged.  At 2.1 amps per port your devices can charge quickly and safely.The unit will not charge two iPads at the same time as only one port can be detected by an iPad.  This is because the iPad requires special circuit impedance that is present in only one of the two ports.  The second port can be used to charge an iPhone or an Android device.The unit is nicely designed and it fits snugly into my car's charger port.  There is a LED on the unit that indicates that the unit is powered.  I like that this is a high powered charger and that it has protection built in for over-heating, over-charging and over-current.  This protects your vehicle, your devices and the charger.This is a nice quality product and it works well.  I rated it as a 5 star product.I was supplied a sample for test and evaluation and I promised a fair and honest review.
summary: A nicely designed and powerful dual USB port car charger!

reviewText: I currently own the Tylt UPPLANT2-T Powerplant but I decided to give this sleek looking battery pack a try.Pros:I like that it comes fully charged, so no waiting to charge it before using it. I also like the nice slick aluminum appearance and it did power my iPod. Unfortunately, that’s about all I can say on the positive side.Cons:Though it did charge my iPod, it only charged it to about 75%. — My Tylt UPPLANT2-T Powerplant isn’t as sleek looking (it looks like a black brick) but it can charge my iPod to 100% twice before having to recharge its battery. It can also charge two units at the same time.Though both power packs are a little expensive, the myCharge costs more than the Tylt UPPLANT2-T Powerplant but does less. So with its high price and with its limitations, I reluctantly can’t recommend buying the myCharge battery pack.

reviewText: The wireless works fine, is fast, and the config has all the usual features of a home router. However I bought a 32GB flash drive to use as network attached storage (NAS) and there is some issue with permissions when deleting write protected files and folders. For some reason you need root access to do that and this is not the usual access method when accessing the NAS through Windows 7. I'm a technician and tried various things, formatting the drive with different file systems, updated the router firmware, but found no solution and gave up.

reviewText: Only thing I missed was Bluetooth, my wife's P8Z68 V Pro motherboard had BT, yet was missing from this, but I picked up WiFi, so it works out.Updated BIOS helped with ISRT/SSD function as it was quite fussy until the update was done.  I've only built a few computers so can't compare this board to many others, but the BIOS setup screens are pretty easy to navigate, the instruction book makes everything pretty clear.My only complaints (minor ones, I did give it 5 stars) is with the instructions for some of the BIOS setup information.  Perhaps it's my noob status as a computer builder, but I tried to look up info about xHCI Mode because I saw it in the BIOS setup page.  Books says "enables optimized xHCI".  Real helpful.  Some other features it has more info about to give you some basic info about if that feature is needed or not.  If you're a noob builder, it's worth going through all the options and considering how to set each one, as the defaults aren't always what you want or need.

reviewText: When it comes to buying Asus, I'm usually pleased with the quality.  I was not let down with this purchase except when it came to the height of the card - it's just a wee bit taller than my Apevia Q-Pack2 sliding motherboard tray accommodates.When it comes to performance, I'm getting at least around 30fps average in the Heaven benchmark.  3dMark 2011 not so much... but if you play games like Diablo 3 don't sweat.  The card runs off the power supplied by the PCI-E slot so no extra power cable!  It's also low wattage and runs very quiet.For the price (currently @ $109) it is so worth it. I was hoping the HD4000 integrated graphics of my Intel Core i5 3570K was enough; not if you want decent eye candy though.  In case you're wondering what the V2 version of the card is, it's better capacitors.  Always something, right?UPDATE (7/14/2012) - I've uploaded a couple pics showing the correct backplate view and also the height issue.

reviewText: I didn't realize this drive is for Mac native. To use it with Windows, a HFS+ software need to be downloaded and installed to the PC system first. Since I don't have MAC, I simply reformat the whole drive for NTFS. After that, the drive is really plug-and-play in Window-based PCs.My PC is an iCore7 system with 6 USB2 port, 2 USB3 ports and 1 eSATA port. I usually do weekly backup to backup user data files to external drive. Each backup is about 128GB. It takes at least half day to complete the backup with USB2 connection. Or about 1.5 hour to complete the backup with eSATA connection. This is my first USB3 drive that I can see how fast it goes. The outcome: about 1.5 hour to complete the backup. So, about the same speed as my eSATA hard drive.However, the eSATA driver requires external power plug. But this Seagate drive is fully powered by the USB3 cable directly. It occupies only one USB3 port (not TWO). Some USB2-powered devices will take two USB2 ports. There is no ON/OFF switch. When I turn on my PC, this driver is automatically powered on too. When I shut off my PC, this driver is also off. When my PC goes into sleep mode, I can tell this drive is go sleeping.All in all, this is a fast, portable external drive with very small form factor.
summary: A fast, portable external drive with very small form factor.

reviewText: The PJ790V camera I'm testing is an update to the older PJ760V of the Sony's top of the consumer line. While it is an incremental update, it brings a very good package of features, and if you're planning to use a single camcorder on different occasions, this might be a very good choice.The main differences with the previous model are the external surround microphone (which reduces internal noise in recordings), and a better projector system (including a brighter light, and an HDMI input). However it still shares familiar the optics of the previous gen, and it is not a bad thing.I tested it in both outdoor, and indoor conditions. At all occasions it produced great quality results. Even when it had difficulty indoors, the camera offered sufficient manual controls for compensating with worse lighting. And of course for very low to no light situations, there is night vision (infrared) recording, at the cost of losing color, and a big drain on the battery.The image stabilizer handled vertical shakes very well. Sony has designed the entire optical system (including the sensor) with movable parts, and it easily compensates for regular shake of the hand. While it would not be perfect, you can actually use the camera while walking -- this should be the one of the first things you try with the camera, and it is very satisfying to see the anti-shake mechanism in actionThe additional features, like the GPS tagging, a large storage (96G), external USB and SD card support (for quick backups) will help with longer trips. The projector, while sounding like a questionable addon, is actually very good for quickly showing something to friends or family. And smile detection shoots automatic pictures while recording a crowd, which is very handy.The product comes as an almost complete package. The Carl-Ziess lens, 10-17x optical zoom, built in usb cable, bundled wind screen, HD lcd touchscreen, lower powered viewfinder, leaves almost nothing to be desired. But there is always a but...I had two issues with it that I should tell. First of all the bundled battery has a very low capacity. Sony's ownNP-FV100is a must for extended use without power, anda chargerwill help keeping spare batteries charged while the main one is in use. Of course, it's also possible to buy them much cheaply from 3rd party manufacturers (for example, I had good experience withWasabi Power products). The second thing lacking is the internal WiFi module. It already has an antenna for GPS, and most radio chips can handle both of them at the same time. However Sony will require buyinga separate Wi-Fi adapter.But except for these issues, I found everything I could look for in a camera (at least consumer ones). It's a very good recommendation, if you need to shoot high quality videos, in many different occasions (events, trips, picnics, talks, and even safaris).
summary: Sony's Flagship Camera does not Disappoint

Sony has designed the entire optical system (including the sensor) with movable parts, and it easily compensates for regular shake of the hand. While it would not be perfect, you can actually use the camera while walking -- this should be the one of the first things you try with the camera, and it is very satisfying to see the anti-shake mechanism in actionThe additional features, like the GPS tagging, a large storage (96G), external USB and SD card support (for quick backups) will help with longer trips. The projector, while sounding like a questionable addon, is actually very good for quickly showing something to friends or family. And smile detection shoots automatic pictures while recording a crowd, which is very handy.The product comes as an almost complete package. The Carl-Ziess lens, 10-17x optical zoom, built in usb cable, bundled wind screen, HD lcd touchscreen, lower powered viewfinder, leaves almost nothing to be desired. But there is always a but...I had two issues with it that I should tell. First of all the bundled battery has a very low capacity. Sony's ownNP-FV100is a must for extended use without power, anda chargerwill help keeping spare batteries charged while the main one is in use. Of course, it's also possible to buy them much cheaply from 3rd party manufacturers (for example, I had good experience withWasabi Power products). The second thing lacking is the internal WiFi module. It already has an antenna for GPS, and most radio chips can handle both of them at the same time. However Sony will require buyinga separate Wi-Fi adapter.But except for these issues, I found everything I could look for in a camera (at least consumer ones). It's a very good recommendation, if you need to shoot high quality videos, in many different occasions (events, trips, picnics, talks, and even safaris).
summary_clean: Sony's Flagship Camera does not Disappoint

reviewText: I am not an audiophile.  I have been content with my TV speakers for years.  I have never owned an audio receiver, and I have never owned any speakers for my television.  I have always liked the idea of a "sound bar", as well as owning a subwoofer.  I love movies, so you'd think this would have been something I bought long ago.  I held off on it for a long time because I live in an apartment, and I never liked the idea of a subwoofer shaking my place and possibly upsetting the neighbors.  This device has a solution for that, which I will go into in a minute.First, set up is a breeze.  You literally do nothing - no waiting, no pairing.  Just plug it in.  Even the wireless subwoofer you just plug into a power outlet.  I'm told that the human brain cannot detect which direction low-frequency sounds are coming from, so I have this sitting across the room behind my couch.Second, there are many, many sound options.  There's a "Movie" mode, a "Game" mode.  Even a "Sports" mode.  Again, I'm not an audiophile, so I can't tell the difference.  What I CAN tell the difference on are two wonderful options; Voice and Night modes.  I am terrible at picking out people talking when there is other noises going on.  Crowded restaurants - forget it.  I have taken to reading lips - or at least watching people's lips when they speak - it helps so much.  But - this thing has a "Voice" button on the remote and has several options when you hit that button which amps up the vocals for whatever it is you're watching.  It's been a lifesaver for me!  The Night mode is also a life-saver; when it's dark out, I use the "night" mode and it kills the super-bass you get from that subwoofer.  Everything sounds great still, but now my couch won't shake when there's an explosion on TV!  I love that feature too.Third; I don't like the app.  I don't use it.  I don't get it.  Why is it every device out there thinks it needs an app?  My Blu-ray player has one, my little ipod speaker thing has one.  Who uses them?  It just kills my battery on my iphone.  And for a speaker - it just needs to crank out sound - that's it.  Who needs an app for that???Fourth; there are only 3 HDMI inputs.  The idea being, you plug your HDMI cable from your Blu-ray into the sound bar, then another cable to the TV.  Do you know how many HDMI devices I have?  5; Cable box, Blu-Ray player, Xbox 360, a Roku 2 box and that lame Chromecast thing.  Now, this device comes with one of those old-school "light" cables- remember when those were the wave of the future back in 1999?  Fiber-optic.  That's it.  Anyhow, my TV thankfully has an output for that cable - so anything on TV will play through the sound bar.  WITH a slight delay - I notice it all the time and it drives me batty.  So - I don't suggest using that but since I have 5 devices and only 3 inputs - what else can I do?Overall I like it very much.  The options to customize what you're hearing are excellent, and it looks awesome sitting under my TV.  The wireless subwoofer is idiot-proof and you'll get a kick out of it for sure.
summary: I like it well enough.  The app is unnecessary

title_clean: Belkin 3-Outlet Mini Travel Swivel Charger Surge Protector with Dual USB Ports, 5 Charging Outlets Total (1 AMP / 5 Watt)
description_clean: Whether you're crossing continents or just heading across town, the Belkin BZ103050-TVL Mini Surge Protector/Dual USB Charger is the type of travel companion that makes your life easier. Featuring three protected AC outlets, two protected, powered USB outlets, and a unique rotating plug design that lets you work in tight spaces, this compact surge protector lets you plug in and charge all your essential devices wherever you are.Mini Surge Protector/Dual USB ChargerAt a Glance:3 AC outlets and 2 powered USB portsComplete protection on all outlets360-degree rotating plug with 4 locking positionsIncludes mini-USB cable for charging phones, MP3 players, and other devicesLifetime Product and $75,000 Connected Equipment WarrantiesYou can easily slip this mini surge protector into your laptop bag or carry-on.Includes mini-USB cable for charging phones, MP3 players, and other devices.Convenient, Dependable Design for Worry-Free TravelHotel rooms, airport terminals, and coffee shops never seem to have enough power outlets to handle all your devices at once. With the Belkin Mini Surge Protector you no longer have to choose what to charge first.This surge protector acts as a power strip, letting you plug three AC devices into a single wall outlet. It is rated to handle 918 Joules and provides protection against power surges and spikes, since the smart traveler is looking for protection of essential gear and irreplaceable data, not just extra outlets.Two Powered USB Outlets Let You Charge More Devices EasilyIn addition to its three AC outlets, this surge protector features two protected, powered USB outlets, so you can easily charge your iPod along with other USB devices. These USB outlets do not transmit data and the surge protector cannot be used as a hub, but they do make it exceptionally easy to keep devices that are charged via USB interfaces up and running without blocking your computer's USB ports or the AC outlets that you need for bigger devices.Plus you may be able to leave long, tangle-friendly cords and clunky item-specific chargers at home, since this mini surge protector comes with a mini-USB cable. This is especially convenient now that many phones, including Blackberries and Motorola RAZR phones, feature USB power connections.Unique, Efficient Design with Rotating Plug for Added VersatilityIts compact, lightweight, and efficient design means that you can easily slip this mini surge protector into your laptop bag or carry-on, and because Belkin knows that working on the road often means trying to plug in despite awkward outlet or furniture positioning, a 360-degree rotating plug with four locking positions makes it easy to use this device in tight spaces.About Belkin International, Inc.Belkin offers a diverse product mix that provides people with seamless electronics integration in their homes, cars, and on the go. Founded in California in 1983, Belkin is a privately held company and the recognized leader in connectivity solutions, in addition to accessories for MP3 devices, computers, and more. We provide extensive solutions for networking, home theater-with our PureAV line of cables, power, and digital wireless accessories-and many more categories. Belkin's phenomenal growth has led to our expanding global presence. In addition to corporate headquarters in Los Angeles, we now have offices throughout Europe-in the United Kingdom, the Netherlands, and Germany, among others-and in the Asia Pacific region, including Australia, Shanghai, and our regional headquarters in Hong Kong.The Belkin Mini Surge Protector/Dual USB Charger is backed by a lifetime warranty and a $75,000 Connected Equipment Warranty.What's in the BoxMini Surge Protector/Dual USB Charger, mini-USB power cable, and user guide.Wall-MountedConnected Equipment WarrantyNumber of OutletsUSB PortsJoule RatingNetwork ProtectionPhone Line ProtectionCoax ProtectionPower Safety Shut DownOverload ProtectionCord LengthWarrantyMini$75,00032918NoNoNoYesYesWall-mountLifetime1-Outlet Wall-Mount$50,0001 1045NoYesNoYesYesWall-mountLifetime6-Outlet Wall-Mount$50,0006 1045NoYesNoYesYesWall-mountLifetime

reviewText: UPDATE 9/2/12I did order a new cable and it was as good as the first cable that I ordered.These cables cost much less than you'll spend for a lunch. Get a spare or two.I'm removing my pictures. The company selling them now is a different company and shouldn't catch any blame for the bad cable I received.------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------UPDATE 6/6/12My new cable came in and was a major disappointment (See the pictures at the top of the product page).The SAMSUNG cover on the wide connector that attaches to the Galaxy Tab 2 7.0 pulls off with the slightest pull when trying to disconnect it from the Tab. If that were the only problem I would have kept the cable and just glued it in place.The real killer was at the USB end of the cable - there is no protective rubber "boot" on the cable where it goes into the USB housing ***AND*** the shielding within the cable, as it goes into the USB housing, is exposed.Other minor differences were a low grade finish on the metal parts, the cable/connector itself has been manufactured differently, and a slightly lower grade USB logo on the USB housing.With everything taken together I'm not too sure that *this* is a real SAMSUNG cable. The first one that they sent was fine, so I'll order another one after the refund. And you can bet that I'll look it over very carefully!------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------UPDATE 6/1/12This is so handy that I ordered a 3rd one. One for work, one for my van, and one for home.------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------This cable works perfectly with my Galaxy Tab 2 7.0.It'll charge the Tab while plugged into my desktop *slowly* as I use it, **BUT** that's because a desktop/laptop USB is designed to provides less current.When used with the Samsung 110 charger, or theRND Power Solutions Dual Black USB car charger for Tabletswhich provides 2.1 amps it works as well as the original.Buy several and you won't need to keep track of where you left it.
summary: I now have 2 of these cables and will soon buy anoither

reviewText: This is an upgrade to replace an NZXT Source 210 (a great case) for a customer that wanted to add water cooling for their system and future upgradability.This is a big case, and the HAF in the name implies high airflow, and you get a lot of it with this box. I was surprised that it's a mid tower, as it's big enough to be a full tower. It's 22.5"L x 9.9" W x 20.9" H, so it's pretty big. It weighs around 22 lbs. It's made mostly of plastic and sheet metal. The plastic and sheet metal aren't thin and flimsy, and seem very sturdy and well-made. The PSU is on the bottom where it should be. The front panel came off easily, and the knock-outs for the expansion bays came out without a hassle as well. Inside it's painted black with a textured finish that's durable and unlikely to chip or rub off. Same with the mesh panels, which are plastic and would resist denting. The hard drive trays are plastic, which is good. There are also dust filters that you can change.It includes a lot of features, but it should considering you pay for it. Included are 3 fans. You get a 200mm fans in the front behind the front panel in front of the hard drive bays, a 200mm fan on top under the removable dust cover, and a 140mm fan at the rear above the expansion slots. The front fan is clear and it has a red LED in it that's controlled from the front panel. You can put up to four 200mm fans in here, top, front, and on the side if you wanted to, or up to 9 smaller fans. There's ample room for mounting a water cooling system. The H100i radiator fit with tons of room to spare.The side front side access panel is latched so it comes off easy, but it's held on with thumbscrews also. The other side panel also comes off so you can access the back of the motherboard and route cables. There is plenty of room for cables and the passthroughs are covered with rubber grommets ti protect the cables. There are lots of passthroughs and they are placed conveniently. I did run into some issues with them though as some cables couldn't reach across the back of the motherboard to get to the ATX input for the CPU, and the two 8-pin PCIe connectors wouldn't reach the graphics card if I ran them from behind.You also get lots of expandability. There are three 5.25" and one 2.5" external bays for optical drives, fan controllers, USB hubs, or multi card readers. One is an X-Dock that's for 2.5" hard drives that plug into a daughterboard. It has Molex power plug and two SATA connectors that get plugged into the motherboard and PSU. There are 6 hard drive trays for 2.5" and 3.5" hard drives or SSD's. They are quick release bays (which I like) that unlock and pull out easily. There aren't adapters for the 2.5" drives in them though, but 3.5" drives are held in by metal pins on rubber grommets so there's no screws needed. The front panel has three buttons, a power, reset, and one for the front fan's LED. There are also 2 USB 3.0 and 2.0 ports, audio in and out (supports digital audio). The power button and HDD activity are illuminated with red LED's. Out back there's an I/O for the main board, and an 8+1 expansion slots for expansion cards, so you can run 3-way SLI or CrossfireX no problem with the full-size graphics cards (18+ inches long with the HDD cage removed). The cut-outs are metal with vent cutouts, and are screwed in so you can reinstall them if you need to. On the top there's a removable cover that can house cans or a radiator. It's held on with a thumbscrew at the rear and slides off easily. There's also a rubber-lined tray on top for holding your phone, keys, change, or whatever else.Cooler Master makes some really great products, and this is no exception. Installing the motherboard was very easy, although the standoffs had a little trouble going in. It's marked for mATX, ATX, and E ATX boards. I had no issues with the Corsair H100i water cooler either. The fans and radiator went in no problem. Installing the SSD was easy, and routing the cables wasn't an exercise in futility as there was lots of passthroughs and they were large enough. The bottom PSU also has a sliding cover to conceal cables as well. Nice touch. The fans were very quiet when running as well.What I like:Sturdy and well-madeGood lookingLots of expandabilityExcellent airflow capabilities with tons of fan mountsLots of cable passthroughs with rubber grommetsQuick release HDD traysDust filtersIncludes two 200mm and one 140mm quiet fansFront USB 3.0Quick release side panel and top coverWhat I don't like:Huge for a mid-towerHeavyQuick release panel is screwed on with thumbscrewsButtons felt cheapExpensiveWould have liked to see the front panel connectors in a single plug like on other high-end casesOverall this is a great box. Excellent for an overclocked system with big coolers, water coolers, or lots of fans, multiple GPUs or expansion cards. You could use this for a server as well with good results. I liked the fans and how easy it was to manage cables. Aside from the little quirks, I think the HAF MX is a great deal.

reviewText: This is a bigger power supply, check your dimensions to make sure it will fit your application space.Pro: Fully modular so you only use what you need and have a very clean install. Awesome cables that are sleeved very well. Very flexible wires for easy manipulation.  Comes with every kind of connector you will need.  Evga has awesome customer service, and it has a very long 10 year warranty!Cons: only size limitations and it is not really a con.This power supply is a beast, it handles my high end gaming system with 2 R9 290's with no problem, I was able to push it to over 800watts with overclocking. Unfortunately my video cards generated too much heat inside the case, and I decided it would be better to split them into 2 systems. Now my sytem is super quiet, efficient and has plenty of GPU power to run whatever I want.Here are some facts you need to know when picking out equipment for a build.1) Never exceed 400 watts of (video cards) power, which translates directly into heat produced, in an enclosed case with air cooling. Your main PCIE16 card will be hotter because of radiant heat from the second card. This will make card 1 throttle more to control the heat, which will equal bad performance. (This exponentially multiplies with more cards.)  It will also lead to all your fans running at 100%  2+ high end video cards (above 200 watts each) I reccommend liquid cooling the GPU's.  Reference "hamster fans" are extremey loud and sound like a hair dryer running, I do not recomended them.2) It is fine to overkill your Power supply! Honestly you should double the wattage of the PS to what you think you will use. It allows for growth and overclocking if you want.  Power Supplies run most efficiently at 50% of thier rated wattage and once you hit 70% efficiency goes down fast, while heat increases.3) One 24vdc rail is the best, and most versatile for multiple video card setups because you do not waist power.4) Fully Modular is the ONLY way to go5) Spend the extra money on a GOLD standard power supply, you will have a super stable and reliable system because you did.6) NEVER use power supply cables from ANOTHER power supply, because they can be wired different at the PS. USE ONLY THE POWER CONNECTORS THAT ARE SUPPLIED with this POWER SUPPLY.  I know this because I have fried components before.
