title_clean: Celestron SkyMaster Giant 15x70 Binoculars with Tripod Adapter
description_clean: Binoculars come in a wide range of shapes and sizes these days, and an even wider range of prices. It's easy to spend less than $100 or more than $500 for what may appear to be, at least outwardly, comparable models. While they may look the same, they are probably quite different on the inside.Recently, the binocular market has seen a flood of giant binoculars at prices that were unheard of just a few years ago. In general, giant binoculars are defined as those that magnify the view 10 times or more and have 70-mm or larger front (objective) lenses. It used to be that the least expensive giant binoculars cost in excess of $150, even $200. All that changed not long ago, when the bottom fell out of the price cellar. Now, several companies import giant binoculars that sell for half that, or less.Celestron's 15x70 SkyMaster binoculars are one of the leaders in the low-price giant binocular arena. They certainly sound good on paper. The SkyMasters include multicoated optics and BaK-4 internal prisms, two features that promise brighter, better images, and key points to look for when judging a pair of binoculars. They also come with an adapter for attaching them to a photo tripod, which is a must to use them to their fullest, and a soft carrying case. But just because they are cheap doesn't always mean they are worth the price. Would it be better to save up for a more expensive pair?To find the answer, I had an opportunity recently to judge the SkyMasters against a pair ofFujinon 16x70 FMT-SX binoculars, one of the finest pairs of giant binoculars sold today. Like the SkyMasters, the Fujinons feature BaK-4 prisms, but also have fully multicoated optics. As a general rule, superior coatings mean superior image sharpness and contrast. But then, that should be expected, given that the Fujinons cost many times more than the Celestrons.While the Fujinons were clearly the better performer, the Celestron SkyMasters held up admirably. Image brightness, quality, and contrast were all remarkable considering their bargain price. Although images were a little soft across the outer 25% of the Celestron's field, the overall view was impressive nonetheless.Some inexpensive binoculars have very sloppy focusing, causing the eyepieces to tilt and shift. Not so with the SkyMasters. I found that their center-focusing mechanism worked smoothly, with no apparently backlash or wobble. Eye relief (the distance you hold your eyes away from the eyepieces to see the full field) is stated to be 18 mm, a good distance for higher power binoculars and an important consideration if you must wear glasses when viewing. The SkyMasters are also light enough to support by hand for short periods of time, although buyers would be well advised to mount them on a sturdy photo tripod.The bottom line is, if you are considering a pair of giant binoculars, whether for bird watching, stargazing, or another recreational use, and have a limited budget, Celestron's giant 15x70 SkyMasters represent an excellent value. --Phil Harrington, author ofStar WareandStar WatchPros:Exceptional value for the priceLight enough to support by handBaK-4 prismsMulticoated opticsCons:Outer 25% of the field is soft and a little blurryRequires a tripod to use for extended periods

reviewText: These earphones are a true pleasure to use.  They are crystal clear, have a quality bass, and possess an amazing dynamic range to them.  I particularly like the flat cord that keeps them from getting tangled, and the slider adjustment to add your personal fit to it.  Although the set arrived with a generous amount of alternative buds, I found the ones on the set to fit just fine.  These phones have a quality feel to them that I have not found even in phones that cost twice as much.  In fact I like them so much I planned on giving these to my son but decided to keep them for myself.  You can't do any better for the price in my opinion, and I highly recommend these babies... : )Note:  I received a free pair of these headphones in return for a fair and honest review, which is exactly what they got.. : )

Although the set arrived with a generous amount of alternative buds, I found the ones on the set to fit just fine. These phones have a quality feel to them that I have not found even in phones that cost twice as much. In fact I like them so much I planned on giving these to my son but decided to keep them for myself. You can't do any better for the price in my opinion, and I highly recommend these babies... : )Note: I received a free pair of these headphones in return for a fair and honest review, which is exactly what they got.. : )

reviewText: I have had devices which promised to allow me to pretty much eliminate the need to keep my actual DVDs and/or CDs but because of limitations associated with the ease of use, need for hard-wired network connections, compatibility with my system (computer or Home theater), it always fell short.This drive has basically allowed me to remove all of my DVDs and CDs from the living room.  I'm not disposing of them... yet.  (I hate the thought that something might happen to this drive and then I would be starting over again).  But then again, I have had good luck with Seagate drives and assuming I don't have a massive failure on ALL my electronics, should be pretty safe.Streaming is great -- you are able to take advantage of the fact that your bandwidth issues are not INSIDE the house -- they exist from the ISP (in other words, even though you may be on a cable modem, you generally won't achieve the performance promised by TWC because you are competing with the rest of the houses in your neighborhood for bandwidth and you can't control that.However, you CAN control the bandwidth inside your house and as a result, the performance associate with streaming from this drive is much better than streaming from the cloud.  As a result, your playback experience is much much better.I also love the portability aspect and cross platform aspect associated with using this device.  You are no longer tied to only being able to have your collection at home.  Going to the beach?  Great -- bring this with you and you don't have to worry about bringing all the kids favorite DVDs that you'll need when it rains.  Want to be able to share your pictures with family when you go to the family reunion -- its all here... no need to worry about did you remember to keep it synced on your iPad/tablet/computer/cloud drive.I love cloud technology but because of the limitations of external internet -- I really like to be able to control my own files and libraries -- but I just don't have the room (or desire to look at cabinets full of jewel cases) to keep all that down in my main TV Viewing area.  This drive provides you with the ability to back up your files and use them without with ease.[NCJVR]

reviewText: I recently heard a report that a major complaint with the iPhone 5 was that is was too small, too light and too thin.That is my major complaint about this Sony underwater camera. It is hard to hold.  It is hard to push the correct buttons.  But you do get used to it.The other problem is the picture to picture time.  Once you take a picture it seems like several seconds before you can take another picture, though it is only just over a second (most times).Other than that it is a very nice camera.It takes beautiful pictures in and out of the water.  One note after coming out of the water, the lens does tend to spot.  So make sure you rinse it off well or wipe it.The panoramic function is easy to use and pretty cool.It also takes very nice videos.  Even underwater, though the sound is strange underwater (as expected).I've added some pictures to this pages as examples.I recommend this underwater camera.I've included some pictures as an example.I recommend this underwater camera.

reviewText: Only have 8 or 16gig on your phone or tablet? Don't worry, load this up with movies, music, etc, and have up to 4 devices connect and stream media from it. Connects to PC or MAC via USB 2.0. Take it on the go, it is very small and thin and light weight. Turn it on and use it to create a hotspot. Join that hotspot and stream media files to your devices. If there is a network present for internet, this guy can bridge that connection so even when you are connected to its personal wifi spot, you still have internet.I've connected up to three devices and streamed video to them with no lag or issues. Range is good, but not like your home router, so don't expect a great experience leaving this upstairs and go downstairs or outside to stream from it. The form factor feels like another phone in your carry inventory. It is that small and thin. Great for family adventures out to keep the kids busy.There was not anything I did not really like about this device. A win!
summary: A Great Storage addon solution for SmartPhones and Tablets!

reviewText: I have tried many BT headsets, searching for just the right combination of comfort, battery life, and reliability. The S305 is as good as it gets. I can wear these headphones for hours in comfort. A fully charged battery will last for 8 to 10 hours, and these headphones are durable. I finally destroyed a pair of these after a few years. The muffies were gone, the battery life down to 5 or 6 hours, and the BT connection started to drop on occasion. I replaced them with the exact same unit and I am very happy with the selection. I use the S305 with an iPod, iPad, laptop, and mobile phone. No problems. I would give this headset 5 starts if it had replaceable muffies.

title_clean: Motorola S305 Bluetooth Stereo Headset w/ Microphone (Black) - Retail Packaging
description_clean: The Motorola MOTOROKR™ S305 Stereo Headset delivers style, performance, and remarkable sound for your iPhone, iPod, or other stereo-capable Bluetooth® device. This lightweight headset lets you make hands-free calls and wirelessly listen to music so you'll stay tuned-in and hooked-up no matter where you're headed.Motorola MOTOROKR™ S305 Stereo HeadsetAt a Glance:Bluetooth headset lets you listen to music or take phone calls wirelessly.High-quality speakers deliver crisp, rich sound and deep bass.Accept incoming calls or toggle between tracks with the touch of a button.Lightweight, comfortable design for all-day listening.Listen to music in full-range stereo and make hands-free calls with the S305.View larger.Speakers Deliver Robust Audio PerformanceThe S305 lets you wirelessly stream music from any compatible Bluetooth stereo-capable device, including the iPhone 3G, iPhone 3G S, and iPod touch 2G. The headphones generate rich, deep sound thanks to two high-quality 30mm speakers. With strong bass and dynamic audio, the headphones render all the highs and mids of your music with superb fidelity. You'll also enjoy remarkable call clarity without ambient background noise.Music Pauses for Incoming CallsThanks to a small, high-grade microphone located beneath the right speaker, the S305 will pick up your voice in crisp detail. And if you should receive a call while your tunes are playing, the music will automatically pause. Just press the call button on the side of the headset to accept an incoming call.Comfortable, Lightweight DesignWith its stylish silver-and-black finish, the S305 headset has a sleek, futuristic look. Just as comfortable as it is attractive, the headset features a curved, behind-the-head wearing style and weighs less than comparable products. Also, the over-the-ear headphones are cushioned, making them soft enough for all-day listening.Easy-to-Use ControlsThe S305 has a control interface that allows you to adjust volume, accept calls, and switch music tracks with ease. A large call button on the side of the right speaker makes it simple to accept incoming calls and make outgoing calls. By tapping on either side of this button, you can also remotely change music tracks. Additionally, a conveniently placed volume button lets you adjust the volume of your music or phone call at any time.Long-Lasting Charge and Universal Bluetooth CompatibilityThe S305 provides up to 6.5 hours of uninterrupted talk or music. For added convenience, a micro-USB charging port is included on the side of the device.The stylish and lightweight S305 offers comfortable, all-day listening.View larger.The headset also features universal compatibility and can be used with any Bluetooth-enabled device--it's simple to set up and takes only seconds to sync. A special adapter (sold separately) may be required for use with MP3 players, iPhones, and PCs.About MotorolaMotorola, a recognized leader in mobile connectivity, is committed to developing tools and technologies to make people's lives easier, more efficient, and more connected. Founded in 1928, Motorola's prominent record of invention and innovation includes equipment that carried the first words spoken from the moon as well as the world's first handheld cellular phone. Now, with their new line of Bluetooth® headsets, Motorola continues to change the shape of communications by developing technologies to eliminate boundaries for people, businesses, and public safety agencies, enhancing and advancing how they communicate.

reviewText: After using the NTV300 for a couple of weeks I am disappointed in the performance of this product. I connected my Neotv NTV300 directly to my router via Ethernet. My internet service speed is 20 mbs and the NTV300 shows a download capability of 8.6 mbs. I have experienced several screen freeze ups and very slow performance. I bought this product because it has Netflix, Vudu and HuluPlus which I have accounts with. When using Hulu the streamer it will tend to freeze up when Hulu finishes a commercial. Will also freeze during streaming of shows. I have also noticed that when in Netflix and using the search function, the results shown don't always match what is selected in the scroll of listed programs. Sometimes Netflix will freeze up too.  Other things include slow start up time, it takes about 35-40 sec to bring screen up, slow response to remote inputs, sometime you'll press the button 2 or 3 times (because you think the unit didn't receive that command) before the unit responds, causing the unit to jump pass the selection you're trying to make. I think they put the NTV300 on the market before they completed QC. I also have a NTV200 which performs perfectly. It starts quickly, responds to remote quickly and doesn't freeze up. I like the Neotv units because they have a Ethernet port to connect directly to your router, and they support 1080p resolution. You have to spend almost $100.00 to get a Roku with Ethernet connection. If you're looking for a unit that supports 1080p and has a Ethernet connection and cheap, then this is your unit. I hope that Netgear will have a fix for the list of known issues shortly.Update: After 3 weeks of use I have given up on the NTV300. It is a very poor performer. Pictures freeze regulary, today I couldn't access Hulu. It kept saying I needed to update date and time in my settings. There is no date or time functions in settings. If you pause for a few minutes, then restart, the picture will show a couple of sec but then it will freeze. I should mention that I have the latest software ver 1.1.2NA installed but problems persist. Don't know what the update was suppose to fix. Apprently nothing. I do have a Netgrear NTV200 which works perfectly. It has a different software program.

reviewText: I purchased the Sanyo Eneloop AAA, Sanyo Eneloop AA, and Sanyo Eneloop XX AA batteries. Since Amazon clumps them all together, this review is about those 3 items.Being an average user with remotes, flashlights, toys, game controllers, I've gone through hundreds of akaline batteries. I've even upgraded to use those Lithium branded ones that Energizer and Duracell sells, but those things carry a premium price (like $20 for a pack of 4). Over my life, I've probably spent thousands of dollars on disposable batteries. Tired of spending money on disposables, a couple years ago I bought one of those Duracell rechargeable battery kits from Walmart. It came with a 4-battery wall charger and 4 2000mAh batteries (made in China). Over time, those four batteries held up their end (I used them in my digital camera) but 2 of those batteries never kept their charge for long and I ended up throwing them away. I still have the other two and they work "OK".Recently about a year or so ago, I needed some more batteries and I only had 4 rechargeables from my original Durcell kit. I ended up buying a 4-pack of Duracell Rechargeable 2450mAh (made in Japan) and an even newer 4-pack of Duracell Rechargeable 2650mAh (made in Japan). Those worked pretty good but because of the number of devices I have requiring batteries, I needed to invest more in batteries... but I wasn't about to until I did more research on what were the best because my past rechargeable battery experiences were either a hit or miss.From my research (just Google for best rechargeable batteries) I learned that the best rechargeable batteries come from Japan (the China ones are OK) and Duracell actually sometimes rebrands batteries made by Sanyo (their Eneloop line). Now I know why my Chinese Duracells never lasted quite as long as my Japanese Duracells! I also learned that the wall charger (most of them that come with rechargeable batteries these days) I got with my kit do not charge batteries properly and is one of the reasons why all my batteries don't seem to last as long as they did when I first bought them.In addition, I found a great resource on Amazon, "NLee the Engineer" who knows his stuff about batteries & chargers (he's an electrical engineer). Based on his FAQs & reviews, I made my choice for a good charger & rechargeable batteries by his recommendation. So in one swoop, I invested in an intelligent battery charger (Maha C9000) and a handful of Sanyo Eneloop batteries (over $100 worth).Upon receiving the batteries, I verified that they were indeed the *latest* generation of Sanyo Eneloops (they have a grayish-silver crown logo on the side of them). While there is very little difference between the prior generation and the latest, the latest ones are slightly better and if I'm going to drop over $100 on batteries, I want to make sure I got the best & latest.The Eneloop packaging & several review sites stated that the Sanyo Eneloops are top rated because they have 1) a high durability, allowing estimated 1500 charges and 2) low self-discharge rate, maintains a large percentage of its charge after 3 years. While I can't attest to either because I only had them for a short period of time, I can say that they are very good when I used them in conjunction with my Maha C9000 charger. They power everything I have without issues (I had some weird issues with other types not powering up some devices).One thing I will say to be aware of is that the white Eneloops are rated at 2000 mAH. Other brands do boast a higher mAH and the higher the mAH, the more "juice" you have for your devices. Some people consider 2000 mAH to be a little low for some high powered devices. My Duracells (~$14), which I'm fairly certain are rebranded Eneloops, have a similar rating to that of the Eneloop XX brand (Sanyo XX Battery Powered by eneloop, 2500mAh typical / 2400 mAh minimum High Capacity, 4 Pack AA Ni-MH Pre-Charged Rechargeable Batteries)) and last nearly as long as the XXs.So the question you have to ask yourself is, if you need higher capacity, do you take a gamble on a brand that could potentially not be an Eneloop or just pay the $7 difference and get the XX Eneloops that are guaranteed at 2500mAh? Either way, I'm very satisfied with my purchase and have no complaints whatsoever about the Eneloops. I would recommend them to anyone because they are truly quality batteries.
summary: Genuine Quality - Cream of the Crop!

Over time, those four batteries held up their end (I used them in my digital camera) but 2 of those batteries never kept their charge for long and I ended up throwing them away. I still have the other two and they work "OK".Recently about a year or so ago, I needed some more batteries and I only had 4 rechargeables from my original Durcell kit. I ended up buying a 4-pack of Duracell Rechargeable 2450mAh (made in Japan) and an even newer 4-pack of Duracell Rechargeable 2650mAh (made in Japan). Those worked pretty good but because of the number of devices I have requiring batteries, I needed to invest more in batteries... but I wasn't about to until I did more research on what were the best because my past rechargeable battery experiences were either a hit or miss.From my research (just Google for best rechargeable batteries) I learned that the best rechargeable batteries come from Japan (the China ones are OK) and Duracell actually sometimes rebrands batteries made by Sanyo (their Eneloop line). Now I know why my Chinese Duracells never lasted quite as long as my Japanese Duracells! I also learned that the wall charger (most of them that come with rechargeable batteries these days) I got with my kit do not charge batteries properly and is one of the reasons why all my batteries don't seem to last as long as they did when I first bought them.In addition, I found a great resource on Amazon, "NLee the Engineer" who knows his stuff about batteries & chargers (he's an electrical engineer). Based on his FAQs & reviews, I made my choice for a good charger & rechargeable batteries by his recommendation. So in one swoop, I invested in an intelligent battery charger (Maha C9000) and a handful of Sanyo Eneloop batteries (over $100 worth).Upon receiving the batteries, I verified that they were indeed the *latest* generation of Sanyo Eneloops (they have a grayish-silver crown logo on the side of them). While there is very little difference between the prior generation and the latest, the latest ones are slightly better and if I'm going to drop over $100 on batteries, I want to make sure I got the best & latest.The Eneloop packaging & several review sites stated that the Sanyo Eneloops are top rated because they have 1) a high durability, allowing estimated 1500 charges and 2) low self-discharge rate, maintains a large percentage of its charge after 3 years. While I can't attest to either because I only had them for a short period of time, I can say that they are very good when I used them in conjunction with my Maha C9000 charger. They power everything I have without issues (I had some weird issues with other types not powering up some devices).One thing I will say to be aware of is that the white Eneloops are rated at 2000 mAH. Other brands do boast a higher mAH and the higher the mAH, the more "juice" you have for your devices. Some people consider 2000 mAH to be a little low for some high powered devices. My Duracells (~$14), which I'm fairly certain are rebranded Eneloops, have a similar rating to that of the Eneloop XX brand (Sanyo XX Battery Powered by eneloop, 2500mAh typical / 2400 mAh minimum High Capacity, 4 Pack AA Ni-MH Pre-Charged Rechargeable Batteries)) and last nearly as long as the XXs.So the question you have to ask yourself is, if you need higher capacity, do you take a gamble on a brand that could potentially not be an Eneloop or just pay the $7 difference and get the XX Eneloops that are guaranteed at 2500mAh? Either way, I'm very satisfied with my purchase and have no complaints whatsoever about the Eneloops. I would recommend them to anyone because they are truly quality batteries.

title_clean: Orion 05662 1.25-Inch 13 Percent Transmission Moon Filter (Black)
description_clean: We are able to see the Moon at night thanks to sunlight reflecting off its rocky surface. When looking at the Moon through a telescope, bright reflected sunlight can produce significant glare. The Moon's disk, even at partial phases, is in fact so intensely bright with reflected sunlight that observing surface details can be challenging due to the overwhelming glare. This glare can be so bright that it washes out most of the interesting lunar features such as craters, rilles, mountains, and valleys. The considerable brightness also reduces contrast on our nearest neighbor in the solar system. To improve contrast and tone down glare easily, we recommend using a neutral-density 1.25 inch Orion 13 percent Transmission Moon Filter. This inexpensive accessory threads directly into a 1.25 inch eyepiece barrel and blocks 87 percent of the light gathered by the telescope, making for more comfortable lunar views exhibiting higher contrast. Once installed on a 1.25 inch telescope eyepiece, the Orion 13 percent Transmission Moon Filter will bring out considerably more lunar surface details thanks to the boosted contrast. Not only will more surface features and details pop out, but you can study them in greater comfort, thanks to Moon Filter reducing overall brightness without altering color. This neutral-density telescope eyepiece filter reduces irradiation, which is the distortion at the boundary between light and dark areas, such as along the lunar terminator. Using a Moon filter also helps conserve dark-adapted vision while viewing the lunar surface, especially when using big telescopes with 6 inches of aperture and larger. The Moon is one of the most interesting objects in the night sky to observe through a telescope. Its rugged surface is a feast for the eyes of amateur astronomers, with fascinating craters, mountainous highlands, and large, dark lunar seas formed by ancient volcanic activity.

reviewText: Took me about 5 minutes to fit it, and it certainly cured the missing number keys problem that my old one had started to show, but unfortunately the left and right shift keys do not behave the same way in conjunction with the arrow keys. I can only highlight in the forward direction using the left shift key. To highlight in reverse or to back off a highlight a few characters or a line I have to use the right shift key and that is awkward so a star comes off.The keyboard driver is up to date and there doesn't seem to be a way to interfere with the keys in software, so it looks like I'm stuck with the behavior. No help on Microsoft Help either (no surprise there).The action of the keys seems the same as the old keyboard.The hardest part was getting the tabs on the cable end to engage in the slots for them in the socket on the motherboard, but perseverance and patience paid off. There isn't much room for my hands between the keyboard and the laptop during this operation, so this is a definite challenge for me.All in all, an acceptable replacement, but not a drop-in one-for-one replacement for the original.[EDIT 3/30/14] I ended up replacing this keyboard with an Eathtek model that works exactly like the original.[/EDIT]

reviewText: I recently switched from Comcast Xfinity to Time Warner Cable and have been using my oldCisco DPC3008 DOCSIS 3.0 Cable Modemsuccessfully with TWC's 30Mbps Extreme internet service...however when I upgraded my internet to Ultimate my old Cisco modem couldn't reach the advertised 50Mbps - 100Mbps speeds for that service tier. I was told I needed a TWC approved modem to get those speeds. This is where the NETGEAR N450 modem/router comes in. It was up and running in literally 2 minutes. All I had to do was activate the modem with TWC by giving them the make/model/MAC...that's it. After it was activated and working I immediately tested the downstream speed and I was getting a whopping 110 Mbps! All 8 downstream channels had signal locks. When I was using the Cisco modem I only had 1 single channel signal lock.On the router side everything worked fairly well however the Wi-Fi speeds were nowhere near what I would expect except for a new Toshiba laptop which got 60Mbps at the Speedtest site. For the rest of the wireless clients I was only getting about 15Mbps using my Iphone 4 which was only about 2 feet away from the router. One of my wireless desktops using a USB based adapter got 20Mbps. Also some features that I liked using on my standaloneLinksys AC1900 Dual Band SMART Wi-Fi Router (EA6900)were missing on the NETGEGAR. For example the integrated USB ports are 2.0 not 3.0 and the router doesn't support the AC Wi-Fi protocol...only bgn. Also there is no "guest network" option from what I could tell even though the box lists that feature? Finally there is no option to reboot the router from the menu. Of course this is an unfair comparison because the NETGEAR is a combo modem/router that is moderately priced but no reboot? With that said the router portion is fairly basic but it is probably good enough for most users. This model has a built-in removable stand so could be placed horizontal or vertical. It's not a very pretty router..unlike my Linksys which is a work of art but it does the job and is priced attractively.
summary: Plug and Play...Time Warner Cable approved for up to 100Mbps

reviewText: I have bought 4 of these and the first was great.  It was silent, bright enough on a single USB plug connection, and just great as a *third* monitor.  The next three all emit a high pitched whine that is completely intolerable.  I only returned one because I put two into a server room where the ambient sound was loud enough that you couldn't hear the whine.  The fourth and final one was meant for a room that is too quiet... the whine drives everyone nuts.So, 25% ratio of good to bad monitors earns a 2 star rating.  I still need to get another USB monitor, but I will wait for a different vendor.  I'm not going to keep buying and returning squealing monitors.

reviewText: DISCLAIMER: my review is based on the darker colored stylus, and so this rating isn't a critique of the color.  Figuring curiosity about the technology probably outweighs the color, I thought it would be helpful nonetheless....This stylus let's you use your iPad for handwriting like you would a pen and paper. The precision is excellent but the writing isn't jagged and there are no line breaks, even with my Moshi Crystal Clear iVisor screen proteor.In this review I will include comparisons the Jot Pro by Adonit, the other stylus I've found allows you to do that. So far this stylus writes better than the Jot Pro. Here are the details:I'll break the mold and start with the bad:- the body is not magnetic (something I really like about the Jot Pro), and- it doesn't quite have the heavy weighted feel of the adonit pen; slightly more hollow and less expensive feeling (also, less expensive :-)).The good:- A nice looking stylus.- Tip is protected by screw tight "cap" so there's no chance of it being damaged when not in use.- The cap screws onto the back of the pend when in use, so it's never lost.- A clever *twist* is that the "cap" forms a significant part of the stylus body so you won't forget to attach it or lose it.The brilliant:- Comes with a replacement disk for the tip, whereas adonit requires you to buy extras direct from them at something like $8/pair with like $7 s & h.- The most smooth, elegant stylus I've written with.While the Jot Pro has a higher quality look and feel to it, the quality of writing of the Musumee is superior to the Jot Pro. That, plus the extra writing disk put the Musumee at the top of my list, where it should stay unless the writing quality degrades rapidly.

reviewText: Programming a micro controller can be a little intimidating, particularly if it has been a while since you have done any programming at all. I was pleasantly surprised at how easy it was to get the Arduino up and running, and how much interesting stuff you could get it to do with just minimum components.This is easy enough to use that anyone can learn use. There is an abundance of free source code that you can use to get your feet wet, and learn the system. In the first day I had it I worked through about a dozen simple projects with temperature sensors, LED's, photosensors, relays, and motors. The programming language is much like C, but if you have any programming experience you will pick up the "sketches" really quickly, and even if you do not have programming experience, it is easy to learn o this platform.I love the Arduino platform and am now completely hooked. My only suggestion is that if this is your first Arduino, you would probably do better to buy one of the "kits" that has some of the sensors and other parts to allow you to get some quick projects going.Also, this is a great platform for education. It is affordable enough so that each student can have his/her own Arduino board, and then share components from a supply cabinet. It is well within the capability of high school students to build interesting projects with this board.

It has 14 digital input/output pins (of which 6 can be used as PWM outputs), 6 analog inputs, a 16 MHz crystal oscillator, a USB connection, a power jack, an ICSP header, and a reset button. It contains everything needed to support the microcontroller; simply connect it to a computer with a USB cable or power it with a AC-to-DC adapter or battery to get started

reviewText: *** Update 4-23-2014 ****I managed to download additional drives from the manufacturer's website for my Macs. Once I had done this, the adapter worked with both Macs and Windows computers. the performance with Macs was very smooth and fast. I am leaving the original review below.*** The original review. ***The main laptop that I use is a MacBook Air. It is a really great device, very portable, well engineered, and very fast for the purposes of the main tasks I use it for - word processing, email, web surfing, some light photo and video editing. However, its lightness and portability come at a price - MacBook Air is extremely ports-deficient. It has only two USB ports, one SD card slot and a small headphones jack. Most of the times when I use it none of this lack of ports bothers me, but there are situations when I need to use more than two USB devices at the same time, or connect to the Internet via a wired connection. This small Inateck USB/Ethernet hub seemed like an ideal accessory to have around. Unfortunately, I couldn't get ethernet working.I am running Mac OS-X Mavericks on all of my computers. I've connected bot my MacBook Air and Mac Mini to this adapter, but neither one of them was able to recognize the ethernet connection. (The USB hub part was fine.) The adapter comes with no printed instructions, and the pdf manual is very sparse and very clearly geared to Windows computers.In order to see if I didn't by any chance get a defective unit, I connected this adapter to my Windows 8 machine. The adapter was recognized immediately without any need for the installation of the driver software. The Ethernet connection was extremely smooth and fast, and I didn't see any difference as compared to getting online through the dedicated Ethernet port.The three USB 3.0 ports have functioned splendidly, both on my Mac and Windows computers. They really help with the additional connectivity, without the need for external power. The USB strip is fairly compact, so you would not want to connect any bulkier USB devices to it.This could have been a really great overall adapter, but unfortunately right now I cannot recommend it to any Mac users out there. The users of Windows ultrabooks, on the other hand, should really appreciate all the additional connectivity that this adapter offers.**** Product provided for review purposes. ****
summary: Update: Works with Macs and Windows Computers

reviewText: It seems that about every other reviewer of this item was using this for a mac book pro..... since I buy good computers let me clearly say that this was not for a Mac but rather an Alienware 14 (the new redesign as of 2013) and this thing fits like a glove. The security friendliness is not something I sought after but was more of an added bonus. The main issue I have with the Alienware cases is they are ridiculously expensive for their protection, and their quality on the cases are slacking. This case by case logic is 1/3 of the price and I have used this brand before and am very happy with the quality for the price. Pockets are very spacious and can hold all the accessories that I carry with my laptop on a daily basis. The padded pocket is superb compared to the last 2 laptop cases I have bought that were similar to this. The size dimensions that are in the description of the product description are accurate, so make sure of the outer dimensions of your laptop/tablet/whatever and it should be fine. Very happy with the purchase, would buy again.
summary: Exactly what I was looking for Alienware 14

title_clean: Magnasonic MGUC500 Professional Ultrasonic Jewelry & Eyeglass Cleaner With Digital Timer
description_clean: Make your wedding ring glisten just as beautifully as it did on your special day. The Magnasonic Digital Ultrasonic Jewelry Cleaner will restore your valuables to their former glory. Using only water, this cleaner generates 42,000 Hz of ultrasonic waves that gently remove dirt and grime in minutes. There are five preset cleaning cycles to choose from, so you can easily control the cleaning intensity you need. You'll get professional results on jewelry, eyeglasses, watches, dentures, razor blades, utensils and so much more. Great for business, commercial or home use, this ultrasonic cleaner will have your items looking brand new again.Cleans Dirty Tarnished Jewelry, Eyeglasses, Watches, Utensils and MoreYou won't believe how your items will shine with just water! Simply fill the tank with water, insert your items, and you'll see professional jewelry cleaning results. A bit of liquid hand/dish soap can be added for enhanced cleaning, but all the work is done by the ultrasonic waves. This powerful unit cleans in minutes without damaging delicate items. So whether it's your dirty everyday items or tarnished priceless treasures, the Magnasonic Digital Ultrasonic Jewelry Cleaner will safely make them sparkle again.Ultrasonic Sound Waves for a Deep and Gentle CleanThis powerful cleaner packs a gentle punch. 42,000 Hz of ultrasonic energy waves create millions of microscopic cleansing bubbles that gently lift dirt and grime away without using harsh chemicals or scrubbing. The motion of the water may look mild, but it's actually producing a deep and thorough clean to penetrate the most difficult areas.Digital Display with 5 Preset Cleaning Cycles and Auto Shut OffThere are 5 different cycles to choose from, depending on the cleaning time you require, for easy and precise control. Just select the desired time and watch the digital display count down to the end of cleaning and then automatically shut off.

reviewText: This is probably a good receiver as I have an Onkyo TX-NR 608 already and it rocks. I installed the 717 but the sound was weaker so I did some research and this receiver says 4-16 OHMS but it is actually only 6 OHMS for all channels. My speakers are 8 OHMS so I need a receiver that is 8 OHMS or all channels. Before purchasing this make sure your receiver and speakers are the same OHMS, if you do you will hear the difference. I love Onkyo receivers and purchased a TX-NR 818 which is 8 OHMS for all channels.Update: I am returning receiver and was given a shipping label to print out. I love Amazons return policy.

Also, be very, very careful to make absolutely sure every segment is solidly locked before you walk away.

title_clean: Velbon UT 45L 61.6-inch Compact Tripod with Panhead & Case
description_clean: The UT 45L 5-Section Aluminum Tripod with PHD-42Q 4-Way Head is a sturdy tripod that folds out to a working height of 61.6" from the tiniest of packages. At less than a foot long (11.6") when its twist-lock legs are retracted and folded up 180deg. (so the feet meet the included 4-way head), the UT 45L is perfect for stowing in a backpack or even a tote bag, for the ultimate in low-profile yet high-performance camera support.Lightweight for traveling, the tripod weighs just 2.73 lb and supports up to 6.6 lb. The tripod's maximum height is 5.3 times its folded length. The secret to the UT 45L's tight package is its section count: the aluminum-alloy legs have six each and the center column has two. The PHD-42Q head features four dimensions of adjustment: 360deg. panning, back-to-front tilt and tilt to either side. There are independent controls for pan and tilt. The included quick-release plate is the Velbon QB-62. A carry case is also included.

reviewText: This was the most I'd ever spent for just a camera body (in the digital age), and Robin and I took this, along with a G5KK body, an Olympus E-Pm2 body and a bunch of lenses to Dallas for the "Texas Frightmare Weekend". Between the 3 camera bodies, this one by far took the most accurate color images I'd seen before [using my usual ISO 1600 to avoid flash]. The way the buttons are placed, and the size of the camera itself - not too tiny to hold, this was a joy to use. The weird downside was when we returned from the weekend journey I saw that Amazon had dropped the price by $100 so I checked to see if I could get a $100 refund-or-Amazon card worth $100 and I received (very quickly) a responce via email that it was past the 7-day mark and the Amazon agent suggested I return the body I purchased for a refund, then turn around and re-purchase the body for $100 less.This doesn't make a lot of sense for Amazon to have me go through this (after all, they're paying shipping back'n forth), and it would seem to their benefit to just credit me the $100 and let it go at that. I haven't decided if I'll follow their advice or not - the body I received is already programmed to my liking, and I know it works great. What if I return it and get another body that for one reason or the other doesn't match up to my opinion of the one I now have? Perhaps someone @ Amazon will read this and figure out they won't lose more than the $100 credit and contact me. Perhaps they won't - nonetheless this is a great body to put your micro 4/3 lenses on!!
summary: The best micro 4/3 body I've used (so far), but Amazon has a stupid policy.

description_clean: The new Tokina AT-X 116 PRO DX is an ultra-wide angle lens with a fast f/2.8 aperture for better photography in low-light situations. title_clean: NETGEAR Universal N300 Wi-Fi to Ethernet Adapter (WNCE2001)
description_clean: Connect any Ethernet-enabled device to your wireless home network with the NETGEAR WNCE2001 Universal WiFi Internet Adapter. The adapter is perfect for home theater devices such as the Xbox 360, PS3, TiVo, Blu-ray player, and more. And thanks to its elegant, compact design, you'll save space and have a lot of flexibility in choosing where to place it.Universal WiFi Internet AdapterAt a Glance:Adds wireless capability to any Ethernet-enabled deviceWorks with Xbox 360, PlayStation 3, TiVo, Internet-enabled TVs, and moreWireless-N for fast performancePush 'N' Connect provides easy securityThe easy-to-setup WNCE2001 brings wireless-N capability to any Ethernet-enabled device.View larger.Dynamic LEDs display real-time network connection status.View larger.Wireless Connectivity for Your Ethernet-Enabled DevicesMore and more of today's home theater devices are Ethernet enabled, including TiVo, VUDU, Blu-ray players, Xbox 360, PlayStation 3, Internet TVs, and more. With this NETGEAR adapter, you'll be able to cut the cord and use a wireless connection to network your devices.Universal CompatibilityWith the WNCE2001 Universal WiFi Internet Adapter, you will no longer need to buy individual proprietary WiFi dongles for the TV, Xbox, etc. because WNCE2001 works with all of them. You can simply plug it into the device when you need to and share it among multiple gadgets.Wireless-N Technology for Fast PerformanceThe WNCE2001 adapter supports Wireless-N (2.4 GHz 802.11n) technology for outstanding speed and performance, keeping pace with your home theater devices. In addition, it is also backwards compatible with 802.11g and 802.11b networks.The adapter can also repeat 2.4 GHz WiFi signals from devices made by NETGEAR and other brands, and it features dynamic LEDs that display real-time network connection status.Push 'N' Connect for Easy SecuritySetting up a secure connection couldn't be easier with NETGEAR's Push 'N' Connect technology. Push 'N' Connect using WiFi Protected Setup (WPS) offers true plug-and-play simplicity by requiring you to simply push the Push 'N' Connect button on your router. In addition, the adapter also supports WiFi Protected Access (WPA2-PSK, WPA-PSK) and WEP encryption.Compact, Smart Design Can Use USB for PowerThe Universal WiFi Internet Adapter is a compact device that measures just 3.2 x 2.4 x 0.7 inches, giving you flexibility in choosing where to place it. In addition, the adapter can be powered by either the included power adapter or with the USB port. By using the USB port, you can avoid using an additional power outlet, and reduce exposed wires in your home.The NETGEAR WNCE2001 Universal WiFi Internet Adapter works with Windows 7/Vista/XP/2000, Mac OS, UNIX, or Linux. reviewText: Purchased this about 3 weeks ago and I have not been disappointed.  Really great sound, connects well to my bluetooth devices.  As far as battery life, I have gotten the 6 hrs that are advertised.  One great feature is that when the battery has lost it's useful life, it is replaceable!  The only issue I have is the instructions that say the charging light will change from red to amber when it is charged. I plug mine in and it seems that when it is charged, the power light goes out.  Not sure what is the issue here, but it seems fully charged.  No other issues.

title_clean: Belkin 3-Outlet Mini Travel Swivel Charger Surge Protector with Dual USB Ports, 5 Charging Outlets Total (1 AMP / 5 Watt)
description_clean: Whether you're crossing continents or just heading across town, the Belkin BZ103050-TVL Mini Surge Protector/Dual USB Charger is the type of travel companion that makes your life easier. Featuring three protected AC outlets, two protected, powered USB outlets, and a unique rotating plug design that lets you work in tight spaces, this compact surge protector lets you plug in and charge all your essential devices wherever you are.Mini Surge Protector/Dual USB ChargerAt a Glance:3 AC outlets and 2 powered USB portsComplete protection on all outlets360-degree rotating plug with 4 locking positionsIncludes mini-USB cable for charging phones, MP3 players, and other devicesLifetime Product and $75,000 Connected Equipment WarrantiesYou can easily slip this mini surge protector into your laptop bag or carry-on.Includes mini-USB cable for charging phones, MP3 players, and other devices.Convenient, Dependable Design for Worry-Free TravelHotel rooms, airport terminals, and coffee shops never seem to have enough power outlets to handle all your devices at once. With the Belkin Mini Surge Protector you no longer have to choose what to charge first.This surge protector acts as a power strip, letting you plug three AC devices into a single wall outlet. It is rated to handle 918 Joules and provides protection against power surges and spikes, since the smart traveler is looking for protection of essential gear and irreplaceable data, not just extra outlets.Two Powered USB Outlets Let You Charge More Devices EasilyIn addition to its three AC outlets, this surge protector features two protected, powered USB outlets, so you can easily charge your iPod along with other USB devices. These USB outlets do not transmit data and the surge protector cannot be used as a hub, but they do make it exceptionally easy to keep devices that are charged via USB interfaces up and running without blocking your computer's USB ports or the AC outlets that you need for bigger devices.Plus you may be able to leave long, tangle-friendly cords and clunky item-specific chargers at home, since this mini surge protector comes with a mini-USB cable. This is especially convenient now that many phones, including Blackberries and Motorola RAZR phones, feature USB power connections.Unique, Efficient Design with Rotating Plug for Added VersatilityIts compact, lightweight, and efficient design means that you can easily slip this mini surge protector into your laptop bag or carry-on, and because Belkin knows that working on the road often means trying to plug in despite awkward outlet or furniture positioning, a 360-degree rotating plug with four locking positions makes it easy to use this device in tight spaces.About Belkin International, Inc.Belkin offers a diverse product mix that provides people with seamless electronics integration in their homes, cars, and on the go. Founded in California in 1983, Belkin is a privately held company and the recognized leader in connectivity solutions, in addition to accessories for MP3 devices, computers, and more. We provide extensive solutions for networking, home theater-with our PureAV line of cables, power, and digital wireless accessories-and many more categories. Belkin's phenomenal growth has led to our expanding global presence. In addition to corporate headquarters in Los Angeles, we now have offices throughout Europe-in the United Kingdom, the Netherlands, and Germany, among others-and in the Asia Pacific region, including Australia, Shanghai, and our regional headquarters in Hong Kong.The Belkin Mini Surge Protector/Dual USB Charger is backed by a lifetime warranty and a $75,000 Connected Equipment Warranty.What's in the BoxMini Surge Protector/Dual USB Charger, mini-USB power cable, and user guide.Wall-MountedConnected Equipment WarrantyNumber of OutletsUSB PortsJoule RatingNetwork ProtectionPhone Line ProtectionCoax ProtectionPower Safety Shut DownOverload ProtectionCord LengthWarrantyMini$75,00032918NoNoNoYesYesWall-mountLifetime1-Outlet Wall-Mount$50,0001 1045NoYesNoYesYesWall-mountLifetime6-Outlet Wall-Mount$50,0006 1045NoYesNoYesYesWall-mountLifetime

reviewText: Sometimes you have to read beyond the title before choosing a product. It's always best to carefully read the product description, and perhaps delve into some of the product reviews, both the positive and negative ones, before making your choice. Such is the case with this one:Etón FR160R Microlink Self-Powered AM/FM/NOAA Weather Radio with Flashlight, Solar Power and Cell Phone ChargerPicking the title apart, it is a self-powered AM/FM/NOAA weather radio, and depending on location, offers decent reception. It's a good basic flashlight, and it is solar-powered, but as a cell phone charger, don't expect miracles. Here's a quick breakdown for those who want just the subjective good and not so good points.Pros:+ AM & FM bands plus NOAA weatherband (all 7 channels); excellent for emergencies+ Good emergency flashlight; 3 white LEDs provide reasonable light+ Two power sources; built-in solar cells or crank generator+ Internal Ni-MH rechargeable battery; can be replaced if needed+ Standard 3.5 mm headphone jack; rubber cap prevents environmental damage+ Small rubber feet on base; keeps it from sliding around+ Compact size; 5 x 2 x 1 inches, weighs 8 ouncesCons:- Inadequate as a cell phone charger for contemporary smartphones- No AC charger available; needs an additional method of chargingIn Use:Ever since Hurricane Sandy slammed into the New York region in October 2012, I've been upgrading my emergency supplies. Some of us were without power for five days, others longer, and though I was relatively well prepared for this costly disaster, products like this can do nothing but help.First thing that should be mentioned is that this full-featured emergency radio is amazingly small. Reading its approximate dimensions of 5" wide x 2" high x 1" deep can be misleading, so imagine it placed on its side on top of a dollar bill: it's actually smaller than US paper currency (which measure 2.61 inches wide and 6.14 inches long), that's just one of the things that make this small radio so appealing. It also weighs just over half a pound, so it's jacket pocketable in an emergency.The radio's tuner pulls in both AM and FM stations, and with surprisingly clear reception. Tested this in both in Pennsylvania and in the New York City areas. It receives all seven NOAA bands using the slide selector on the radio panel, so you can monitor changing weather conditions during emergency conditions.You can charge the FR160 in less than two minutes using its hand crank. Using the crank to charge it will give you radio reception at low volume for about 15 to 20 minutes. Crank for a longer period and it will play longer. You can also place it in sunlight (even on an overcast day, as I found out) and its built-in solar panel handily powers the radio and recharges its battery pack. If you're looking for audio attributes on the level of Bose, JBL or Polk Audio speakers, this radio isn't for you... but the sound quality of this small radio is quite good considering its size. Listened to a favorite "smooth jazz" station for awhile, switched to classical then to '80s rock, and was quite pleased all around. The NOAA weatherband with its robotized constant announcements was good, and as clear as one could expect.It has a flashlight with three LEDs on its end, providing decently bright illumination. For comparison it's about on the same level as myGarrity Power Lite 3 LED Crank Light. This model is also brighter than some of the predecessors from Eton.However...Getting back to product titles and descriptions, forget anything stellar if you think that this would be a good product for cell phone charging. Its output is inadequate for contemporary smartphones such as the iPhones or Samsung Galaxy android phones, unless you want to put its cranking action as part of a daily fitness routine. Simply put, you'll get your workout cranking away and then find that you only have a couple of minutes of charge. If your cell phone has the option of spare batteries, get them. There's also no AC wall charger available for this model, so let it charge itself in a window.If smartphone charging is a personal imperative, then you might want to look into the AC poweredEton BoostBloc 2000mAh Portable Backup Battery Pack-Charger for Smart Phonesor one of the other variations available here. Just do a search for 'BoostBloc' and a variety of models with different capacities will show up, including some of the crankable BoostTurbine models. There are other similar smartphone charging products available if you just search for them.That being said, must admit to liking Eton's emergency radio products. Part of this is due to happy prior ownership of an olderEton FR150 Microlink Solar-Powered, Self-Powered AM/FM/Weatherband Portable Radio with Flashlightand an even olderEton FR400 Hand Crank Radio and Power Generator, which have proven themselves over time. These are still functional and in use to this day.Summary:ThisEtón FR160Ris a good product at a reasonable price, if you are aware of its strong points along with its limitations. As an emergency smartphone charger, it's a 2-star product at best, but my priorities were as (1) a multi-band AM/FM radio with NOAA reception and alternative power, and (2) a backup emergency flashlight. With both of these subjective needs, along with prior experience with this brand, this one's a 4-star choice, hampered by the lack of an AC charger.3/23/2013
summary: Etón FR160R Microlink: Small, crankable and solar powered

reviewText: Installing couldn't have been easier. I did have to replace the bracket before installing since I have a small case, but all needed parts were supplied with the card. All it took was booting up and installing the driver CD. Card works much better than the onboard video that came with my MSI motherboard.  I'd recommend this to anyone who wants to low priced video card for a home theatre PC.The real reason I purchased this card was because the onboard MSI video didn't with work XBMCUbuntu, which I'm reviewing as a possible replacement for Windows Media Center. The card works great, so after poking around a bit, I may make the switch to XBMC. Windows Media Center really is a pretty terrible user experience, and if XBMC has all the features I'm interested in, then it's bye-bye Windows 7 for my home theatre.
summary: Works Great with Windows 7 and XBMCUbuntu

reviewText: This is one of those products that is good to have, but even better if you never need to use it since you'll probably be using it when the electricity is out. It offers a lot of functionality in a compact size: a flashlight, AM radio, FM radio and weather band radio. It runs off of an internal rechargeable battery that is kept charged either via solar power, USB connection or by cranking the handle. It can also serve as a source to charge a cell phone (albeit with very limited capacity to do so since the internal battery is only rated at 800mAh).It works pretty well. The flashlight is very bright - had no problems lighting my way down a dark stairway and in a totally dark room. The radio is OK. The reception is spotty and it only picked up a few of the very strong stations in the area. It's very susceptible to positioning - moving it just a couple of inches turned a clear station into static.Cranking the handle to keep it charged is pretty easy. It turns easily and the handle is comfortable. According to the manual, one minute of cranking equals 30 minutes of flashlight use or 20 minutes of radio use.This is a good product to keep on hand in case of emergency, such as a bad storm or extended power outage. It won't keep you cool in the summer or warm in the winter, but at least you can see where you're going and listen to the radio. Definitely worth a spot in the emergency kit. The only shortcoming is the somewhat limited radio reception.[sample provided by manufacturer for review]
summary: Glad to have it; hope I never need to use it

reviewText: This is by far the very best router I have ever had based on speed. There is very negligible speed/signal loss compared to my former combo Motorola SBG6850 modem/wireless router. The old SBG6850 was getting 56mbps at the wired Ethernet port on the router and anywhere from 10-30mbps on the wireless side. The speed loss was massive compared to the AC1900 router.It was easy to set up with TWC and the SB6141. The Netgear genie setup wizard did not see the modem on setup. Had to go to the browser and log into the modem to see what it's known MAC address was and manually enter it into the AC1900. The router wizard ended up asking me for the modems MAC address anyway so it was a pretty fool proof installation. Maybe took a whole twenty  minutes to install it, upgrade the firmware and finally connect to the internet. Fast and easy compared to any of the routers I have installed over the years. They are so much easier now to configure that it's almost plug and play.Now getting 56mbps on the wired side and 54mbps wireless down the hall in another room. It's like the wireless stuff in my house is now wired. It's incredible how little the speed loss is now.I used to feel like I was getting ripped off paying for 50mbps and only getting 15-35 at best wireless. Also range is no longer an issue. The AC1900 range has been one bar better than my old AT&T; 2-Wire router and linksys routers.If you own another fast modem like the SB6141, don't hesitate to get one of these new high speed routers even if it's another brand. They are worth every penny,  I've never seen anything faster or I would buy it.
summary: Time Warner Cable with Motorola SB6141 modem and the AC1900 router

reviewText: With performance is almost universally recognized as being outstanding and reliable, the Sanyo Eneloop is among the most popular of the low discharge NiMH rechargeable batteries.  Of high quality construction, Eneloop's are not inexpensive, but for those who use a lot of batteries, they can be well worth the money.Prices for Eneloop products fluctuate, but are generally quite good at Amazon, with the Eneloop Battery Power Pack currently selling for about $35.  If you add up the costs for the individual items, you get a cost of approximately $50.For those who need a battery charger, this bundle could be a good deal.  However, I already have aLa Crosse Technology BC-700smart charger, as well as several other miscellaneous chargers.  There's nothing special about the Sanyo charger included in the Power Pack, and if you subtract the $15 cost for the charger, you're back at $35, which makes the Power Pack not such a great a deal for me.  The only reason I bought this, was because it was a Gold Box deal selling for $26.99, making a marginal buy, a little sweeter.While I liked the design of D cell adapter, which locks the battery in place, I wasn't at all impressed by the Eneloop C cell adapter, which allows it to slide freely.  There are cheap Asian split C cell adapters, that do a better job of protecting the cell.  The Eneloop C cell adapters look pretty, but they are not well designed.Wrapping things up, the Eneloop is a great product, and if you don't already have a battery charger, this set is decent buy at the $35 dollar level.  If you already have a smart charger, you're probably better off buying the individual components you really need.Providing 8 AA's is fine, but I would have appreciated having at least 4 AAA batteries, rather than just 2.  The carrying case makes for a nice package, but once you start using the batteries, you'll probably find some other use for it.
summary: perhaps not the greatest deal, if you already have a decent charger...

reviewText: 256GB is a good size for laptop or desktop as long as you keep your media / photos on another drive. It may not be the fastest drive, but it is (relatively) inexpensive and it speeds up boot time and application launch significantly. Mine has been working flawlessly in my desktop for more than a year now, with heavy use. I configured Windows 7 so that my downloads, music, videos, and documents are all stored in another drive (a regular 3.5" disk). On a laptop, you get faster speed, more ruggedness and better battery life. Other than the higher price compared to normal spinning disk, what's not to like?

reviewText: I got this thinking the smallest size would be great.  While I have another Grid-It, slightly longer than this...like, say putting two of these side by side, it's size limits it to obviously smaller items and probably less a chance of bigger items as the straps of the 'grid' are permanent and you can't rearrange their location.  So it kind of limits what and where you place everything.  I'd say in the pictures they chose the 'best' configuration for what it can hold probably seeing if it can hold at least one large item followed by at least a medium as well as a small item.  This thing is probably best suited for many small items.  Do your homework with these as opposed to getting what size initially seems to work for you.  I think this is still a great product despite some shortcomings.

reviewText: I currently have a 24-inch ASUS TN panel LED monitor mounted to an articulating monitor arm.  It's a good monitor overall and it has a good selection of inputs.  My usage is primarily browsing the web, writing, and watching videos.  I was pretty excited to give the HP Envy 23-inch LED monitor a try because of its IPS panel.  While I liked the display, I was rather disappointed by the lack of a couple of features: a DVI input and VESA support for mounting.DISPLAYMost monitor guides will tell you that IPS panels are the most expensive and they're known to have good color accuracy and significantly better viewing angles than other types of panels.  Compared to my ASUS, I did actually prefer the screen of the HP Envy.  I'm not a graphics pro, so I may not recognize subtle differences, but I spent a lot of time trying to make the two panels look as similar as possible.  And in the end, my eyes just preferred the HP Envy.  Text looked great while browsing the web and writing emails, my pictures looked nice, and movies looked fine.  I actually enjoyed the movie watching more on the Envy, probably because of the glossy display.  My ASUS has a matte screen.CONTROLS & STANDThe controls and menu for the HP Envy are pretty decent and not too difficult to figure out.  The buttons are much more responsive than the ones on my ASUS.  The stand is easy to attach and looks nice.  Unfortunately, the only adjustment you can make is a front tilt.  On my desk, the Envy is a good one to two inches too low for ergonomic viewing.  Being able to raise it would've been a wonderful feature, but most monitors come with annoyingly bad stands and the HP Envy monitor is no different.  My ASUS also came with a poor stand, but I made up for it by mounting it on an articulating monitor arm.  I would have done the same with the HP Envy, but it lacks VESA support for mounting -- ARGH.  I really would have replaced my ASUS with the HP Envy, but if I can't adjust its height without getting a monitor riser, it's a no-go for me.  Such a shame.CONNECTIONSThe HP Envy touts connectivity, but it has just one VGA and two HDMI inputs.  To keep the panel inexpensive, HP left out a DVI input.  On the plus side, it did come with both VGA and HDMI cables.  After plugging the HDMI cable in to my PC, I noticed my desktop didn't fill the screen, so I had about a half inch black border on every side.  Text was also very blurry.  I eventually figured out that my AMD Radeon graphics software was underscanning the display for some reason.  I went into my scaling options and set it to 0%, which fixed the scaling issue and blurry text.CONCLUSIONThe HP Envy 23-inch LED monitor has a good display and is a decent value, as long as you like it as-is.  Unfortunately, it's not very ergo-friendly and it lacks a DVI input.  Though it has Beats Audio technology built in, it's just for headphones.  It doesn't have built-in speakers, which would've made more sense than a headphone jack.  I can't really recommend the HP Envy 23-inch LED monitor, but it's not a terrible buy either, if your needs are pretty basic.
summary: Good display, but no VESA mount, no DVI, and pointless Beats Audio

Do your research and buy accordingly.

reviewText: I bought this keyboard for my home theatre PC (HTPC).At first it worked brilliantly:-It worked flawlessly from 15 feet away-The batteries had great longevity.-Better multi-touch than some tablets and phonesWe recommended this to several other people. Then the problems started. The mouse would occasionally stop working. We thought it was dirt or debris on the track pad. Later, even an impeccably clean track pad would stop working. Fresh batteries didn't fix the problem either. Now the o, 0 and windows (start menu) key don't work on our HTPC or any other computer. We hope Logitech replaces this under their 3 year limited warranty.
summary: Worked great for a while, now mouse and several keys don't work

reviewText: I bought aOoma Telo Air Wireless VoIP Free Telephone Service with WiFi plus 60-Days Ooma-Premierand went through three useless wireless adapters from Ooma (including many hours with multiple levels of their tech support) until I gave up and installed one of these (without help - although it worked much better after a fireware upgrade). I've plugged it through the Ooma into aD-Link 5-Port Gigabit Desktop Switch (DGS-1005G)(the Gigabit capabilities are wasted since this adapter only has a 100/10 Enet connection) and now have a PC, XBOX 360, Blu-ray player, 5.1 AV receiver, as well as the Ooma telo all working great through it (in my master bedroom with a plasma screen), which I have plugged into aAPC BE550G Back-UPS ES 8 Outlet 550VA 120V.I have the Netgear WNCE2001 WiFi adapter powered through the Ooma USB port (althougth there's a power adapter I could have used). It adds a few small wires but this allows me to move it up in the audio cabinet for better reception. I was able to thusly remove the 50-foot eye sore of a cable running around the room's baseboard. I had made great effort to wire the house with Ethernet cabling when I remodeled five years ago but then moved the AV system to the other side of the room (ha ha). All that past cabling effort seems silly now. I am very happy.
summary: Worked better than adapter made by vendor

description_clean: Connect any Ethernet-enabled device to your wireless home network with the NETGEAR WNCE2001 Universal WiFi Internet Adapter. The adapter is perfect for home theater devices such as the Xbox 360, PS3, TiVo, Blu-ray player, and more. And thanks to its elegant, compact design, you'll save space and have a lot of flexibility in choosing where to place it.Universal WiFi Internet AdapterAt a Glance:Adds wireless capability to any Ethernet-enabled deviceWorks with Xbox 360, PlayStation 3, TiVo, Internet-enabled TVs, and moreWireless-N for fast performancePush 'N' Connect provides easy securityThe easy-to-setup WNCE2001 brings wireless-N capability to any Ethernet-enabled device.View larger.Dynamic LEDs display real-time network connection status.View larger.Wireless Connectivity for Your Ethernet-Enabled DevicesMore and more of today's home theater devices are Ethernet enabled, including TiVo, VUDU, Blu-ray players, Xbox 360, PlayStation 3, Internet TVs, and more. With this NETGEAR adapter, you'll be able to cut the cord and use a wireless connection to network your devices.Universal CompatibilityWith the WNCE2001 Universal WiFi Internet Adapter, you will no longer need to buy individual proprietary WiFi dongles for the TV, Xbox, etc. because WNCE2001 works with all of them. You can simply plug it into the device when you need to and share it among multiple gadgets.Wireless-N Technology for Fast PerformanceThe WNCE2001 adapter supports Wireless-N (2.4 GHz 802.11n) technology for outstanding speed and performance, keeping pace with your home theater devices. In addition, it is also backwards compatible with 802.11g and 802.11b networks.The adapter can also repeat 2.4 GHz WiFi signals from devices made by NETGEAR and other brands, and it features dynamic LEDs that display real-time network connection status.Push 'N' Connect for Easy SecuritySetting up a secure connection couldn't be easier with NETGEAR's Push 'N' Connect technology. Push 'N' Connect using WiFi Protected Setup (WPS) offers true plug-and-play simplicity by requiring you to simply push the Push 'N' Connect button on your router. In addition, the adapter also supports WiFi Protected Access (WPA2-PSK, WPA-PSK) and WEP encryption.Compact, Smart Design Can Use USB for PowerThe Universal WiFi Internet Adapter is a compact device that measures just 3.2 x 2.4 x 0.7 inches, giving you flexibility in choosing where to place it. In addition, the adapter can be powered by either the included power adapter or with the USB port. By using the USB port, you can avoid using an additional power outlet, and reduce exposed wires in your home.The NETGEAR WNCE2001 Universal WiFi Internet Adapter works with Windows 7/Vista/XP/2000, Mac OS, UNIX, or Linux. reviewText: My dad has a small older TV and a VCR. I wanted to buy him a DVD player and some wood-working DVDs, but his TV only has the cable connector on the back. I also didn't want to complicate things for him either since he is turning 80 soon and technology is not his friend.This device is exactly what I was looking for. It allows a composite video input (think yellow video and red and white audio cables), and the standard cable connector to connect to this box and then the active source is automatically switched to.So in my dad's case, if he plays a VCR tape, the box send the VCR video to the TV and if he plays a DVD, then the DVD video gets sent to the TV. Nothing to switch, all automagically. Cool little device!
summary: Exactly what I needed for easy automatic switching between a DVD player and a VCR

reviewText: If you've ever faced the "The device is drawing too much power. It is being shut down" dialog when plugging your expensive USB Superdrive into your Mac Book Pro / Air via a powered USB hub, but can't figure it out because it's the only device plugged in, this unit is the solution.  For 1/3 the cost of that branded device, it works plugged into a power USB hub with no complaining from the system.This drive is just as compact as the Apple unit, but the cable is removable and far more flexible than Apple's attached cable.Caught in a situation where you don't have a powered hub?  The unit includes a second USB-5V cable to provide that additional juice to keep things going.Now, you can use a DVD drive with your MBP / MBA even though you're limited to 2 USB ports on the laptop and prefer to connect via a hub.The unit works immediately upon plugging it in - no drivers or other futzing around.  Tested on OS X 10.5.8, OS X 10.6.8, 10.7.5 and 10.8.2 on 4 different MB units.

reviewText: I was without a cooling pad for my laptop and noticed the internal fan seemed to running more than usual. I thought the cooling pad might extend the life of my four year old machine and scrolled through all of the cooling pads that were offered by Amazon. I read the reviews for this bargin priced pad and thought I would give it a try. Just installed it today and was pleasantly surprised at the setup and operation. It even has a pass through USB connector so that it does not take up one of the ports on the computer....a nice feature that I was unaware of. I like the cool blue lights and how my laptop is lifted up off the desk by about 2". It seem like a very stable platform. Hopefully, it will continue to perform for me well into the future.

reviewText: After using the Brainwavz S1 earphones for a few days, they may be my favorite wired earphones. Okay, they're not Bluetooth, which gives you the freedom to move around at a distance from the audio source, as well as controlling a playlist and sound volume remotely. But wired earphones have been around for a long time and have served a good purpose, so I'm judging the Brainwavz S1 unit primarily on audio quality and comfort.About the audio quality: I'm not a dedicated audiophile, and I don't know all the technical terms for describing the quality of the sound, but to my ears, the music that pumped out of the earphones sounded terrific, as good or better than any earphones I've used. The bass was remarkably good for the tiny earphones, and the clarity of the lyrics was excellent.And the earphones were very comfortable. The kit included eight different sets of silicone earpieces of several sizes and shapes, plus a set of earpieces labeled "Premium Earphone Isolation Tips" made of memory foam. After trying several of them, I found the type that was most comfortable in my ears. If they're inserted properly, they blocked all but the loudest ambient sounds. (I actually missed two phone calls while testing them, and the phone was only twenty feet away.) While using the earphones, the limp flat cable lets you drape the cables over your ears to relieve any tugging on the earphones.There's a nice semi-hard pocket-size case for carrying everything, including the spare earpieces. Another thoughtful touch is the airplane adapter for aircraft that still use a double plug.The bottom line: I've tried earphones costing much more than the Brainwavz S1, but none have sounded any better or were more comfortable to wear.A product sample was provided by the manufacturer for review purposes.

reviewText: I was pleasantly surprised. The pictures on Amazon, the description on Amazon, the box it came in, and the guide book in the box all say that it has 2 USB 3.0 (SuperSpeed) and 1 USB 2.0 (high-speed) ports. In fact, the actual device itself has 3 USB 3.0 ports (blue). For a minute, I thought that they just soldered in the wrong connector. However, the marking above all 3 ports say SS (USB 3.0 / SuperSpeed).Here is a Crystal Disk Mark measurement on the 3rd port (which was expected to be USB 2.0) and a Patriot Xpress 32GB USB 3.0 drive:-----------------------------------------------------------------------CrystalDiskMark 3.0.2 x64 (C) 2007-2013 hiyohiyoCrystal Dew World : http://crystalmark.info/-----------------------------------------------------------------------* MB/s = 1,000,000 byte/s [SATA/300 = 300,000,000 byte/s]Sequential Read :  183.093 MB/sSequential Write :  49.752 MB/sRandom Read 512KB :  122.308 MB/sRandom Write 512KB :  0.938 MB/sRandom Read 4KB (QD=1) :  7.160 MB/s [  1748.1 IOPS]Random Write 4KB (QD=1) :  0.106 MB/s [  25.9 IOPS]Random Read 4KB (QD=32) :  7.120 MB/s [  1738.2 IOPS]Random Write 4KB (QD=32) :  0.171 MB/s [  41.7 IOPS]Test : 1000 MB [I: 20.7% (6.0/29.0 GB)] (x5)Date : 2013/08/24 0:09:10OS : Windows 7 Ultimate Edition SP1 [6.1 Build 7601] (x64)Here's the same test on port 1 (expected to be USB 3.0):-----------------------------------------------------------------------CrystalDiskMark 3.0.2 x64 (C) 2007-2013 hiyohiyoCrystal Dew World : http://crystalmark.info/-----------------------------------------------------------------------* MB/s = 1,000,000 byte/s [SATA/300 = 300,000,000 byte/s]Sequential Read :  179.351 MB/sSequential Write :  49.861 MB/sRandom Read 512KB :  122.090 MB/sRandom Write 512KB :  0.931 MB/sRandom Read 4KB (QD=1) :  7.267 MB/s [  1774.2 IOPS]Random Write 4KB (QD=1) :  0.154 MB/s [  37.6 IOPS]Random Read 4KB (QD=32) :  6.669 MB/s [  1628.3 IOPS]Random Write 4KB (QD=32) :  0.153 MB/s [  37.3 IOPS]Test : 1000 MB [I: 20.7% (6.0/29.0 GB)] (x5)Date : 2013/08/24 0:22:28OS : Windows 7 Ultimate Edition SP1 [6.1 Build 7601] (x64)What's cool is that this does not seem to be just a dumb physical connector for USB ports, but rather it is an actual USB 3.0 hub.PS. reviewText: I had one pair break after a few months use, so far the next pair have been holding up okay. They sound good but I am not an audiophile. When used for calls clarity was generally quite good and people generally didn't know I was on a Bluetooth headset. I have some concerns about durability after the first pair died so quickly. The headphones generally linked reliably with a Galaxy Nexus and Motorola Triumph. I didn't track battery life too closely but it seemed about in line with the specs. Any questions just ask.
summary: Okay headphones but don't pay too much for them.
